WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.560
[Amit Varma]: When I think about the battle for India's independence, I have to sometimes remind myself

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:13.440
[Amit Varma]: of the shifting meaning of both those words.

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:18.000
[Amit Varma]: For much of our freedom struggle, the word India would have had a shifting, nebulous

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:23.280
[Amit Varma]: meaning without the firm shape of the nation-state that we know by that name today.

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:26.480
[Amit Varma]: And equally, what was independence?

00:00:26.480 --> 00:00:30.720
[Amit Varma]: Our early freedom fighters cared about the well-being of our people and negotiated for

00:00:30.720 --> 00:00:37.920
[Amit Varma]: greater rights, but independence, in the specific shades of meaning of 1947, took shape pretty

00:00:37.920 --> 00:00:39.320
[Amit Varma]: late in the game.

00:00:39.320 --> 00:00:44.420
[Amit Varma]: This is especially so when I think of our 19th century leaders who had the harsh reality

00:00:44.420 --> 00:00:48.720
[Amit Varma]: of the British Empire to work with, a reality they could not wish away.

00:00:48.720 --> 00:01:09.280
[Unknown]: When Dadabhai Naoroji fought for his fellow Indians, what exactly was he fighting for?

00:01:09.280 --> 00:01:10.960
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen.

00:01:10.960 --> 00:01:15.680
[Amit Varma]: Today's episode is about Dadabhai Naoroji, known in our popular culture as a grand old

00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:20.920
[Amit Varma]: man of India, a man who Mohandas Gandhi once called father of the nation.

00:01:20.920 --> 00:01:26.480
[Amit Varma]: Naoroji was an inspiration not just for Gandhi, but an entire generation of our freedom fighters

00:01:26.480 --> 00:01:31.300
[Amit Varma]: and he epitomized what is known as the moderate school within the Congress Party.

00:01:31.300 --> 00:01:36.200
[Amit Varma]: He wanted peaceful change from within the system, so much so that he became the first

00:01:36.200 --> 00:01:41.360
[Amit Varma]: Indian to win election into the British Parliament so that he could push for change from within.

00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:47.000
[Amit Varma]: He was 67 years old at the time, with a lifetime of activism behind him, and in his last years,

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:51.840
[Amit Varma]: having failed in his moderate ways, he turned towards the so-called extremist wing of the

00:01:51.840 --> 00:01:57.440
[Amit Varma]: Congress Party, men like Bal Gangadhar Tilak, and gave them reason to be inspired.

00:01:57.440 --> 00:02:03.120
[Amit Varma]: Dadabhai Naoroji lived into his 90s, and when a man spent so many decades in public life,

00:02:03.120 --> 00:02:07.480
[Amit Varma]: beginning with fighting for the education of girls and ending with a battle against

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:12.760
[Amit Varma]: the empire, it's hard to build a simple narrative around him. Like so many other great figures

00:02:12.760 --> 00:02:16.960
[Amit Varma]: in our freedom struggle, Naoroji contained multitudes.

00:02:16.960 --> 00:02:22.240
[Amit Varma]: My guest today on the show is Dinyar Patel, whose outstanding biography of Naoroji, simply

00:02:22.240 --> 00:02:28.400
[Amit Varma]: titled Naoroji, Pioneer of Indian Nationalism, is on the stands now. It's a rich and nuanced

00:02:28.400 --> 00:02:33.320
[Amit Varma]: look at Naoroji's life, not just giving a sense of the interior life of this complex

00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:39.680
[Amit Varma]: man, but also painting a vivid picture of Indian society and British politics. I had

00:02:39.680 --> 00:02:44.360
[Amit Varma]: been hearing rave reviews of Dinyar's book for a while now, and I was delighted to get

00:02:44.360 --> 00:02:50.600
[Amit Varma]: him onto the show. Before we begin our conversation though, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:50.600 --> 00:02:55.480
[Amit Varma]: Are you one of those people who not only loves to read, but also wants to write better? If

00:02:55.480 --> 00:02:59.520
[Amit Varma]: so, I have something for you. Since April this year, I've been teaching an online course

00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:04.880
[Amit Varma]: called The Art of Clear Writing, four webinars spread out over four Saturdays, in which I

00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:09.520
[Amit Varma]: share whatever I've learned about the craft and practice of writing over 25 years as a

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:14.920
[Amit Varma]: professional writer. The course also contains many writing exercises, discussions on email

00:03:14.920 --> 00:03:21.120
[Amit Varma]: and WhatsApp, and much interactivity. It costs rupees 10,000 or $150. You can check out the

00:03:21.120 --> 00:03:26.840
[Amit Varma]: details at indiankar.com slash clear writing. This link will be in the show notes. If you

00:03:26.840 --> 00:03:30.600
[Amit Varma]: want to bridge the gap between the thoughts in your head and the words on the page, then

00:03:30.600 --> 00:03:36.800
[Amit Varma]: the art of clear writing might be just what you need. September batches begin on Saturday,

00:03:36.800 --> 00:03:42.680
[Amit Varma]: September 5th. So hurry and register before then, indianuncut.com slash clear writing.

00:03:42.680 --> 00:03:47.280
[Amit Varma]: Dinyar, welcome to the scene and the unseen. Thank you. It's great to be here.

00:03:47.280 --> 00:03:52.480
[Amit Varma]: Dinyar, I loved reading your book on Dadabhai Naoroji, especially because despite my deep

00:03:52.480 --> 00:03:56.200
[Amit Varma]: interest in Indian history, I hadn't really read much about him. You know, he was a peripheral

00:03:56.200 --> 00:04:00.640
[Amit Varma]: figure in all the other books I'd read on Gokhale and the 19th century freedom struggle

00:04:00.640 --> 00:04:05.320
[Amit Varma]: and so on. And part of the reason, of course, is that your book is really the first comprehensive

00:04:05.320 --> 00:04:09.880
[Amit Varma]: biography out there. But before we get started on the book, which, you know, had so many

00:04:09.880 --> 00:04:14.200
[Amit Varma]: TIL moments for me, and I enjoyed reading so thoroughly, I'd like to know a little bit

00:04:14.200 --> 00:04:19.960
[Amit Varma]: about yourself, you know, what has your journey been like, not just your, you know, bare bones

00:04:19.960 --> 00:04:24.560
[Amit Varma]: career or academic journey to getting a PhD in history and at Harvard and writing the

00:04:24.560 --> 00:04:29.920
[Amit Varma]: book and so on. But in general, your intellectual history, who are the sort of thinkers who

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:34.280
[Amit Varma]: influenced you? Were there books that made a big difference to your life? What drew you

00:04:34.280 --> 00:04:36.600
[Amit Varma]: to history? What drew you to Dadabhai?

00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:42.200
[Guest]: Yeah, so I was born and raised in the US, actually, I was born in Houston, and I grew

00:04:42.200 --> 00:04:47.880
[Guest]: up in a relatively small town in California called Bakersfield, which is unlike most of

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:52.520
[Guest]: California in the sense that it's quite conservative. And, you know, it's the type of place that

00:04:52.520 --> 00:04:58.160
[Guest]: voted for Trump quite solidly in the last election. So keeping in mind where I grew

00:04:58.160 --> 00:05:01.920
[Guest]: up, it's a little bit of an unusual trajectory to first of all, land up in Mumbai and also

00:05:01.920 --> 00:05:06.320
[Guest]: be studying Indian history. But I think there were a few things again, growing up that kind

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:11.400
[Guest]: of pointed me in this direction, studying kind of the world around you. When at least

00:05:11.400 --> 00:05:15.800
[Guest]: I was in school, again, obviously, before internet and such, I, you know, while other

00:05:15.800 --> 00:05:20.680
[Guest]: people are reading, you know, teenage novels or whatnot, I would pick up books from a series

00:05:20.680 --> 00:05:25.640
[Guest]: that our library had on countries around the world. And I just got very interested in geography,

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:30.600
[Guest]: you know, in the US, at least there's a geography B that takes place. So I used to take part

00:05:30.600 --> 00:05:35.080
[Guest]: in that every year. And so I just, you know, I think also just growing up in a relatively

00:05:35.080 --> 00:05:40.160
[Guest]: small town, you naturally become much more interested in the world around you. And, you

00:05:40.160 --> 00:05:44.280
[Guest]: know, the little bit of experience I had traveling before college kind of solidified that experience.

00:05:44.280 --> 00:05:50.000
[Guest]: I, you know, I remember going with my mother to visit relatives in Calcutta when I was

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:53.800
[Guest]: about 10 years old. And that was kind of the first trip at least to India, which I really

00:05:53.800 --> 00:05:56.880
[Guest]: remembered and kind of left an impression on me and also traveling through different

00:05:56.880 --> 00:06:00.520
[Guest]: parts of Asia on the way to get there between Los Angeles and Calcutta, through Bangkok

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:06.860
[Guest]: and Tokyo. And so once I got to college, at least, you know, I was deciding between two

00:06:06.860 --> 00:06:10.280
[Guest]: different trajectories. I've, I've always been quite interested in architecture and

00:06:10.280 --> 00:06:13.640
[Guest]: urban planning. And still, to this day, I kind of wonder if maybe I should have done

00:06:13.640 --> 00:06:18.080
[Guest]: that instead. But the other trajectory was doing something with international relations

00:06:18.080 --> 00:06:25.280
[Guest]: or history. And so in college, I went to college in Stanford, I started taking a lot of IR,

00:06:25.280 --> 00:06:29.480
[Guest]: international relations courses and history courses, and eventually studied abroad or

00:06:29.480 --> 00:06:33.640
[Guest]: worked abroad for the equivalent of about one and a half years. And that really was

00:06:33.640 --> 00:06:38.600
[Guest]: a very formative experience for me. I mean, just kind of living outside of one's comfort

00:06:38.600 --> 00:06:42.400
[Guest]: zone. And, you know, I studied in China for a long time. Actually, I learned Chinese in

00:06:42.400 --> 00:06:46.640
[Guest]: college and eventually gave it up once I realized that I just could not, you know, I just could

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:51.320
[Guest]: not do the language. It's, it's a very complex process. But nevertheless, that allowed me

00:06:51.320 --> 00:06:56.680
[Guest]: the opportunity to live in China for a few months in, I think, the year 2002. So a fascinating

00:06:56.680 --> 00:07:00.600
[Guest]: time to be there. I just do with all the breakneck change. I got to see the Three Gorges Dam

00:07:00.600 --> 00:07:05.400
[Guest]: being under construction, go to parts of China that were just opening up to kind of foreign,

00:07:05.400 --> 00:07:09.960
[Guest]: foreign visitors and, you know, signs of economic development around you. And slowly, I got

00:07:09.960 --> 00:07:14.800
[Guest]: drawn more and more towards Indian history in college. And I worked for a few years after

00:07:14.800 --> 00:07:20.680
[Guest]: college and while working, I decided I wanted to do a PhD, but in history, in Indian history

00:07:20.680 --> 00:07:27.080
[Guest]: specifically. But I did not anticipate becoming an academic after doing a PhD. So even when

00:07:27.080 --> 00:07:31.560
[Guest]: I was admitted to my program in Harvard, I told my advisor, look, you know, I probably

00:07:31.560 --> 00:07:36.640
[Guest]: won't become an academic historian after this. I'll probably go into more of a policy world

00:07:36.640 --> 00:07:42.000
[Guest]: type job. And I was looking at programs at MIT, for example, that had programs on on

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:47.760
[Guest]: IR and such. And as happens inevitably, I guess, when you're on a PhD program, you get

00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:51.800
[Guest]: sucked into it. So you don't really have a choice. So, you know, here I am so many years

00:07:51.800 --> 00:07:58.960
[Guest]: afterwards in an academic career. And when I began my academic career, at least in Harvard,

00:07:58.960 --> 00:08:04.520
[Guest]: when I started my PhD, you know, I was very struck by certain things about the discipline

00:08:04.520 --> 00:08:09.560
[Guest]: of Indian history. I mean, when you when you study 19th and 20th century history in India,

00:08:09.560 --> 00:08:15.040
[Guest]: you notice that there's a great deal of focus on certain things, and the rest is oftentimes

00:08:15.040 --> 00:08:21.360
[Guest]: just a blank slate. So there's a great deal of work on Bengal, specifically in the 19th

00:08:21.360 --> 00:08:27.360
[Guest]: century. You have the subaltern studies perspective on kind of this bottom up approach of history.

00:08:27.360 --> 00:08:32.640
[Guest]: You know, you have a great deal of writing on a few characters. But again, you know,

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:38.200
[Guest]: there was hardly anything on on on anyone else. So this struck me, especially for early

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:43.600
[Guest]: Indian nationalist leaders. I mean, where were good up to date books and writings on

00:08:43.600 --> 00:08:48.400
[Guest]: figures like Naoroji, or Gokhale, or Ranade, or those other characters, or even later on?

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:54.720
[Guest]: I mean, people like Patel, or Azad, or others, where was that scholarship? And so I got attracted

00:08:54.720 --> 00:08:59.840
[Guest]: to writing something on Naoroji for partly that reason. And the other reason was, I always

00:08:59.840 --> 00:09:05.920
[Guest]: had a long standing interest in Parsi history. I'm a Parsi myself. And so, you know, a PhD

00:09:05.920 --> 00:09:09.440
[Guest]: was a good excuse to kind of find out more about, you know, your community and your family.

00:09:09.440 --> 00:09:13.320
[Guest]: And Naoroji kind of fit the bill. I mean, since he was a Parsi leader, in addition to

00:09:13.320 --> 00:09:19.160
[Guest]: being a nationalist, he was kind of a natural choice for investigating and researching.

00:09:19.160 --> 00:09:24.080
[Guest]: But you know, again, when you when you are in a PhD program in the US in history, and

00:09:24.080 --> 00:09:29.560
[Guest]: you propose to write on someone like Naoroji, you oftentimes will get a lot of stares, or

00:09:29.560 --> 00:09:33.880
[Guest]: people ask you, what are you doing? Because at least 10 years ago, that was not the type

00:09:33.880 --> 00:09:39.640
[Guest]: of PhD dissertation people expected you to do, you're supposed to do something kind of,

00:09:39.640 --> 00:09:44.800
[Guest]: I guess, you know, to use a word more fashionable, more in keeping with some of the political

00:09:44.800 --> 00:09:49.080
[Guest]: orientations of the field, maybe something a bit more narrow, definitely not something

00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:54.520
[Guest]: on a political elite. So I definitely got a lot of question marks from people, why are

00:09:54.520 --> 00:10:00.280
[Guest]: you doing this? Why are you researching this boring elite? You know, who has very little

00:10:00.280 --> 00:10:04.200
[Guest]: to do with where the rest of the field is going. And I was very lucky, at least in the

00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:09.080
[Guest]: sense that my advisor was very supportive, first of all, and I got to meet other people

00:10:09.080 --> 00:10:15.120
[Guest]: who were, you know, again, slowly changing the parameters of the field. So I met Ramchandra

00:10:15.120 --> 00:10:20.440
[Guest]: Guha, when I was probably in my third or fourth year, I think, was, I think, third year of

00:10:20.440 --> 00:10:24.360
[Guest]: my PhD program. And again, I found someone who was extremely supportive, and who has

00:10:24.360 --> 00:10:29.200
[Guest]: supported me ever since then, and has, again, really helped shape the direction in history

00:10:29.200 --> 00:10:35.800
[Guest]: where now we are taking biographies more seriously. So I was very fortunate to have that particular

00:10:35.800 --> 00:10:39.520
[Guest]: source of help. And, you know, through Ram and through others, I've met so many others

00:10:39.520 --> 00:10:43.520
[Guest]: who again, are kind of pushing the boundaries and helping diversify the field of history

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:48.320
[Guest]: beyond kind of the ideological frames that it's been, you know, oftentimes kind of channeled

00:10:48.320 --> 00:10:49.800
[Amit Varma]: in over the past few decades.

00:10:49.800 --> 00:10:53.900
[Amit Varma]: In fact, that that's something that, you know, non historians don't often realize looking

00:10:53.900 --> 00:10:58.940
[Amit Varma]: from the outside in, that so much of history writing is driven by ideology, like you pointed

00:10:58.940 --> 00:11:04.240
[Amit Varma]: out that it became unfashionable at one point to, you know, do biographies to focus on the

00:11:04.240 --> 00:11:10.360
[Amit Varma]: lives of men, especially elite men, as Naoroji obviously was, and you instead want to, you

00:11:10.360 --> 00:11:15.000
[Amit Varma]: know, follow other set narratives, and, you know, look at bottom up currents of history

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:20.920
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. And so is that something that was a strain to fight against in the

00:11:20.920 --> 00:11:25.720
[Amit Varma]: academy? Or did you find that meeting professional historians who don't take that approach, like

00:11:25.720 --> 00:11:29.880
[Amit Varma]: Ram, for example, is something that helped you kind of work past that? And what do you

00:11:29.880 --> 00:11:35.600
[Amit Varma]: feel about that? Is that a problem? Does it color the way we view history or write history?

00:11:35.600 --> 00:11:40.000
[Guest]: It definitely is a problem. I mean, now, I think that we're seeing a bit more of a diversity

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:44.400
[Guest]: in history. But I mean, when we think of the current political moment we're in right now,

00:11:44.400 --> 00:11:49.560
[Guest]: I mean, obviously, politics and the way history has been politicized, if you think of, you

00:11:49.560 --> 00:11:54.040
[Guest]: know, again, the whole principle of action and reaction, I mean, you can understand why

00:11:54.040 --> 00:11:58.680
[Guest]: we're in a particular moment right now when history has been so deeply colored by political

00:11:58.680 --> 00:12:04.160
[Guest]: perspectives from, you know, the other side, from the left side. So, you know, I mean,

00:12:04.160 --> 00:12:08.160
[Guest]: when we have these particular narrow perspectives for studying history, and, you know, India

00:12:08.160 --> 00:12:12.500
[Guest]: is no different in many cases from other parts of the world, which have had these ideological

00:12:12.500 --> 00:12:16.760
[Guest]: straitjackets, you know, it has a knockoff effect. And yes, it was difficult a little

00:12:16.760 --> 00:12:22.400
[Guest]: bit, you know, while writing and researching the PhD to kind of justify my project. But

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:28.720
[Guest]: with the help of people like Ram and others, and, you know, you meet people along the way

00:12:28.720 --> 00:12:33.680
[Guest]: who kind of, you know, take on a supportive role. And I think as I started to write a

00:12:33.680 --> 00:12:39.360
[Guest]: bit more about what I was finding, you know, I was looking at a series of papers in the

00:12:39.360 --> 00:12:43.800
[Guest]: National Archives in Delhi, which really had not been looked at by more than three or four

00:12:43.800 --> 00:12:49.680
[Guest]: historians ever, since Naroji passed away, you know, those tons of interesting new material

00:12:49.680 --> 00:12:55.560
[Guest]: that, you know, one finds in such a collection. And once you start writing about that, people

00:12:55.560 --> 00:13:00.880
[Guest]: tend to kind of latch on and realize that what, you know, what you're going after. So,

00:13:00.880 --> 00:13:05.040
[Guest]: even though I've always been very skeptical about theory, I've never really enjoyed it,

00:13:05.040 --> 00:13:09.560
[Guest]: I found it very frustrating to read in graduate school. And, you know, maybe I wasn't a very

00:13:09.560 --> 00:13:14.760
[Guest]: popular grad student on account of that. I do think that I do believe very, very strongly

00:13:14.760 --> 00:13:21.440
[Guest]: in kind of these strongly empirical groundings and methods that, you know, historians have

00:13:21.440 --> 00:13:26.120
[Guest]: used. And, you know, the really good historians have, you know, known to make sure to read

00:13:26.120 --> 00:13:30.360
[Guest]: everything that's out there, or, you know, as much as you possibly can. And that really,

00:13:30.360 --> 00:13:36.080
[Guest]: you know, the example that I had from people like Ram or others, like the senior Indian

00:13:36.080 --> 00:13:41.040
[Guest]: professor SR Mehrotra, really made a very big difference in kind of providing a source

00:13:41.040 --> 00:13:45.680
[Amit Varma]: of encouragement. And one of the things that I really liked about your book is, you know,

00:13:45.680 --> 00:13:49.160
[Amit Varma]: when I get historians on the show, and if you're talking about the 17th century, or

00:13:49.160 --> 00:13:54.080
[Amit Varma]: the 16th century, or whatever century, which is not the current time, you know, I'll often

00:13:54.080 --> 00:13:58.400
[Amit Varma]: ask things like, what did they eat in those days? You know, what was their day like, give

00:13:58.400 --> 00:14:02.480
[Amit Varma]: me a sense of the texture of their day and all of that. And they're kind of blank about

00:14:02.480 --> 00:14:06.160
[Amit Varma]: that. And one of the things I enjoyed about your book is, of course, you said that there

00:14:06.160 --> 00:14:11.200
[Amit Varma]: are a lot of papers which cover especially his London years, right down to, you know,

00:14:11.200 --> 00:14:15.600
[Amit Varma]: little quotidian bills and small memos and all of that. But from all of that, you could

00:14:15.600 --> 00:14:20.800
[Amit Varma]: actually also, you know, draw a picture for the reader of the kind of clothes he wore,

00:14:20.800 --> 00:14:25.800
[Amit Varma]: how that changed depending on the occasion and the thinking behind it, the kind of food

00:14:25.800 --> 00:14:30.000
[Amit Varma]: he ate, how, I mean, I was fascinated by, you know, he wakes up, he doesn't have breakfast,

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:34.440
[Amit Varma]: he has three raw eggs for lunch while standing and all of that. And, and those I thought

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:39.080
[Amit Varma]: were excellent details, which other historians may have just chosen to ignore because they're

00:14:39.080 --> 00:14:44.520
[Amit Varma]: so mundane and banal that you, but I'm glad that you put them in. So tell me a little

00:14:44.520 --> 00:14:49.360
[Amit Varma]: bit about your process. And that's really a two part question. One is the process for

00:14:49.360 --> 00:14:53.880
[Amit Varma]: the project. How do you approach the project? Where are the papers located? What kind of

00:14:53.880 --> 00:14:58.000
[Amit Varma]: condition are they in? What do you do? Do you, you know, like, if they're at an archive,

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:01.680
[Amit Varma]: you go, you take them out, you photograph them all? How do you handle them? How are

00:15:01.680 --> 00:15:08.520
[Amit Varma]: they kept? And then secondly, just the mental process of then working on the narrative where

00:15:08.520 --> 00:15:14.360
[Amit Varma]: obviously you go in knowing a lot of facts about Naoroji, which are in the popular domain.

00:15:14.360 --> 00:15:18.680
[Amit Varma]: But you know, do you kind of have to ignore them and pretend that you have a blank slate

00:15:18.680 --> 00:15:23.120
[Amit Varma]: in your mind and you're discovering everything all over again, given that, you know, we all

00:15:23.120 --> 00:15:27.680
[Amit Varma]: suffer from the hindsight bias, we know everything that has happened intimately, we feel it was

00:15:27.680 --> 00:15:33.840
[Amit Varma]: inevitable. And your book doesn't seem to sort of make that mistake at all, you know,

00:15:33.840 --> 00:15:38.360
[Amit Varma]: reflected, for example, in the way that someone like Mahatma Gandhi plays such a small peripheral

00:15:38.360 --> 00:15:43.080
[Amit Varma]: part in it, though I can easily imagine other approaches to the history making, you know,

00:15:43.080 --> 00:15:48.100
[Amit Varma]: because of what he went on to become, giving more importance to his connection with Naoroji,

00:15:48.100 --> 00:15:53.720
[Amit Varma]: but he was a peripheral figure for India and Naoroji and that kind of comes across. So

00:15:53.720 --> 00:15:58.000
[Amit Varma]: yeah, so these two, you know, one is, you know, what is the process in terms of physically

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:02.960
[Amit Varma]: what do you have to do? How long did it take you? What is the work like? Do you get disheartened?

00:16:02.960 --> 00:16:05.640
[Amit Varma]: And then mentally, how do you approach it?

00:16:05.640 --> 00:16:10.120
[Guest]: So if you are studying Indian history in the 19th or the 20th century, and to a certain

00:16:10.120 --> 00:16:15.400
[Guest]: degree, the 18th century, chances are you're going to be in one of two or three places,

00:16:15.400 --> 00:16:19.320
[Guest]: including the National Archives of India or Teen Murthy, the Nehru Memorial Museum and

00:16:19.320 --> 00:16:25.120
[Guest]: Library in Delhi. And I was in both places because Naoroji's papers, so when Naoroji

00:16:25.120 --> 00:16:33.280
[Guest]: died, there was a collection of probably maybe 50,000 documents in Naoroji's collection.

00:16:33.280 --> 00:16:37.520
[Guest]: And there's a very kind of long history of what happens to those papers after he dies.

00:16:37.520 --> 00:16:42.500
[Guest]: They're kept in Bombay and they rot away and every 10 years or so someone will fish them

00:16:42.500 --> 00:16:47.940
[Guest]: out and see what's there and make a catalog. And there's a attempt to catalog and publish

00:16:47.940 --> 00:16:53.260
[Guest]: the papers, but it ultimately falls through. Eventually, they move to Pune and there's

00:16:53.260 --> 00:16:58.960
[Guest]: a scholar there called R. P. Patwardhan who spends, he's told by someone called R. P.

00:16:58.960 --> 00:17:03.460
[Guest]: Masani, who was Naoroji's first biography. He was told by Masani that, look, it'll take

00:17:03.460 --> 00:17:08.960
[Guest]: you a few years, just go through the papers, show me, tell me what is good to publish in

00:17:08.960 --> 00:17:14.440
[Guest]: a selected volume. And it took the rest of R. P. Patwardhan's life, it took him 20 odd

00:17:14.440 --> 00:17:20.560
[Guest]: years to go through the papers and cull out collections for publication. And eventually

00:17:20.560 --> 00:17:26.320
[Guest]: from Patwardhan's residence, they get transported to the National Archives in Delhi in the 1960s.

00:17:26.320 --> 00:17:31.440
[Guest]: And by this point in time, what had originally been a collection of about 50,000 documents

00:17:31.440 --> 00:17:37.960
[Guest]: when Naoroji died, had whittled down to maybe around 40 to 30,000 documents. And by the

00:17:37.960 --> 00:17:44.120
[Guest]: time I got there, probably 30,000, you know, maybe a little bit more. So what we have over

00:17:44.120 --> 00:17:51.760
[Guest]: here is a very clear track record of loss, which is true across the board in Indian archives

00:17:51.760 --> 00:17:57.600
[Guest]: and records. Because of the climate, because of bad record keeping, because of, you know,

00:17:57.600 --> 00:18:02.400
[Guest]: people just throwing away their collections, a lot of stuff gets lost. And Naoroji is actually

00:18:02.400 --> 00:18:07.800
[Guest]: one of the best cases of preservation that we have, because at least here the collection

00:18:07.800 --> 00:18:12.920
[Guest]: is in, you know, the order of tens of thousands, right? If you look at someone like Ranade,

00:18:12.920 --> 00:18:18.800
[Guest]: we have a handful of his letters, right? If you look at W.C. Banerjee, the first president

00:18:18.800 --> 00:18:23.960
[Guest]: of the Congress, we have basically nothing. I mean, someone had his letters up until 1940,

00:18:23.960 --> 00:18:28.240
[Guest]: published a few in a not terribly good book, and that's it. We never hear anything after

00:18:28.240 --> 00:18:33.880
[Guest]: that about what happened. So India's had a very shoddy track record of archival preservation.

00:18:33.880 --> 00:18:38.040
[Guest]: And at least with the Naoroji papers, that record was much better. So a lot had been

00:18:38.040 --> 00:18:43.600
[Guest]: lost, yes, but the vast majority had been preserved. It was not in a very good state

00:18:43.600 --> 00:18:48.720
[Guest]: of preservation. So when I got to the National Archives, and I think that was the year 2011

00:18:48.720 --> 00:18:54.040
[Guest]: to start my research, you know, I was taken to a room and said, here's the catalogue,

00:18:54.040 --> 00:18:58.760
[Guest]: you know, tell me what you want, basically. So, you know, only when I got to the archives

00:18:58.760 --> 00:19:03.000
[Guest]: did I discover that there are these 30,000 documents, right? And, you know, I thought

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:06.640
[Guest]: I might be in the National Archives for a few months. I ended up being there for about

00:19:06.640 --> 00:19:09.840
[Guest]: two years, and I only got through about half of the collection. So there's another half

00:19:09.840 --> 00:19:14.360
[Guest]: that I haven't even seen. But, I mean, one of the nice things about doing archival work

00:19:14.360 --> 00:19:19.520
[Guest]: in India, which you do not get at, say, like a British library or archives in America,

00:19:19.520 --> 00:19:23.920
[Guest]: is that if you show to the archivists that you're there for the long run, and, you know,

00:19:23.920 --> 00:19:29.200
[Guest]: you are, you know, an honest and committed scholar, they give you certain privileges

00:19:29.200 --> 00:19:34.120
[Guest]: that you would not otherwise enjoy in other facilities. So I started working very closely

00:19:34.120 --> 00:19:37.760
[Guest]: with some of the archivists and saying, you know, I found this document, can you make

00:19:37.760 --> 00:19:41.800
[Guest]: sure it gets preserved properly, because otherwise it will fall apart. And over time, at least

00:19:41.800 --> 00:19:45.760
[Guest]: I was lucky enough to build up a relationship of trust with them that they allowed me to

00:19:45.760 --> 00:19:49.480
[Guest]: actually go into the back room and get material myself. So I didn't have to worry for, you

00:19:49.480 --> 00:19:52.640
[Guest]: know, about waiting for someone to deliver the papers for me, I could go in the back

00:19:52.640 --> 00:19:56.840
[Guest]: and get the material myself. And that definitely helped me in the sense of understanding what

00:19:56.840 --> 00:20:02.040
[Guest]: the papers were like, what it's like to go through someone's life collection and how

00:20:02.040 --> 00:20:06.080
[Guest]: it's organized, and where there are discrepancies and where there's too much material where

00:20:06.080 --> 00:20:10.440
[Guest]: there's too little material. So I mean, to answer your question, at least of methodology,

00:20:10.440 --> 00:20:15.080
[Guest]: I, you know, I think the author Robert Carroll was onto something when he said, you know,

00:20:15.080 --> 00:20:19.480
[Guest]: you have to go through everything, you have to turn every page. And of course, you know,

00:20:19.480 --> 00:20:22.600
[Guest]: in a PhD program, you don't necessarily have that luxury, because you eventually have to

00:20:22.600 --> 00:20:26.840
[Guest]: graduate. And I definitely took much longer than I should have, I took eight years, and,

00:20:26.840 --> 00:20:31.080
[Guest]: you know, I should not have taken that long. But I tried to get as close to that as possible.

00:20:31.080 --> 00:20:35.640
[Guest]: And I think in the ultimate end, it was very helpful. I mean, perhaps 80% of the material

00:20:35.640 --> 00:20:41.240
[Guest]: I collected, I never used in the book. But it helped me kind of create an overall structure

00:20:41.240 --> 00:20:45.280
[Guest]: of where this individual's life was going. And it ultimately will help me as I write

00:20:45.280 --> 00:20:47.200
[Guest]: my next books as well.

00:20:47.200 --> 00:20:52.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and Caro, of course, has taken more than 40 years over his Lyndon Johnson biography,

00:20:52.120 --> 00:20:57.880
[Amit Varma]: which I think the sixth volume will be out sooner. So that was so I'm glad you didn't

00:20:57.880 --> 00:21:03.600
[Amit Varma]: follow his example that seriously. And the second part of the question, then, you know,

00:21:03.600 --> 00:21:07.160
[Amit Varma]: when you begin, how do you sort of approach it? Do you have a preset narrative in your

00:21:07.160 --> 00:21:12.640
[Amit Varma]: mind that kind of changes as you go along? Or do you try to just sort of put yourself

00:21:12.640 --> 00:21:18.320
[Amit Varma]: in the moment that a document is from and try to figure it out from there? You know,

00:21:18.320 --> 00:21:20.840
[Amit Varma]: how did the book mutate and take shape in your head?

00:21:20.840 --> 00:21:27.240
[Guest]: Yeah, so when I started the project, you know, I read the little material on Naroji that

00:21:27.240 --> 00:21:32.120
[Guest]: was around beforehand. I mean, the first biography, as I mentioned, for Naroji was written by

00:21:32.120 --> 00:21:38.280
[Guest]: Rustom Masani, R.P. Masani. And it was written in 1939. And it's a great book in the sense

00:21:38.280 --> 00:21:42.360
[Guest]: that it's far more comprehensive than mine in terms of, you know, wanting to know about

00:21:42.360 --> 00:21:47.960
[Guest]: Naroji's life. It's 400 odd pages. He had access to material that was gone and lost

00:21:47.960 --> 00:21:53.280
[Guest]: by the time I had the chance to look at the material. But it is ultimately colored by

00:21:53.280 --> 00:21:59.200
[Guest]: the politics of the time. I mean, Masani was a moderate, and he was writing in a way to

00:21:59.200 --> 00:22:04.520
[Guest]: try to show Naroji as kind of a moderate, loyalist leader, in that sense, somewhat separate

00:22:04.520 --> 00:22:10.240
[Guest]: from Gandhi. And he tried to hold up Naroji as a model of what nationalism was like before

00:22:10.240 --> 00:22:15.440
[Guest]: it took this kind of break from, you know, some sense of British loyalism, you know,

00:22:15.440 --> 00:22:19.520
[Guest]: this difference that took place after the Puran Swaraj Declaration was made by the Congress

00:22:19.520 --> 00:22:25.840
[Guest]: in 1929, 1930. And so, you know, I went into the archives with kind of this literature

00:22:25.840 --> 00:22:30.760
[Guest]: showing Naroji as being quite a moderate leader, ultimately a loyalist, not a terribly radical

00:22:30.760 --> 00:22:36.640
[Guest]: leader. And again, I think the most important thing I gained from reading his private correspondence

00:22:36.640 --> 00:22:41.080
[Guest]: was helping me get away from that narrative. I mean, ultimately, yes, Naroji, during the

00:22:41.080 --> 00:22:45.840
[Guest]: course of his life, made several declarations talking about how he was loyal to British

00:22:45.840 --> 00:22:50.960
[Guest]: rule. You know, he was a proud member of the British Empire. But at the same time, he was

00:22:50.960 --> 00:22:55.240
[Guest]: making completely contradictory statements. He was talking about British rule being evil.

00:22:55.240 --> 00:22:58.800
[Guest]: If you read his private correspondence with certain people, he's talking about British

00:22:58.800 --> 00:23:03.160
[Guest]: rule in quite condemnatory terms. I mean, he's talking about how British rule was responsible

00:23:03.160 --> 00:23:07.880
[Guest]: for mass famine, and people were being killed in the millions because of the policies that

00:23:07.880 --> 00:23:14.120
[Guest]: were being pursued or not pursued by the British. So, you know, it kind of evolved, in my sense

00:23:14.120 --> 00:23:18.480
[Guest]: at least, a question of what does it mean to be loyal? So you can say that you are a

00:23:18.480 --> 00:23:24.040
[Guest]: loyal member of, you know, the Empire, you're loyal to the Queen or the King or whatever,

00:23:24.040 --> 00:23:29.200
[Guest]: but what does that mean? And ultimately, you know, I kind of understood Naroji's loyalism

00:23:29.200 --> 00:23:34.440
[Guest]: as a bit of a tactic, and a way to kind of undercut a lot of the elements of, you know,

00:23:34.440 --> 00:23:39.120
[Guest]: nefarious colonial policy. You know, he said, he and other early nationalists kind of built

00:23:39.120 --> 00:23:42.840
[Guest]: up this narrative of British rule should be this, it should be X, right? But in reality,

00:23:42.840 --> 00:23:48.280
[Guest]: we have Y. British rule should be something about equality, democratic rights, some sort

00:23:48.280 --> 00:23:52.080
[Guest]: of progressive impulse. But in reality, you know, what you had in India was this very

00:23:52.080 --> 00:23:58.060
[Guest]: reactionary, undemocratic, fiercely authoritarian rule where, you know, progressive, any sense

00:23:58.060 --> 00:24:03.000
[Guest]: of progressive policy was completely absent, right? I mean, it was very derogatory towards

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:08.080
[Guest]: Indians, it didn't really support education. So, you know, the idea of British rule was

00:24:08.080 --> 00:24:13.040
[Guest]: ultimately, you know, not British rule. It was some kind of idealized conception that

00:24:13.040 --> 00:24:19.000
[Guest]: involved separating yourself 99% from actual British rule. So, in many ways, it was kind

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:24.960
[Guest]: of a tactic, and that helped me kind of separate my particular view on Naroji from, say, what

00:24:24.960 --> 00:24:30.040
[Guest]: Massani or others had written about beforehand. And, you know, this is important, at least

00:24:30.040 --> 00:24:34.920
[Guest]: from the standpoint of writing history. Whenever you investigate an individual, what someone

00:24:34.920 --> 00:24:38.520
[Guest]: writes and publishes in public is obviously very different from what they're saying in

00:24:38.520 --> 00:24:43.000
[Guest]: private or writing in private. And this only really comes across when you're able to do

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:47.520
[Guest]: sustained archival research. I mean, again, not something like what Caro has done. I can't

00:24:47.520 --> 00:24:51.360
[Guest]: afford to take 40 years. But, you know, if you put several months or perhaps years into

00:24:51.360 --> 00:24:56.000
[Guest]: it, you gain a familiarity with someone's life and you're able to discern what the real

00:24:56.000 --> 00:24:57.000
[Guest]: meanings were.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:02.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, one of the things that strikes me, especially about how we view history today,

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:07.440
[Amit Varma]: is that we look for simplistic narratives, and especially we make these harsh binaries.

00:25:07.440 --> 00:25:12.280
[Amit Varma]: While the fact is that someone who's been in public life for decades, as Naroji was,

00:25:12.280 --> 00:25:16.160
[Amit Varma]: will inevitably contain multitudes. And also what seems to happen, and what you've charted

00:25:16.160 --> 00:25:21.520
[Amit Varma]: out very well in your book, is that at different stages of his life, and you, of course, divided

00:25:21.520 --> 00:25:27.400
[Amit Varma]: his career into sort of three broad stages, but at different stages of his life, he's

00:25:27.400 --> 00:25:32.120
[Amit Varma]: responding to incentives. And a lot of the moderating statements come from that, like

00:25:32.120 --> 00:25:36.400
[Amit Varma]: in that initial theoretical phase, where he comes up with a drain theory. And because

00:25:36.400 --> 00:25:41.880
[Amit Varma]: he needs to be taken seriously, he can't take a radical tone. So he's got to sort of be

00:25:41.880 --> 00:25:45.680
[Amit Varma]: moderate there. Similarly, when he's standing for parliament, of course, he's got to gain

00:25:45.680 --> 00:25:50.040
[Amit Varma]: and again, proclaim his loyalty. And once that is done, of course, he's, you know, towards

00:25:50.040 --> 00:25:56.360
[Amit Varma]: the end of his life, he's a little more radicalized. Let's start by sort of talking about, at this

00:25:56.360 --> 00:26:01.920
[Amit Varma]: point, the early phase of his life, which was quite interesting to me, because even

00:26:01.920 --> 00:26:08.000
[Amit Varma]: his early years, like, of course, he leaves Bombay when he's 30, when he goes to London.

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:14.880
[Amit Varma]: But even in that time, he seems to have lived a fairly rich life, been a community leader,

00:26:14.880 --> 00:26:20.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, especially in something like, speaking of feminism, starting girls schools, all of

00:26:20.680 --> 00:26:26.000
[Amit Varma]: that. Tell me a bit about those early days in Bombay and what his background is, like

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:30.520
[Amit Varma]: he is, of course, from this Parsi priestly family, which had once seen much better days,

00:26:30.520 --> 00:26:34.840
[Amit Varma]: but is relatively impoverished when he comes and he's expected to join the priesthood.

00:26:34.840 --> 00:26:39.400
[Amit Varma]: And you've spoken about how, you know, when he's three, his father dies, and that probably

00:26:39.400 --> 00:26:45.320
[Amit Varma]: saves him from a life of priesthood. And even though he does a little bit of early training,

00:26:45.320 --> 00:26:50.360
[Amit Varma]: but otherwise, you know, so tell me a bit about the Bombay of those days and Naoroji

00:26:50.360 --> 00:26:55.400
[Amit Varma]: growing up and what was the sort of environment around him, which shaped him and which shaped

00:26:55.400 --> 00:26:57.800
[Amit Varma]: his thinking about the empire?

00:26:57.800 --> 00:27:03.240
[Guest]: So if we want to talk about Bombay in the early 1800s, we automatically have to think

00:27:03.240 --> 00:27:07.480
[Guest]: about the places where people were coming from, right? I mean, Bombay, as this immigrant

00:27:07.480 --> 00:27:12.880
[Guest]: center was drawing in people from all across Western India, and in Naoroji's case, the

00:27:12.880 --> 00:27:19.240
[Guest]: place his family came from was Navsari and Dharampur. Navsari was a very old Parsi settlement.

00:27:19.240 --> 00:27:25.480
[Guest]: You know, there still is a relatively large Parsi population there. And Naoroji's family

00:27:25.480 --> 00:27:30.080
[Guest]: was from a priestly line. You know, they could actually trace the descent right back to the

00:27:30.080 --> 00:27:37.920
[Guest]: first priest, the first Zoroastrian priest who settled in Navsari. And so, you know,

00:27:37.920 --> 00:27:42.160
[Guest]: it's kind of funny, the people in Navsari who still believe that Naoroji was born there.

00:27:42.160 --> 00:27:48.480
[Guest]: And if you go to Navsari today, you will see a Naoroji birthplace. It's a very old house.

00:27:48.480 --> 00:27:52.680
[Guest]: And, you know, ever since the early 1900s, people have believed that Naoroji was born

00:27:52.680 --> 00:27:57.160
[Guest]: there. Even Gandhi thought that Naoroji was born there. And he went and paid a pilgrimage

00:27:57.160 --> 00:28:03.000
[Guest]: to that site in the 1920s during non-cooperation. Naoroji wasn't born there. He was born in

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:10.000
[Guest]: Bombay. And he was born out of this kind of poor migrant perspective. I mean, his parents

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:16.240
[Guest]: had left Gujarat in probably the year 1824, 1823. And at that moment in time, there was

00:28:16.240 --> 00:28:20.200
[Guest]: a famine in parts of Gujarat. So there's a good chance that his family was impelled to

00:28:20.200 --> 00:28:24.400
[Guest]: move because of the real specter of poverty. And that was the same reason that was pushing

00:28:24.400 --> 00:28:32.600
[Guest]: people, Parsis, Gujaratis, you know, Maharashtrians, Konkanis, from all across Western India into

00:28:32.600 --> 00:28:37.480
[Guest]: this new commercial entrepreneur. So Bombay was growing by leaps and bounds. In the year

00:28:37.480 --> 00:28:44.760
[Guest]: that Naoroji is born, 1825, the Maidan, what is now Azad Maidan, was covered with tents

00:28:44.760 --> 00:28:49.200
[Guest]: of people who were living there who had just migrated from famine tracts. So it's a city

00:28:49.200 --> 00:28:55.120
[Guest]: that's growing every day. And you get the sense of a city that's really kind of in formation.

00:28:55.120 --> 00:28:58.920
[Guest]: It was also a very kind of rough and tumble place at this point in time. I mean, this

00:28:58.920 --> 00:29:03.760
[Guest]: is before, you know, the grand colonial buildings that were constructed that we think of when

00:29:03.760 --> 00:29:08.200
[Guest]: we associate that particular era of Bombay. So it was not an easy place to live in. I

00:29:08.200 --> 00:29:14.840
[Guest]: mean, if you read descriptions of Bombay from this era, people talk about wide sewers, you

00:29:14.840 --> 00:29:22.120
[Guest]: know, that basically would lap up on the doorsteps of people. Trash was a huge problem. The water

00:29:22.120 --> 00:29:26.520
[Guest]: that you drank was muddy and there was a good chance that it would kill you. So it was not

00:29:26.520 --> 00:29:31.480
[Guest]: a great place to live in from the standpoint of the vast majority of people. But I think

00:29:31.480 --> 00:29:36.040
[Guest]: that the important thing for Naoroji and many others in his generation who grew up to be

00:29:36.040 --> 00:29:41.160
[Guest]: important political leaders, is that they recognize the power of the diversity of the

00:29:41.160 --> 00:29:45.960
[Guest]: city. I mean, unlike any other city in India at this point in time, you had people coming

00:29:45.960 --> 00:29:50.560
[Guest]: from all walks of life and they were all living right next to each other. So the region of

00:29:50.560 --> 00:29:55.360
[Guest]: Bombay that he grew up in, an area called Khadak, is located right next to an area called

00:29:55.360 --> 00:30:00.960
[Guest]: Israeli Mohalla, which is where, you know, members of the Beni Israeli community lived.

00:30:00.960 --> 00:30:05.680
[Guest]: It's next to a very large Muslim district, today's Bendi Bazaar. And just to the north

00:30:05.680 --> 00:30:13.360
[Guest]: of it, you have very rich Anglo-Indians, Pisces, Jews, British individuals living in places

00:30:13.360 --> 00:30:18.000
[Guest]: like Baikala, which were fashionable in that day. So he got a very strong flavor of kind

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:24.000
[Guest]: of this cosmopolitan diversity. And this played a really important role in his early activities.

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:29.560
[Guest]: I mean, he was admitted into a school at a very young age. And as you mentioned, you

00:30:29.560 --> 00:30:35.160
[Guest]: know, the fact that his father passed away soon probably saved him from a priestly career.

00:30:35.160 --> 00:30:41.240
[Guest]: And he instead goes into a free school that was a quite novel experiment in this era.

00:30:41.240 --> 00:30:47.200
[Guest]: Free schooling was not common anywhere in the world really at this point in time, 1830s.

00:30:47.200 --> 00:30:52.920
[Guest]: And that really commits him to a life of public service because he realizes, at least he says

00:30:52.920 --> 00:30:57.080
[Guest]: so later on when he writes about this later in life, he realized from a very early age

00:30:57.080 --> 00:31:02.440
[Guest]: that he owed something to the general public. They had paid for him getting as good an education

00:31:02.440 --> 00:31:06.640
[Guest]: as you possibly could in Bombay at this time. And he was learning from British teachers.

00:31:06.640 --> 00:31:10.800
[Guest]: He was learning from Indian teachers. He was reading Shakespeare. He was reading, you know,

00:31:10.800 --> 00:31:15.840
[Guest]: the latest science and philosophy coming from Europe. So, you know, he received a very well-rounded

00:31:15.840 --> 00:31:21.080
[Guest]: education and as importantly, it was in the English language. So he grew up speaking English

00:31:21.080 --> 00:31:26.360
[Guest]: fluently and being able to write in English fluently in addition to Gujarati. And he probably

00:31:26.360 --> 00:31:31.520
[Guest]: knew some Hindustani and Marathi as well. So that really set him on kind of this course

00:31:31.520 --> 00:31:36.600
[Guest]: of needing to pursue a public career. And so he attends Elphinstone College. He kind

00:31:36.600 --> 00:31:41.520
[Guest]: of widens his intellectual horizons more at this point in time because the professors

00:31:41.520 --> 00:31:46.320
[Guest]: there are quite progressive in this era. You know, even the British people who are teaching

00:31:46.320 --> 00:31:51.040
[Guest]: are very forward-looking and kind of freely associated with Indians and support their

00:31:51.040 --> 00:31:55.960
[Guest]: reformist efforts. And ultimately, after he leaves college, he decides to join Elphinstone

00:31:55.960 --> 00:32:00.200
[Guest]: as a teacher and he rises through the ranks quite quickly and becomes the first ever Indian

00:32:00.200 --> 00:32:05.280
[Guest]: appointed to the rank of full professor in a colonial college in India. So, you know,

00:32:05.280 --> 00:32:11.040
[Guest]: from this very early age, he is already marked out for success and, you know, kind of he's

00:32:11.040 --> 00:32:15.000
[Guest]: a symbol of change in many ways. I mean, he was this very poor individual who's now at

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:20.520
[Guest]: the very top of Indian society. And this impels him, you know, this whole experience of, you

00:32:20.520 --> 00:32:25.840
[Guest]: know, getting a kind of a very liberal education, feeling responsible to the public, pushes

00:32:25.840 --> 00:32:31.960
[Guest]: him to adopt progressive causes. And one of them, again, was female education. You know,

00:32:31.960 --> 00:32:36.840
[Guest]: in the 1850s, no Indian community had a strong suit with female education, including the

00:32:36.840 --> 00:32:41.720
[Guest]: Pisces. The Pisces were almost as reactionary as any other community in India at this point

00:32:41.720 --> 00:32:46.880
[Guest]: in time. And Naorochi, to his credit, gets a group of fellow Indians, not just Pisces,

00:32:46.880 --> 00:32:53.680
[Guest]: but also Gujaratis and Maharashtrians, also gets them together, forms a network of indigenous

00:32:53.680 --> 00:32:58.400
[Guest]: schools for girls and persists in getting their parents to send girls to schools in

00:32:58.400 --> 00:33:04.280
[Guest]: spite of threats, in spite of, you know, editorials against them, verbal abuse. And what starts

00:33:04.280 --> 00:33:08.840
[Guest]: as a very unpromising venture grows into an experiment where hundreds and hundreds of

00:33:08.840 --> 00:33:14.480
[Guest]: Indian girls are being educated by the mid-1850s. And this is an unqualified success. So he

00:33:14.480 --> 00:33:19.920
[Guest]: really kind of helps turn the table on orthodox thought at this point in time.

00:33:19.920 --> 00:33:24.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I was struck by a couple of strands here. One was his passion for education, not

00:33:24.240 --> 00:33:28.120
[Amit Varma]: just self-education. And you've actually done another really interesting thing that I liked

00:33:28.120 --> 00:33:32.000
[Amit Varma]: in your book, where when I read the biographies of people, I want to know what are the kind

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:36.760
[Amit Varma]: of books that they read. And, you know, you've got a little list of that. And obviously,

00:33:36.760 --> 00:33:42.400
[Amit Varma]: they're all freely available on the internet, because they're, you know, so I kind of looked

00:33:42.400 --> 00:33:46.000
[Amit Varma]: up a couple of them. And it was quite, quite sort of interesting to try and figure out

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:51.000
[Amit Varma]: what those strands might have been. And he takes education so seriously that at one point

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:55.680
[Amit Varma]: towards the end of his life, you quote him as saying, quote, several honors came to me

00:33:55.680 --> 00:34:01.200
[Amit Varma]: during my lifetime, but no other title created in me that sense of pride, which I felt in

00:34:01.200 --> 00:34:05.200
[Amit Varma]: being known as a professor, stop quote. And as you point out, he was, of course, you know,

00:34:05.200 --> 00:34:10.920
[Amit Varma]: the first Indian to be made a full professor, even the sort of the two people he really

00:34:10.920 --> 00:34:16.040
[Amit Varma]: admired, you pointed out at Elphinstone, Bal Gangadhar Shah, Sri Jambekar and Navroji Fardunji

00:34:16.040 --> 00:34:20.000
[Amit Varma]: were assistant professors at the time. So he was sort of the first. The other strand

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:25.520
[Amit Varma]: that struck me and, you know, very often, I think what happens is that when men get

00:34:25.520 --> 00:34:30.880
[Amit Varma]: into women's rights, they get into women's rights, but they get into it looking at women

00:34:30.880 --> 00:34:37.720
[Amit Varma]: as instrumental to the world of men. And Navroji actually went beyond that. So you've got a

00:34:37.720 --> 00:34:43.840
[Amit Varma]: passage here, which I'll quote, quote, like Kaikhoshru Harmasi, Navroji believed that,

00:34:43.840 --> 00:34:49.600
[Amit Varma]: quote, good and educated mothers only will raise good and educated sons, stop quote.

00:34:49.600 --> 00:34:54.080
[Amit Varma]: But he also possessed notably progressive views on female education, arguing that it

00:34:54.080 --> 00:34:58.480
[Amit Varma]: was a fundamental pillar for establishing gender equality. Indians, he argued, would

00:34:58.480 --> 00:35:04.220
[Amit Varma]: one day, quote again, Navroji's words, understand that women had as much right to exercise and

00:35:04.220 --> 00:35:08.920
[Amit Varma]: enjoy all the rights, privileges and duties of this world as man, each working towards

00:35:08.920 --> 00:35:13.560
[Amit Varma]: a common good, stop quote. And this seems remarkably sort of progressive. And it was

00:35:13.560 --> 00:35:17.420
[Amit Varma]: clearly a cause he cared about, because like you said, he started schools for first Parsi

00:35:17.420 --> 00:35:22.600
[Amit Varma]: girls and then Maharashtrian Hindu girls, and then Muslim girls. And it was something

00:35:22.600 --> 00:35:29.880
[Amit Varma]: that he cared deeply about. Also, give me a sense of, you know, he founded many organizations,

00:35:29.880 --> 00:35:34.920
[Amit Varma]: he was part of many organizations, notably, what you call as Young Bombay. Tell me a bit

00:35:34.920 --> 00:35:39.000
[Amit Varma]: about Young Bombay and his other community work. He also founded a Gujarati newspaper

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:45.160
[Amit Varma]: called Rast Guftar, for which he continued sending dispatches even when he was abroad.

00:35:45.160 --> 00:35:49.840
[Amit Varma]: And all of this before he's turned 30, because he leaves Bombay when he's turned 30. So what's

00:35:49.840 --> 00:35:54.640
[Amit Varma]: going on? How is such a young man so incredibly active and already a leader in his community

00:35:54.640 --> 00:35:57.080
[Guest]: at such a young age?

00:35:57.080 --> 00:36:01.200
[Guest]: So what you said about education really being kind of a hallmark of his career, I think

00:36:01.200 --> 00:36:07.920
[Guest]: can be applied to pretty much all the nationalist leaders of this early era, this kind of pre-Gandhian

00:36:07.920 --> 00:36:13.960
[Guest]: era. It's written all throughout the narratives of, you know, anyone, you can pick Ranade,

00:36:13.960 --> 00:36:18.640
[Guest]: Gokhale, all the way down to people who are less known. I mean, you know, recently in

00:36:18.640 --> 00:36:22.840
[Guest]: my research, I've been coming across articles written in Modern Review by a lot of people

00:36:22.840 --> 00:36:27.320
[Guest]: who are not very familiar to us nowadays. And education is always that theme. Education

00:36:27.320 --> 00:36:32.720
[Guest]: is the key for uplifting Indian society. And, you know, I think the reason why education

00:36:32.720 --> 00:36:37.120
[Guest]: was so important for both Naoroji and these other leaders is that there was a general

00:36:37.120 --> 00:36:41.440
[Guest]: understanding that India was at a very low point in its history. Right. I mean, most

00:36:41.440 --> 00:36:44.960
[Guest]: people, of course, would have no point of reference. They would not be able to understand

00:36:44.960 --> 00:36:52.040
[Guest]: how rich the rest of the world was in comparison to India. But they understood a sense of what

00:36:52.040 --> 00:36:56.480
[Guest]: the type of poverty India was experiencing through oral narratives of, you know, parents

00:36:56.480 --> 00:37:00.880
[Guest]: or grandparents talking about how at one point in time there was this very prosperous, you

00:37:00.880 --> 00:37:07.240
[Guest]: know, trade in cottons, in cotton goods, through understanding that poverty was increasing

00:37:07.240 --> 00:37:13.000
[Guest]: dramatically just through the spate of famines, just through the fact that so many people

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:18.000
[Guest]: were pouring into the city of Bombay due to terrible conditions in the countryside. So

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:22.600
[Guest]: at this point in time, with so much evidence of poverty around you, education was really

00:37:22.600 --> 00:37:27.520
[Guest]: the one tool you had for betterment. And it was also one of those areas which the colonial

00:37:27.520 --> 00:37:32.760
[Guest]: government obviously exercised control, but you had enough space to also exercise your

00:37:32.760 --> 00:37:39.200
[Guest]: own agency. So, you know, the British officials at this time would talk a lot about how Indians

00:37:39.200 --> 00:37:43.840
[Guest]: need to embrace Western education and, you know, they're so ignorant and they're so backward,

00:37:43.840 --> 00:37:47.580
[Guest]: but they wouldn't really lift a finger for that. Right. I mean, if you look at the amount

00:37:47.580 --> 00:37:51.360
[Guest]: of money that the government of Bombay was paying for Indian education at this point

00:37:51.360 --> 00:37:57.280
[Guest]: in time, it's a few hundred rupees. It's not much. Right. I mean, it's terribly low. So

00:37:57.280 --> 00:38:02.680
[Guest]: Indians kind of filled the gap. And so I think there were many reasons why Naoroji was motivated

00:38:02.680 --> 00:38:07.240
[Guest]: to take on these educational activities just by surveying the condition of people around

00:38:07.240 --> 00:38:11.680
[Guest]: them and realizing that he himself had grown up in such an impoverished background. So

00:38:11.680 --> 00:38:19.120
[Guest]: there was, you know, struggle makes people all the more motivated to undertake such work.

00:38:19.120 --> 00:38:23.400
[Guest]: And this theme of betterment and reform through education was something that, again, just

00:38:23.400 --> 00:38:28.360
[Guest]: propelled young Bombay from its very start. And a very similar dynamic worked in Bengal

00:38:28.360 --> 00:38:34.760
[Guest]: with young Bengal, you know, one or two decades beforehand. So there really was an idea that,

00:38:34.760 --> 00:38:41.360
[Guest]: you know, something was wrong. The best way to help India to provide some sort of self-help

00:38:41.360 --> 00:38:46.400
[Guest]: was education. And education could provide reform in three crucial aspects, religious

00:38:46.400 --> 00:38:52.920
[Guest]: reform, social reform, and finally, political reform. And these three spheres of reform

00:38:52.920 --> 00:38:59.200
[Guest]: are completely linked. You know, it was impossible to think of one type of reform throughout

00:38:59.200 --> 00:39:04.080
[Guest]: the other. And these three pillars of reform, therefore, became kind of the foundation upon

00:39:04.080 --> 00:39:09.960
[Guest]: which all these different organizations that Naoroji helped to found in Bombay in the 1840s

00:39:09.960 --> 00:39:17.240
[Guest]: and 1850s, you know, come into life. So, you know, he helps establish learned societies.

00:39:17.240 --> 00:39:21.920
[Guest]: As you mentioned, he helps establish a Gujarati language newspaper, which is explicitly for

00:39:21.920 --> 00:39:25.920
[Guest]: the purpose of disseminating education and talking about the need for reform, not just

00:39:25.920 --> 00:39:31.440
[Guest]: within the Parsi community, but within the wider Gujarati reading public. He takes part

00:39:31.440 --> 00:39:38.240
[Guest]: in the first formal political organization, the Bombay Association in 1851, 1852. So it's

00:39:38.240 --> 00:39:43.680
[Guest]: a very well-rounded attempt to kind of think about how Indian society needed to be reformed

00:39:43.680 --> 00:39:49.560
[Guest]: and changed in reference to, you know, impetus from the West, but also in reference to what

00:39:49.560 --> 00:39:53.160
[Guest]: Indians themselves thought about what was wrong and what the situation was like under

00:39:53.160 --> 00:39:57.920
[Guest]: colonialism. And there definitely was a very radical streak in all of this also. You know,

00:39:57.920 --> 00:40:03.000
[Guest]: I mentioned in my book how people like Naoroji were influenced by a generation of quite radical

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:07.520
[Guest]: Maharashtrian thinkers from the 1840s who talked about colonialism being terrible and

00:40:07.520 --> 00:40:13.040
[Guest]: wrote about it publicly and talked about something like a drain of wealth well before, you know,

00:40:13.040 --> 00:40:18.600
[Guest]: Naoroji popularized the term. So all these different forms of impetus, you know, explain

00:40:18.600 --> 00:40:23.080
[Guest]: how young Bombay took place and why it took place at that particular point in time.

00:40:23.080 --> 00:40:28.280
[Amit Varma]: And you know, just on a tangent to use a phrase which has possibly become overused these days,

00:40:28.280 --> 00:40:33.360
[Amit Varma]: but is there a sense of what is the idea of India, if there is an idea of India, or what

00:40:33.360 --> 00:40:39.440
[Amit Varma]: are the ideas of India that are floating around in the ether which, you know, Naoroji can

00:40:39.440 --> 00:40:43.200
[Amit Varma]: sort of imbibe and, you know, take further?

00:40:43.200 --> 00:40:47.920
[Guest]: Absolutely. Yeah. I mean, you know, depending on what sources you're looking at, India still

00:40:47.920 --> 00:40:52.640
[Guest]: could be, you know, it still could include Afghanistan, it could include Singapore, it

00:40:52.640 --> 00:40:56.160
[Guest]: could include what, you know, what was called the East Indies in the sense of what we now

00:40:56.160 --> 00:41:00.960
[Guest]: know as Indonesia and Malaya. And certainly, since there were Indian populations in all

00:41:00.960 --> 00:41:06.400
[Guest]: of these places, there was an understanding of, you know, India validly being a part of

00:41:06.400 --> 00:41:11.280
[Guest]: these regions. But there definitely is a sense that, you know, the subcontinent as we think

00:41:11.280 --> 00:41:17.920
[Guest]: of it, you know, everything south of the Himalayas and the Hindu Kush, being India, that sense

00:41:17.920 --> 00:41:22.760
[Guest]: is definitely coming into play. I mean, when you read the newspapers from this era, people

00:41:22.760 --> 00:41:27.120
[Guest]: are talking about what's going on in Bengal, what's going on in Madras, they're also talking

00:41:27.120 --> 00:41:32.160
[Guest]: about what's going on in Ceylon. And, you know, eventually, by the time of the mutiny,

00:41:32.160 --> 00:41:36.400
[Guest]: parts of North India gather people's interest. But there definitely is a sense that, you

00:41:36.400 --> 00:41:40.160
[Guest]: know, there is this kind of contiguous unit. I mean, yes, there's a great degree of diversity

00:41:40.160 --> 00:41:45.560
[Guest]: in it, but there's a certain commonality. And there already is the idea that, you know,

00:41:45.560 --> 00:41:49.480
[Guest]: we should, you know, think about what Bengalis are thinking about, because ultimately, you

00:41:49.480 --> 00:41:55.480
[Guest]: know, we're part of the same milieu. We should exchange letters with whatever political association

00:41:55.480 --> 00:42:00.760
[Guest]: is taking place in Madras, because ultimately, their concerns are very similar to what we're

00:42:00.760 --> 00:42:06.080
[Guest]: talking about also. So, you know, there was, I think, a certain sense of cultural cohesion

00:42:06.080 --> 00:42:10.880
[Guest]: happening. And, you know, we can't discredit the, you know, the role of at least British

00:42:10.880 --> 00:42:14.760
[Guest]: colonial administration in this process. I mean, the fact that all of these places were

00:42:14.760 --> 00:42:20.080
[Guest]: under British colonial administration, obviously got people talking about how they could jointly

00:42:20.080 --> 00:42:24.480
[Guest]: together campaign for better rights towards the same government.

00:42:24.480 --> 00:42:31.000
[Amit Varma]: And just looking at what sort of shapes Naoroji's personality and his approach to dealing with

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:36.040
[Amit Varma]: the British, the famous moderate approach, quote unquote, so to say, you know, how big

00:42:36.040 --> 00:42:42.160
[Amit Varma]: a role did the contingency of just the environment around him in Bombay play in that? Because

00:42:42.160 --> 00:42:46.920
[Amit Varma]: it strikes me like there's one passage where you write, quote, as a student, Naoroji was

00:42:46.920 --> 00:42:51.240
[Amit Varma]: exposed to a constant tussle between a miserly government and Indian stakeholders demanding

00:42:51.240 --> 00:42:55.680
[Amit Varma]: more resources and better funding. He did not have to look far beyond the classroom

00:42:55.680 --> 00:43:01.840
[Amit Varma]: walls to observe the many yawning gaps between imperial rhetoric and reality, stop quote.

00:43:01.840 --> 00:43:08.280
[Amit Varma]: And the sense that I got from your chapter on this phase of his life is that number one,

00:43:08.280 --> 00:43:14.560
[Amit Varma]: whatever empire might be, at a personal level, like you said, the British teachers he encounters

00:43:14.560 --> 00:43:19.360
[Amit Varma]: at Elphinstone are very progressive and, you know, different from what the establishment

00:43:19.360 --> 00:43:23.680
[Amit Varma]: is like. Plus, there are other British people in power who take an interest in him, who

00:43:23.680 --> 00:43:29.120
[Amit Varma]: try to help him out in various ways, which to some extent could, you know, explain the

00:43:29.120 --> 00:43:33.840
[Amit Varma]: fact that he isn't a radical and thinking in terms of breaking away. Instead, he wants

00:43:33.840 --> 00:43:38.240
[Amit Varma]: to continue doing and he does for the rest of his life, what he's learned to do in these

00:43:38.240 --> 00:43:41.600
[Amit Varma]: early years in Bombay, that if you want to change something, say, if you want more funding

00:43:41.600 --> 00:43:47.760
[Amit Varma]: for schools, you petition, you know, you try to take legal ways, you send a petition, you

00:43:47.760 --> 00:43:52.520
[Amit Varma]: try to talk to sort of all of these people, you know, how contingent is the background

00:43:52.520 --> 00:43:57.520
[Amit Varma]: of, you know, how you grow up and these sort of influences and what you later on go on

00:43:57.520 --> 00:44:02.320
[Amit Varma]: to do, like, obviously, you've also looked at other historical figures, like, say, a

00:44:02.320 --> 00:44:07.920
[Amit Varma]: Tilak or a Bipin Chandrapal on one end, and, you know, maybe a Gokhale and a Ranade at

00:44:07.920 --> 00:44:13.320
[Amit Varma]: the more moderate end, you know, his fellow Parsi, Feroz Shah Mehta, for example, does

00:44:13.320 --> 00:44:18.200
[Amit Varma]: that make, does that kind of background and all of that sort of make a difference in what

00:44:18.200 --> 00:44:20.280
[Amit Varma]: you do for the rest of your life, you think?

00:44:20.280 --> 00:44:25.940
[Guest]: I think it plays a very large role. You know, towards the end of his life, Naoroji was rightly

00:44:25.940 --> 00:44:32.320
[Guest]: criticized by many radical nationalists as being too unwilling to give up this idea that

00:44:32.320 --> 00:44:36.800
[Guest]: the British people themselves were beneficent. Ultimately, they were on the side of justice

00:44:36.800 --> 00:44:42.160
[Guest]: and only if you tried hard enough, you would you would get what you what you deserved and

00:44:42.160 --> 00:44:47.640
[Guest]: what you demanded. And that sentiment, I think, stems to a large degree from what you said,

00:44:47.640 --> 00:44:53.880
[Guest]: his upbringing in Bombay. He was around a lot of relatively progressive minded Britons,

00:44:53.880 --> 00:45:00.240
[Guest]: you know, people who believed in, obviously, the British Empire, but at the same time,

00:45:00.240 --> 00:45:07.840
[Guest]: were critical of it and did make an honest attempt to help people like Naoroji. So there

00:45:07.840 --> 00:45:13.200
[Guest]: was a definite sense that, you know, the system as it was in Bombay had certain advantages

00:45:13.200 --> 00:45:17.720
[Guest]: and the British British rule, you know, even though it had all these terrible flaws, at

00:45:17.720 --> 00:45:22.120
[Guest]: least that progressive impulse was there. And, you know, if you if you just if you pushed

00:45:22.120 --> 00:45:25.280
[Guest]: and prodded enough and if you try to convince people enough, you know, they'd come around

00:45:25.280 --> 00:45:29.520
[Guest]: to your viewpoint. And that was something very difficult for Naoroji to let go of. I

00:45:29.520 --> 00:45:34.600
[Guest]: mean, by the time he's 80, he's just about wrestling with this idea that, you know, maybe

00:45:34.600 --> 00:45:39.360
[Guest]: all of this is wrong and, you know, ultimately something like Swaraj, where you're completely

00:45:39.360 --> 00:45:43.960
[Guest]: separate from the British Empire, might be a possibility. And again, for someone like

00:45:43.960 --> 00:45:49.640
[Guest]: Tilak or Bipin Chandra Pal or others, this idea, they had thrown out the window many

00:45:49.640 --> 00:45:54.960
[Guest]: decades ago. Right. I mean, they had already realized that this sense of British justice

00:45:54.960 --> 00:45:59.440
[Guest]: was more illusion than fact. And so it was much easier. They had made this realization

00:45:59.440 --> 00:46:04.920
[Guest]: much earlier in life. Naoroji, since he had a relatively positive experience with many

00:46:04.920 --> 00:46:09.560
[Guest]: of these figures and since the figures in his life who were British were more progressive

00:46:09.560 --> 00:46:13.920
[Guest]: in many ways, did not have this opportunity. You know, so I think that's that's one ground

00:46:13.920 --> 00:46:18.560
[Guest]: which we can definitely criticize Naoroji for not seeing, you know, a more holistic

00:46:18.560 --> 00:46:23.000
[Guest]: perspective on what the British public was like or, you know, interrogating this idea

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:24.600
[Amit Varma]: of what British justice meant.

00:46:24.600 --> 00:46:30.160
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, at 30, so till 30, there have been sort of these two strands that I see

00:46:30.160 --> 00:46:35.800
[Amit Varma]: in Naoroji's life. One is that he's intensely into education and he's a math whiz. You know,

00:46:35.800 --> 00:46:43.080
[Amit Varma]: if he was alive today, he'd be a quant or a serious economist. I mean, you know, some

00:46:43.080 --> 00:46:48.600
[Amit Varma]: of that work is just remarkable. And that's on the one hand where he's on the track and

00:46:48.600 --> 00:46:52.640
[Amit Varma]: massive academic success because hey, first Indian professor and all of that. The other

00:46:52.640 --> 00:46:56.840
[Amit Varma]: track is he's doing things within society. He started all these girls schools and he's

00:46:56.840 --> 00:47:01.920
[Amit Varma]: part of these organizations. He started this Gujarati newspaper. And then at 30, he gives

00:47:01.920 --> 00:47:06.920
[Amit Varma]: it all up or not gives it all up, but leaves it for the moment and decides to go to England

00:47:06.920 --> 00:47:11.080
[Amit Varma]: to basically work in a corporate job for the commas, you know, and strikes out on his own

00:47:11.080 --> 00:47:16.240
[Amit Varma]: a couple of years later. But essentially, he ends up spending decades in England. Give

00:47:16.240 --> 00:47:21.280
[Amit Varma]: me a sense of what's going through his head at this time. Like, what does he want? Why

00:47:21.280 --> 00:47:25.960
[Amit Varma]: is, you know, these two things are so important to him being everything that he's doing in

00:47:25.960 --> 00:47:31.200
[Amit Varma]: Bombay as part of Young Bombay and outside that and equally as an academic, you know,

00:47:31.200 --> 00:47:35.640
[Amit Varma]: he's making such a difference here in Bombay. And yet he goes there and this is in fact

00:47:35.640 --> 00:47:41.040
[Amit Varma]: the criticism that will come to him even later when he's, you know, settling down and wants

00:47:41.040 --> 00:47:45.200
[Amit Varma]: to run for parliament after losing the first time and you point out in your book how all

00:47:45.200 --> 00:47:50.240
[Amit Varma]: his friends including people in the Congress because the Congress is supporting him financially

00:47:50.240 --> 00:47:53.680
[Amit Varma]: and morally and they're sort of with him but they're like, no, you come back here, we need

00:47:53.680 --> 00:47:58.520
[Amit Varma]: you here. And he's still there. What does he want? This was very sort of interesting

00:47:58.520 --> 00:48:04.360
[Amit Varma]: to me because it's not like he goes to England and he immediately gets into activism for,

00:48:04.360 --> 00:48:08.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, a better India or whatever. So I was just trying to kind of figure out his

00:48:08.080 --> 00:48:09.720
[Guest]: motivations here.

00:48:09.720 --> 00:48:13.920
[Guest]: It's very tough to understand and figure out those motivations because so much of the source

00:48:13.920 --> 00:48:19.920
[Guest]: material is lost. You know, amongst those 30,000 documents that I talked about, there's

00:48:19.920 --> 00:48:25.080
[Guest]: nothing for this era. Most of the 30,000 documents come from after the year 1886 and we're in

00:48:25.080 --> 00:48:31.920
[Guest]: the year 1855 when he decides to go out to England. So it's very tough to reconstruct

00:48:31.920 --> 00:48:38.100
[Guest]: what his motives are. But we do know that his announcement to sail and go off to England

00:48:38.100 --> 00:48:42.440
[Guest]: and give up everything that he had done in Bombay came as a complete shock to everyone.

00:48:42.440 --> 00:48:49.720
[Guest]: So when his superiors at Elphinstone College learned that he has decided to quit and join

00:48:49.720 --> 00:48:54.920
[Guest]: a commercial firm, they're so caught off guard. I mean, apparently the school principal says

00:48:54.920 --> 00:49:00.520
[Guest]: to him, you know, what a fall. You know, what have you done? There are other officials in

00:49:00.520 --> 00:49:04.680
[Guest]: the government who are so panicked by this that they actually use the telegraph to contact

00:49:04.680 --> 00:49:08.480
[Guest]: the governor. And the telegraph had just been introduced into India at this point in time.

00:49:08.480 --> 00:49:12.640
[Guest]: So they're using this newfangled technology because it's really urgent. What do we do?

00:49:12.640 --> 00:49:16.640
[Guest]: This star teacher is now leaving and he's been such an important part of the urban fabric

00:49:16.640 --> 00:49:21.720
[Guest]: in Bombay. What do we do? What we do know is that Naorochi was only expecting to be

00:49:21.720 --> 00:49:26.680
[Guest]: in the United Kingdom for a few years. He wanted about two or three years leave from

00:49:26.680 --> 00:49:31.480
[Guest]: Elphinstone and then he wanted to come back and teach. That, of course, never happened.

00:49:31.480 --> 00:49:37.400
[Guest]: He ended up staying on in Great Britain and he pursued a career as a businessman. But,

00:49:37.400 --> 00:49:42.040
[Guest]: you know, if we if we try to think of what's going on inside his mind, a few things come

00:49:42.040 --> 00:49:47.760
[Guest]: to mind. I mean, first of all, by 1855, he's getting much more involved in political activities

00:49:47.760 --> 00:49:52.560
[Guest]: and political activities in the direction of criticizing colonial rule. By this point

00:49:52.560 --> 00:49:56.880
[Guest]: in time, the Bombay Association is established. There's kind of a, you know, a more forward

00:49:56.880 --> 00:50:02.160
[Guest]: looking wing within the Bombay Association where people like Bawda Jilard or Naorochi

00:50:02.160 --> 00:50:06.480
[Guest]: Fardunji are participating. And they're much more vocal in their criticism of British rule.

00:50:06.480 --> 00:50:10.440
[Guest]: So what better can you do than to go to the heart of empire and see for yourself what's

00:50:10.440 --> 00:50:15.560
[Guest]: going on there? You know, what what what is the heart of empire like and how how does

00:50:15.560 --> 00:50:20.520
[Guest]: the you know, the whole political process work over there? And the second reason, again,

00:50:20.520 --> 00:50:24.560
[Guest]: of why this would have been an attractive thing for Naorochi is that when he joins the

00:50:24.560 --> 00:50:29.840
[Guest]: Kama Company, he's specifically going there to work in the cotton trade. And in this era,

00:50:29.840 --> 00:50:33.880
[Guest]: the cotton trade was the big business for Bombay. I mean, opium has just started to

00:50:33.880 --> 00:50:37.760
[Guest]: fade as being kind of this important, you know, component of the economy and cotton

00:50:37.760 --> 00:50:43.800
[Guest]: was really coming in. And by being an Indian in Great Britain, you were kind of, again,

00:50:43.800 --> 00:50:47.760
[Guest]: going against the tide. You were, you know, cotton was flowing out of India and enriching

00:50:47.760 --> 00:50:52.320
[Guest]: Great Britain. Here you were an Indian going out to Great Britain in order to kind of reverse

00:50:52.320 --> 00:50:56.760
[Guest]: that direction a little bit and, you know, help Indians acquire machinery by which they

00:50:56.760 --> 00:51:00.640
[Guest]: can eventually build their own cotton mills and maybe take a chunk out of Lancashire's

00:51:00.640 --> 00:51:05.760
[Guest]: profit. So I think it was exciting in that aspect also from him. And the last component

00:51:05.760 --> 00:51:10.120
[Guest]: where I think it really plays an influential, an idea that really plays an influential role

00:51:10.120 --> 00:51:16.680
[Guest]: in Naorochi's thought and his decision to go out to England is that at this time, there

00:51:16.680 --> 00:51:22.080
[Guest]: is, you know, discussion about Indians being allowed to join the Indian Civil Service.

00:51:22.080 --> 00:51:26.720
[Guest]: And again, the Indian Civil Service was this elite cadre, kind of the, you know, the origins

00:51:26.720 --> 00:51:32.680
[Guest]: of what is now the IAS. And 99.9 percent, it was, it was, well, 100 percent at this

00:51:32.680 --> 00:51:36.960
[Guest]: point in time, it was British. The people working at, you know, all rungs of power of

00:51:36.960 --> 00:51:44.920
[Guest]: importance in the ICS were British. And through a system of civil service examinations, finally,

00:51:44.920 --> 00:51:49.400
[Guest]: there was the possibility that Indians could be allowed to compete. And so Naorochi went

00:51:49.400 --> 00:51:55.200
[Guest]: out to England in part in order to kind of help guide the first Indians who came out

00:51:55.200 --> 00:51:59.320
[Guest]: to Great Britain in order to compete for the civil service exam. Because, again, in this

00:51:59.320 --> 00:52:03.680
[Guest]: era, if you as an Indian wanted to join the civil service, you could not take an exam

00:52:03.680 --> 00:52:08.560
[Guest]: in India. You had to, you know, shell out your life savings, sail halfway across the

00:52:08.560 --> 00:52:14.000
[Guest]: world to Great Britain, spend upwards to two years studying in an extremely expensive,

00:52:14.000 --> 00:52:19.240
[Guest]: cold foreign country with bad food, and only then, you know, maybe take the exam and, you

00:52:19.240 --> 00:52:23.800
[Guest]: know, 50 percent chance that you might pass. So, you know, if you failed, you lost everything

00:52:23.800 --> 00:52:28.680
[Guest]: and you had to return to Bombay or Calcutta or wherever, humiliate. So this was not an

00:52:28.680 --> 00:52:34.120
[Guest]: easy prospect for anyone who wanted to undertake this effort. And Naorochi thought, you know,

00:52:34.120 --> 00:52:38.080
[Guest]: as someone who is interested in political matters, why don't I go out there and, as

00:52:38.080 --> 00:52:43.360
[Guest]: a professor, try to help people and help them get prepared for this exam? And that's initially

00:52:43.360 --> 00:52:47.960
[Guest]: what he does. I mean, when he goes out to Great Britain, he joins this cotton firm of

00:52:47.960 --> 00:52:52.640
[Guest]: the Kama family, but he's immediately distracted. He might have been a very bad businessman

00:52:52.640 --> 00:52:57.880
[Guest]: in this aspect, in the sense that he's immediately distracted by political activities. He starts

00:52:57.880 --> 00:53:03.480
[Guest]: to campaign for civil service reform. He joins as a professor in University College in London,

00:53:03.480 --> 00:53:09.200
[Guest]: teaching Gujarati. And this puts him in touch with people like Henry Maine or other important

00:53:09.200 --> 00:53:14.560
[Guest]: colonial officials who are sitting as examiners for the civil service exam. So Naorochi is

00:53:14.560 --> 00:53:19.740
[Guest]: one examiner alongside Henry Maine and other important individuals. And so he's automatically

00:53:19.740 --> 00:53:24.960
[Guest]: drawn into this political world that he could only see at a distance when he was sitting

00:53:24.960 --> 00:53:25.960
[Amit Varma]: in Bombay.

00:53:25.960 --> 00:53:31.640
[Amit Varma]: And I found it instructive to remind myself, and your book makes it easy to do so, that,

00:53:31.640 --> 00:53:36.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, going to London in those days wasn't quite what it is today, that you just take

00:53:36.320 --> 00:53:40.080
[Amit Varma]: a flight and you're there. It took weeks to get there. And London is a shitty city in

00:53:40.080 --> 00:53:45.800
[Amit Varma]: those days. It's polluted, it's grotty, it's Charles Dickens' London, it's full of disease.

00:53:45.800 --> 00:53:50.880
[Amit Varma]: It's a mess, life isn't easy. And you've got various parts in your book where you paint

00:53:50.880 --> 00:53:57.680
[Amit Varma]: a very vivid picture of sort of the trouble Naorochi had in just adjusting there and why

00:53:57.680 --> 00:54:02.580
[Amit Varma]: he became such a focal point of the community. At this point, it's time to actually sort

00:54:02.580 --> 00:54:07.120
[Amit Varma]: of begin with what, in your book, you describe as the three phases of Naorochi's life. We've

00:54:07.120 --> 00:54:10.920
[Amit Varma]: just reached the beginning of phase one, when he lands up in London. So let's take a quick

00:54:10.920 --> 00:54:17.560
[Amit Varma]: commercial break, and then we'll get into the meat and bones of it as soon as we are

00:54:17.560 --> 00:54:18.560
[Amit Varma]: back.

