[Amit Varma]: This is just a gesture of appreciation. Help keep this thing going. sceneunseen.in slash

00:55:33.600 --> 00:55:35.880
[Amit Varma]: support.

00:55:35.880 --> 00:55:39.180
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to The Scene and the Unseen. I'm chatting with Dinyar Patel on his excellent

00:55:39.180 --> 00:55:46.320
[Amit Varma]: biography of Dadabhai Naoroji. And, you know, at this point, Naoroji has reached London

00:55:46.320 --> 00:55:52.480
[Amit Varma]: and we have reached London with him. The year is 1855. And now begins sort of the first

00:55:52.480 --> 00:55:57.560
[Amit Varma]: phase, or rather he moves towards the first phase of his career, which you describe as

00:55:57.560 --> 00:56:03.200
[Amit Varma]: a theoretical phase, where he comes up with what is known as a drain theory. And, you

00:56:03.200 --> 00:56:07.840
[Amit Varma]: know, one of the interesting points you made here is you pointed out how Naoroji is often

00:56:07.840 --> 00:56:14.040
[Amit Varma]: considered an economic nationalist, but you point out that economic nationalism and political

00:56:14.040 --> 00:56:19.800
[Amit Varma]: nationalism for him kind of go together. They are so intimately enmeshed. So tell me a little

00:56:19.800 --> 00:56:24.760
[Amit Varma]: bit about the kind of work he does during this period. What is his thesis? What is his

00:56:24.760 --> 00:56:25.760
[Guest]: solution?

00:56:25.760 --> 00:56:30.240
[Guest]: Economic nationalism and political nationalism, at least in my perspective, and at least in,

00:56:30.240 --> 00:56:36.240
[Guest]: you know, in light of Naoroji's career, were two sides of the same coin. Naoroji began

00:56:36.240 --> 00:56:42.520
[Guest]: his interest in, began pursuing an interest in Indian poverty out of this question of

00:56:42.520 --> 00:56:48.400
[Guest]: reform, government reform, and ultimately poverty becomes the rationale for political

00:56:48.400 --> 00:56:54.240
[Guest]: reform in India. And I think there are a few reasons why, again, he starts to think about

00:56:54.240 --> 00:57:00.760
[Guest]: poverty and reform at the same time. So, again, if you are in London in the late 1850s and

00:57:00.760 --> 00:57:05.800
[Guest]: the early 1860s, you are in the biggest city of the world. You are in the most powerful

00:57:05.800 --> 00:57:10.040
[Guest]: city in the world. As you mentioned, you're in a terrible city also, right? I mean, it's

00:57:10.040 --> 00:57:15.320
[Guest]: horribly polluted. It's smelly. It's dirty. The Thames smells like sulfur. The food is

00:57:15.320 --> 00:57:19.320
[Guest]: awful, of course. I mean, so it's a difficult place to be, but it's also it's a fascinating

00:57:19.320 --> 00:57:24.440
[Guest]: place to be. It's kind of like Bombay today. I mean, it's, you know, it's both, you know,

00:57:24.440 --> 00:57:30.480
[Guest]: dirty and smelly, but also very exciting and, you know, very, you know, it's an exciting

00:57:30.480 --> 00:57:37.840
[Guest]: place to be in. And in this era, when Naoroji is in London, again, he realizes just how

00:57:37.840 --> 00:57:41.920
[Guest]: rich, you know, in spite of all these terrible things about London, how rich Great Britain

00:57:41.920 --> 00:57:46.560
[Guest]: is in comparison to India. You know, the country is booming. It's, you know, the world's most

00:57:46.560 --> 00:57:52.520
[Guest]: prosperous country. There are factories everywhere. There's a large working class that's being

00:57:52.520 --> 00:57:56.440
[Guest]: slowly empowered through political reform. There are politicians who are talking about

00:57:56.440 --> 00:58:01.320
[Guest]: democratization. And at the same time, you know, being in London and Liverpool, which

00:58:01.320 --> 00:58:06.480
[Guest]: was the other city he lived in, he was, you know, miles away from the places where all

00:58:06.480 --> 00:58:10.280
[Guest]: the wealth of empire was dumped and distributed across the country. So when we think of the

00:58:10.280 --> 00:58:14.240
[Guest]: drain of wealth, he was at the very end of the spigot. I mean, he saw the wealth that

00:58:14.240 --> 00:58:18.920
[Guest]: had been drained out, you know, come to British shores and be disseminated through the banks

00:58:18.920 --> 00:58:24.240
[Guest]: and bank accounts of various British individuals. So, you know, there's a very vivid kind of

00:58:24.240 --> 00:58:30.120
[Guest]: understanding of how imperialism works when you're at the very heart of empire. And again,

00:58:30.120 --> 00:58:35.520
[Guest]: the last reason for why this era is particularly important is what is going on around the empire

00:58:35.520 --> 00:58:40.480
[Guest]: and globally at this moment. So, of course, in the early 1860s, you have the American

00:58:40.480 --> 00:58:46.480
[Guest]: Civil War, which has an immediate global knockoff effect. All of a sudden, in one stroke, the

00:58:46.480 --> 00:58:51.600
[Guest]: cotton that had been feeding this great industrial machine in Great Britain is cut off. It had

00:58:51.600 --> 00:58:55.840
[Guest]: come from the American South. And there's this huge panic, right? People like Sven Beckert

00:58:55.840 --> 00:59:00.640
[Guest]: have written about it in his book, Empire of Cotton. What do you do? You know, the cotton

00:59:00.640 --> 00:59:04.720
[Guest]: that was sustaining your industrial prowess is no longer there. Well, eventually, India

00:59:04.720 --> 00:59:08.960
[Guest]: became one of those places where cotton was was brought into to feed these, you know,

00:59:08.960 --> 00:59:15.280
[Guest]: dark sustanic mills, so to speak, of of Great Britain. And Naroji's friends in Bombay and

00:59:15.280 --> 00:59:20.520
[Guest]: he in London get extremely rich during this cotton boom during the American Civil War.

00:59:20.520 --> 00:59:26.400
[Guest]: And as quickly as the cotton boom ends, they all go bankrupt. You know, Naroji goes bankrupt

00:59:26.400 --> 00:59:31.360
[Guest]: because he loans out money to friends who turn out to, you know, not have been able

00:59:31.360 --> 00:59:36.040
[Guest]: to pay him back. He was a bit too honest of a businessman in that regard. But automatically

00:59:36.040 --> 00:59:41.240
[Guest]: you get this huge slump in Bombay, which eventually, you know, which has terrible consequences

00:59:41.240 --> 00:59:46.400
[Guest]: in the countryside. I mean, it contributes to to famines in places like Kandesh and Gujarat

00:59:46.400 --> 00:59:52.640
[Guest]: by the 1860s and 1870s. So there's one kind of big global shock, right, that kind of brings

00:59:52.640 --> 00:59:57.600
[Guest]: home this idea of how the economy is linked together and how poverty and and prosperity

00:59:57.600 --> 01:00:02.320
[Guest]: are again two sides of the same coin. The other big event that takes place, which again

01:00:02.320 --> 01:00:10.160
[Guest]: Naroji is seeing from a distance, is the Orissa famine of 1867, 1868, where again, you know,

01:00:10.160 --> 01:00:14.160
[Guest]: he he'd never stepped foot in Orissa at this point in time. But the reports that were coming

01:00:14.160 --> 01:00:18.400
[Guest]: out of Orissa at this point were gruesome and terrible. One out of every three people

01:00:18.400 --> 01:00:23.840
[Guest]: might have died. And as later investigations took place, it was realized that this was

01:00:23.840 --> 01:00:27.760
[Guest]: largely preventable. I mean, there were boats with grain that could have easily been shipped

01:00:27.760 --> 01:00:31.520
[Guest]: in. But, you know, the colonial officials, for various reasons, did not do it. And the

01:00:31.520 --> 01:00:37.360
[Guest]: result is one million people dead. And so the the very first proper speech that Naroji

01:00:37.360 --> 01:00:41.360
[Guest]: gives on the drain of wealth, he doesn't call it the drain of wealth at this point in time.

01:00:41.360 --> 01:00:45.840
[Guest]: He doesn't even use the word drain, is kind of in reflection to these two particular moments

01:00:45.840 --> 01:00:50.240
[Guest]: and especially the Orissa famine. I mean, he gives a speech in 1867. So the Orissa famine

01:00:50.240 --> 01:00:55.360
[Guest]: is definitely very much on his mind. And he asks a question, you know, OK, so British

01:00:55.360 --> 01:01:00.320
[Guest]: rule, we're told, is good. It's provided us with all these benefits, rule of law. It's

01:01:00.320 --> 01:01:06.640
[Guest]: supposedly better than the chaos that was present in India before British rule. So you

01:01:06.640 --> 01:01:12.080
[Guest]: have that. But at the same time, you have these terrible famines, whereas the life that's

01:01:12.080 --> 01:01:17.520
[Guest]: secured through law and peace is ultimately being killed anyway, right, through terrible

01:01:17.520 --> 01:01:22.800
[Guest]: famine. So what gives? What explains this contradiction? And that really is the impetus

01:01:22.800 --> 01:01:28.800
[Guest]: for understanding Indian poverty in Naroji's mind. Why is, on one hand, British rule being

01:01:28.800 --> 01:01:33.680
[Guest]: credited with giving these benefits to India, yet on the other hand, it's very clearly impoverishing

01:01:33.680 --> 01:01:40.080
[Guest]: the country? Why is there this central contradiction? And as Naroji progresses through about two

01:01:40.080 --> 01:01:47.200
[Guest]: decades of close economic analysis, he again sheds this view that British rule was beneficent,

01:01:47.200 --> 01:01:51.760
[Guest]: that it ultimately was doing all of these good things. So these ideas that he had during

01:01:51.760 --> 01:01:56.800
[Guest]: his first few speeches that, you know, some of the drain was justified, that the services

01:01:56.800 --> 01:02:01.120
[Guest]: that the British were rendered were being paid back in part through the drain, he throws

01:02:01.120 --> 01:02:05.920
[Guest]: these out the window. And he realizes that, no, the drain itself is a nefarious process.

01:02:05.920 --> 01:02:10.400
[Guest]: And he realizes that, you know, the supposed benefits of British rule, like the railways,

01:02:10.960 --> 01:02:15.280
[Guest]: irrigation systems, et cetera, are actually accelerating the drain. You know, with the

01:02:15.280 --> 01:02:20.480
[Guest]: railways, you get the wealth out of places like Kandesh or Berar or Gujarat even quicker,

01:02:20.480 --> 01:02:25.040
[Guest]: and you impoverish the people even quicker. So, you know, this is also where this whole

01:02:25.040 --> 01:02:30.240
[Guest]: idea of radicalization kind of seeps in, this kind of ability to kind of discard your previous

01:02:30.240 --> 01:02:35.280
[Guest]: notions and based on the facts and evidence before you, go in a more progressive political direction.

01:02:36.640 --> 01:02:43.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it kind of struck me, you've given an example of how in many of these early speeches,

01:02:43.200 --> 01:02:47.760
[Amit Varma]: he's saying kind of fairly conciliatory things to the British, where his tone is extremely

01:02:47.760 --> 01:02:52.400
[Amit Varma]: moderate, like at one point, you write, quote, somewhat incredibly, he believed that part of

01:02:52.400 --> 01:02:56.960
[Amit Varma]: the drain was justified in exchange for the supposed political, moral and social benefits

01:02:56.960 --> 01:03:01.600
[Amit Varma]: of British rule. It was inevitable that India had to sacrifice some of its wealth. And now,

01:03:01.600 --> 01:03:07.120
[Amit Varma]: you quote, Navroji, if India is to be regenerated by England, India must make up its mind to pay

01:03:07.120 --> 01:03:13.200
[Amit Varma]: the price, stop quote. But, you know, as time goes by, this changes to, for example, at one point,

01:03:14.400 --> 01:03:19.600
[Amit Varma]: you know, speaking publicly, he says, quote, so far as my inquiries go at present, the conclusion

01:03:19.600 --> 01:03:25.120
[Amit Varma]: I draw is that wherever the East India Company acquired territory, impoverishment followed

01:03:25.120 --> 01:03:30.560
[Amit Varma]: their steps, stop quote. And he's far more scathing in private, you quote, something that he wrote to

01:03:30.560 --> 01:03:35.440
[Amit Varma]: his friend, Bairamji Malabari, where he says, quote, these Englishmen cannot understand that

01:03:35.440 --> 01:03:40.240
[Amit Varma]: the wealth that they carry away from this country is the whole and sole cause of our misery. They

01:03:40.240 --> 01:03:45.600
[Amit Varma]: take away our bread, and then turn around asking us why we are not eating it, stop quote. So,

01:03:45.600 --> 01:03:50.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, very biting in this private message. Now, one of the early economic analysis, as you've

01:03:50.480 --> 01:03:56.080
[Amit Varma]: spoken about is where he tries to calculate what we would today call maybe the, you know,

01:03:56.080 --> 01:04:01.600
[Amit Varma]: income per capita. And he figures out that every Indian subject to the empire is getting 27

01:04:01.600 --> 01:04:08.800
[Amit Varma]: shillings, while the average income in the United Kingdom is about 33 pounds per head, and between

01:04:08.800 --> 01:04:16.080
[Amit Varma]: 27 to 40 shillings, depending on how you want to cut it. And one of the things that I was fascinated

01:04:16.080 --> 01:04:25.360
[Amit Varma]: in this chapter by is his incredibly sophisticated use of data. And this also sort of evolves, like

01:04:25.360 --> 01:04:31.040
[Amit Varma]: you've, you know, spoken about how, you know, by the time he's finished the last of his papers on

01:04:31.040 --> 01:04:36.880
[Amit Varma]: the subject, his economic analysis has developed in three distinct stages. I found this incredibly

01:04:36.880 --> 01:04:42.640
[Amit Varma]: fascinating, because each of these stages is one using data generated by the British, and B,

01:04:42.640 --> 01:04:47.440
[Amit Varma]: the analysis is far more sophisticated than anything the British can do. Tell me a bit about

01:04:47.440 --> 01:04:54.800
[Guest]: that. So in this era, again, when you are trying to get proper data on India, you are in many ways

01:04:54.800 --> 01:05:00.880
[Guest]: groping in the dark, it's very hard to get data at all, leave alone reliable data. So what the

01:05:00.880 --> 01:05:05.120
[Guest]: British would do is at least for economic data, they would, you know, there'll be different people

01:05:05.120 --> 01:05:09.360
[Guest]: around the country, and each district would tabulate approximately, you know, what was being

01:05:09.360 --> 01:05:15.440
[Guest]: grown, how much revenue was being collected. And then that data was compiled at a national level.

01:05:15.440 --> 01:05:21.040
[Guest]: But oftentimes, it was done in a very sloppy way. So if you wanted to, you know, get even the gross

01:05:21.040 --> 01:05:25.360
[Guest]: domestic product, you know, it was done in a way where, you know, lots of inaccuracies were in

01:05:25.360 --> 01:05:30.800
[Guest]: place, if you want to get, you know, the average earnings of particular places, oftentimes, you

01:05:30.800 --> 01:05:34.800
[Guest]: just take earnings figures for particular districts and divide by the number of districts.

01:05:34.800 --> 01:05:39.760
[Guest]: And as Naorochi pointed out, that's a flawed process, because each district was different,

01:05:39.760 --> 01:05:46.800
[Guest]: you cannot compare Delhi with, you know, say, Tanna district, or what have you, it's a false

01:05:46.800 --> 01:05:53.840
[Guest]: comparison. So there were many other people who, again, critical of the data, but only someone

01:05:53.840 --> 01:05:57.920
[Guest]: like Naorochi, who, you know, by being in London had access to all of this data that was at the

01:05:57.920 --> 01:06:03.520
[Guest]: India office, and also simultaneously had friends across the subcontinent who could give them

01:06:03.520 --> 01:06:08.720
[Guest]: supplementary data, only someone like him was really able to, you know, kind of take a more

01:06:08.720 --> 01:06:13.520
[Guest]: holistic view. So as you said, you know, he starts off with this original, you know, subset of

01:06:13.520 --> 01:06:19.680
[Guest]: official data, and the picture presented is quite rosy. You know, there's a surplus of exports,

01:06:20.480 --> 01:06:25.280
[Guest]: the economy is growing by X percentage, the amount of money that is being generated

01:06:25.840 --> 01:06:31.120
[Guest]: through various goods being exported, like cotton, or what have you is very large.

01:06:31.120 --> 01:06:35.760
[Guest]: But ultimately, when you put all these different pieces together, you realize that, you know,

01:06:36.640 --> 01:06:40.960
[Guest]: the big components of your economy aren't that big at all, anywhere in the first place. I mean,

01:06:40.960 --> 01:06:47.440
[Guest]: a lot of people by the 1870s and 1880s attacked Naorochi's economic arguments by saying,

01:06:47.440 --> 01:06:52.640
[Guest]: how can you say India is growing poorer, whereas in Bombay, you have this huge mill industry that's

01:06:52.640 --> 01:06:57.440
[Guest]: evolving? And certainly, yes, in Bombay, there was a very large mill industry. But ultimately,

01:06:57.440 --> 01:07:01.680
[Guest]: if you look at the whole economy of India, it wasn't that big, right? I mean, you know,

01:07:01.680 --> 01:07:08.000
[Guest]: you had 30 or 40 mills, and sure, it was, you know, creating a lot of wealth for a few Indians,

01:07:08.000 --> 01:07:11.680
[Guest]: but the vast majority of the country was still agricultural, of course, right, and living in

01:07:11.680 --> 01:07:16.240
[Guest]: rural areas of the country, which were being terribly impoverished. So it was kind of that

01:07:16.240 --> 01:07:21.520
[Guest]: ability to kind of balance things out and look at the big picture that helps Naorochi interrogate

01:07:21.520 --> 01:07:27.840
[Guest]: this data. And again, as he gains more friends around India, and as he himself goes on his own

01:07:27.840 --> 01:07:33.920
[Guest]: tours throughout parts of Gujarat or Western India, he himself collects data, he revises it,

01:07:33.920 --> 01:07:39.360
[Guest]: and he, by the end of his, you know, career as an economic thinker in the early 1880s,

01:07:39.360 --> 01:07:43.360
[Guest]: presents a picture where he shows Punjab, which was thought to be the most prosperous

01:07:44.080 --> 01:07:49.520
[Guest]: province of British India. It was also the part of British India which had British rule for the,

01:07:49.520 --> 01:07:55.040
[Guest]: you know, the shortest period of time, only since the 1840s. He shows even that in Punjab,

01:07:55.040 --> 01:08:02.080
[Guest]: the average person is living at bare subsistence levels. I mean, you know, if a famine came along,

01:08:02.080 --> 01:08:07.760
[Guest]: they would be dead. So it's a really striking comparison that he makes between this, you know,

01:08:07.760 --> 01:08:13.200
[Guest]: rosy pronouncement in the official circles of, you know, moral and material progress. There

01:08:13.200 --> 01:08:17.040
[Guest]: were reports that the British government would issue every year on the supposed moral and

01:08:17.040 --> 01:08:20.800
[Guest]: material progress of India, but the reality, as he discovered, was a very different picture.

01:08:21.520 --> 01:08:26.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, I was kind of extremely struck by your, you know, description of the stages. Again,

01:08:26.320 --> 01:08:31.120
[Amit Varma]: I'll, you know, quote from the book, quote, it indicates how Naoroji's economic analysis

01:08:31.120 --> 01:08:36.560
[Amit Varma]: developed in three distinct stages, approximations based on scanty data such as land revenue as was

01:08:36.560 --> 01:08:41.360
[Amit Varma]: undertaken in the wants and means of India, estimates based on rigorous analysis of official

01:08:41.360 --> 01:08:46.800
[Amit Varma]: raw data seen in poverty of India, and finally, Naoroji's supplementation of this raw data with

01:08:46.800 --> 01:08:51.680
[Amit Varma]: his own collected statistics and observations, enabling even more nuanced estimates and pointed

01:08:51.680 --> 01:08:56.080
[Amit Varma]: refutation of government figures, stop quote. And then you speak about how, you know, the Punjab

01:08:56.080 --> 01:09:01.600
[Amit Varma]: study where you pointed out where you said he, quote, analyzed production in Punjab through 21

01:09:01.600 --> 01:09:06.080
[Amit Varma]: key agricultural commodities, 15 types of manufactured goods, and other activities

01:09:06.080 --> 01:09:10.880
[Amit Varma]: such as mining and livestock, even taking into account marginal occupations such as fishing,

01:09:10.880 --> 01:09:17.440
[Amit Varma]: stop quote. And I can't imagine what he would have made of Indian data today. Because in many ways,

01:09:17.440 --> 01:09:25.280
[Amit Varma]: it is as confusing and obfuscatory and scattered as the data back then seems to have been. And now,

01:09:25.280 --> 01:09:31.840
[Amit Varma]: and here's one thing that I find so fascinating about Naoroji, that he excels in so many different

01:09:31.840 --> 01:09:37.200
[Amit Varma]: areas, which he combines into, you know, one stream of action, but it's not necessarily so.

01:09:37.200 --> 01:09:43.040
[Amit Varma]: Number one, he is a numbers guy, who's actually crunched all this raw data figured out that the

01:09:43.040 --> 01:09:47.520
[Amit Varma]: British conclusions are wrong. And he's, you know, he's done the rigorous analysis, and he's come to

01:09:47.520 --> 01:09:52.960
[Amit Varma]: these his own conclusions. Two, he's skilled at rhetoric, so he can actually go out and talk about

01:09:52.960 --> 01:09:59.120
[Amit Varma]: it, and present it and, you know, frame it in terms everyone can understand. Three, even before

01:09:59.120 --> 01:10:03.760
[Amit Varma]: he actively enters politics, he's actually a very good politician in terms of making all the

01:10:03.760 --> 01:10:09.200
[Amit Varma]: alliances he needs to make to get access to the data and to be able to speak at all these places.

01:10:09.200 --> 01:10:15.760
[Amit Varma]: And four, he's enough of a policy wonk to now go from economic analysis to policy suggestion

01:10:15.760 --> 01:10:20.880
[Amit Varma]: and say that, okay, this is a problem, they're bleeding us dry, this is what we need to do.

01:10:20.880 --> 01:10:25.840
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, do you have a comment on how remarkable it is that one man can combine all of

01:10:25.840 --> 01:10:32.960
[Amit Varma]: these different facets? And also now tell me about sort of what is, after that, tell me what is a

01:10:32.960 --> 01:10:39.120
[Amit Varma]: political conclusion that he then reaches from his economic analysis? It is quite remarkable that

01:10:39.120 --> 01:10:45.120
[Guest]: someone, again, this elite individual, this somewhat anglicized, quite anglicized individual,

01:10:45.120 --> 01:10:51.360
[Guest]: I should say, also had knowledge, such a deep knowledge of Indian agriculture that he could

01:10:51.360 --> 01:10:57.200
[Guest]: identify different types of sugar, different types of soil, and point out where, you know, British

01:10:57.200 --> 01:11:00.800
[Guest]: calculations were wrong, because, you know, they identified a different type of commodity

01:11:00.800 --> 01:11:08.320
[Guest]: than what existed in actuality. So he definitely did his homework. And, you know, I think at this

01:11:08.320 --> 01:11:13.440
[Guest]: point in time, again, he was just, he was a complete workaholic. His central focus of his

01:11:13.440 --> 01:11:18.880
[Guest]: life was understanding this process of impoverishment in India. So pretty much every

01:11:18.880 --> 01:11:24.000
[Guest]: activity he undertook was somehow connected with it. Whenever he went back to India, he would

01:11:24.000 --> 01:11:28.720
[Guest]: obviously spend time with his family, he didn't spend nearly enough, but he would immediately go

01:11:28.720 --> 01:11:34.640
[Guest]: and talk to officials and then head out to the countryside and go and look and see what's going

01:11:34.640 --> 01:11:41.680
[Guest]: on on the ground. Now, with regard to the political aspect of the drain theory, if you look at

01:11:41.680 --> 01:11:49.040
[Guest]: previous scholarship, most scholars have been quite puzzled by Naoroji's particular frame of

01:11:49.040 --> 01:11:54.160
[Guest]: mind on the drain theory, because he ultimately talks about one source of the drain. I mean,

01:11:54.160 --> 01:11:59.920
[Guest]: there were many sources of the drain, right? I mean, in terms of, you know, natural goods and

01:12:00.480 --> 01:12:06.160
[Guest]: natural resources being taken out of the country, high land revenue, but he ultimately focuses on

01:12:06.160 --> 01:12:10.400
[Guest]: one component that seems on the surface not terribly important, and that's the amount of

01:12:10.400 --> 01:12:16.160
[Guest]: money that's paid for the civil service. So, you know, he calculates that about 33 million pounds,

01:12:16.160 --> 01:12:21.840
[Guest]: which of course was a big amount in that day, was taken out of India every year and, you know,

01:12:21.840 --> 01:12:28.080
[Guest]: was, you know, sent back to Great Britain. That was the actual number in numerical terms of the

01:12:28.080 --> 01:12:33.920
[Guest]: drain of wealth. And of that, initially, he says only a small portion of that is the salaries that

01:12:33.920 --> 01:12:38.240
[Guest]: are paid to these British officers, because ultimately those British officers retire,

01:12:38.240 --> 01:12:41.920
[Guest]: or even if they stay in India, they send their earnings back to Great Britain to support family

01:12:41.920 --> 01:12:47.440
[Guest]: members. But there's a reason for why Naoroji focused on this, because again, as I said,

01:12:47.440 --> 01:12:53.440
[Guest]: politics and economics are two sides of the same coin in Naoroji's nationalism. The civil service

01:12:53.440 --> 01:13:00.480
[Guest]: is this major political issue of this era. It's kind of the linchpin of Indian grievances,

01:13:00.480 --> 01:13:05.120
[Guest]: because ultimately the civil servants are the ones that are kind of enforcing these very draconian

01:13:05.120 --> 01:13:09.840
[Guest]: policies throughout India. So Naoroji and others had this idea that if you open up the civil

01:13:09.840 --> 01:13:13.760
[Guest]: service to more Indians, and if Indians themselves are working for their own government,

01:13:13.760 --> 01:13:18.720
[Guest]: those policies will change. Indians would not be beholden to the same imperial principles.

01:13:18.720 --> 01:13:23.520
[Guest]: They would understand the country better. They, of course, spoke the languages. So by focusing

01:13:23.520 --> 01:13:28.320
[Guest]: on that particular component, just the civil service, you could make your political point

01:13:28.880 --> 01:13:34.080
[Guest]: very convincingly. And this was something that I think a lot of early historians didn't really

01:13:34.080 --> 01:13:40.880
[Guest]: focus enough on. They asked, why fixate on this particular small component? And you see

01:13:40.880 --> 01:13:47.280
[Guest]: throughout his writings that he, by the end of his career as an economic theorist, he doesn't

01:13:47.280 --> 01:13:52.240
[Guest]: care anymore about what percentage of the drain of wealth comes from the civil service, paying

01:13:52.240 --> 01:13:57.680
[Guest]: for the civil service. It doesn't matter. No matter what it is, it is what needs to be solved.

01:13:57.680 --> 01:14:02.000
[Guest]: It itself is the source of all other aspects of the drain of wealth, because once you had Indians

01:14:02.000 --> 01:14:07.120
[Guest]: in power, those other forms of drain, the drain of wealth would also dry up.

01:14:07.120 --> 01:14:11.840
[Amit Varma]: You know, it struck even me while I was reading the book that, you know, I couldn't

01:14:11.840 --> 01:14:16.160
[Amit Varma]: figure out at first that, okay, I understand the point he's made with the data that we are losing

01:14:16.160 --> 01:14:21.360
[Amit Varma]: so much money, a quarter of our taxes are just going back to England and we are progressively

01:14:21.360 --> 01:14:27.280
[Amit Varma]: getting impoverished by this. But why fixate on salaries of civil servants? And then it struck me

01:14:27.280 --> 01:14:31.840
[Amit Varma]: and tell me if this sort of interpretation is correct, that he figures out that, okay,

01:14:31.840 --> 01:14:36.560
[Amit Varma]: politically, what can I achieve? This is a reform that I can achieve politically,

01:14:36.560 --> 01:14:41.760
[Amit Varma]: and therefore, I'm going to make this the focus. And I'm not going to focus about all the other

01:14:41.760 --> 01:14:46.320
[Amit Varma]: diffused things that could solve the problem. And of course, the main thing that could solve

01:14:46.320 --> 01:14:52.240
[Amit Varma]: the problem is the end of empire itself. He can't go for that. So this is the one achievable thing

01:14:52.240 --> 01:15:00.640
[Amit Varma]: that he fixates on. But what is then fascinating to me is that he fixates on this for the rest of

01:15:00.640 --> 01:15:05.440
[Amit Varma]: his life, basically, I mean, till the end of his career in England, that, you know, even when he

01:15:05.440 --> 01:15:09.760
[Amit Varma]: is in parliament, which we'll talk about later, this is the one thing that he wants to do. It's

01:15:09.760 --> 01:15:15.600
[Amit Varma]: like for 30-40 years, he's just fixated on getting Indians into the civil service. And you could

01:15:15.600 --> 01:15:20.320
[Amit Varma]: argue that now we have an Indian civil service full of Indians, and it's not that much of an

01:15:20.320 --> 01:15:28.480
[Amit Varma]: improvement. But leaving that aside, you know, it's kind of a fascinating period. What also

01:15:28.480 --> 01:15:34.160
[Amit Varma]: I find really interesting here is this little detour he takes, where he concludes that, listen,

01:15:34.160 --> 01:15:39.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, British India is not one monolithic mass. There are places like Bombay and Madras and all

01:15:39.920 --> 01:15:44.720
[Amit Varma]: which they govern themselves, but there are all these princely states all around some 300 around

01:15:44.720 --> 01:15:49.920
[Amit Varma]: the area of Bombay alone. And they have less interference. And very often, they don't have an

01:15:49.920 --> 01:15:55.280
[Amit Varma]: English British civil service sitting there. And therefore, there is there is a better scope for

01:15:55.840 --> 01:16:00.800
[Amit Varma]: comparing what governance across these two places are and figuring out if good governance can

01:16:00.800 --> 01:16:05.840
[Amit Varma]: actually make a difference. And rather than theorize about it, he actually takes that step

01:16:05.840 --> 01:16:10.800
[Amit Varma]: and becomes the Diwan of Baroda, you know, where for a couple of years, he gets his fellow policy

01:16:10.800 --> 01:16:16.640
[Amit Varma]: wongs from the young Bombay days in and they try to do their own thing. And there is crazy politics

01:16:16.640 --> 01:16:21.040
[Amit Varma]: where the previous cabinet still exists as a shadow cabinet while they are trying to do their

01:16:21.040 --> 01:16:25.760
[Amit Varma]: things. And there are, you know, and there's a British guy there who's fighting with the king

01:16:25.760 --> 01:16:30.880
[Amit Varma]: and the king tries to poison the British guy and it's mad fun. So tell me a little bit about

01:16:30.880 --> 01:16:35.840
[Amit Varma]: that kind of period and what was he trying to do really? I mean, was he trying to sort of prove a

01:16:35.840 --> 01:16:40.560
[Amit Varma]: point that, hey, you know, A, we can govern well and B, if you govern properly, you'll get far

01:16:40.560 --> 01:16:46.240
[Guest]: better outcomes. Is that the whole thing that he was on? Princely states in this era are extremely

01:16:46.240 --> 01:16:50.560
[Guest]: interesting, you know, in terms of both the intrigues that are going on and also the potential

01:16:50.560 --> 01:16:55.600
[Guest]: that they held for some sort of reform. I mean, when we think of princely states nowadays,

01:16:55.600 --> 01:17:01.680
[Guest]: we think of reactionary old rajas who are holding on to power, anti-democratic. But the perspective

01:17:01.680 --> 01:17:09.680
[Guest]: from the late 19th century was very different. They were recognized as being the last vestiges

01:17:09.680 --> 01:17:17.120
[Guest]: of indigenous rule. In many cases, the rulers who are on the thrones in places like, say,

01:17:17.120 --> 01:17:23.040
[Guest]: Baroda or Gondal were quite progressive. They took tentative steps towards political reform.

01:17:23.040 --> 01:17:28.160
[Guest]: So, you know, Mysore, for example, set up a legislative assembly. So did Baroda. States

01:17:28.160 --> 01:17:34.400
[Guest]: like Gondal were experimenting in things like compulsory education by the very early 20th

01:17:34.400 --> 01:17:40.000
[Guest]: century. So these places were thought of as being almost political laboratories. These were the only

01:17:40.000 --> 01:17:45.520
[Guest]: places you as an Indian could, in your country, exercise some real administrative control.

01:17:46.160 --> 01:17:50.880
[Guest]: And it's for that reason that so many early Indian nationalists gravitate towards a few

01:17:50.880 --> 01:17:57.760
[Guest]: princely states. I mean, again, actually Dutt served as a diwan. Naoroji served as a diwan.

01:17:57.760 --> 01:18:02.400
[Guest]: Other individuals in the nationalist movement were constantly advising and were constantly in

01:18:02.400 --> 01:18:07.520
[Guest]: touch with princely officials from Hyderabad, through states that are now in Gujarat,

01:18:08.320 --> 01:18:14.320
[Guest]: through Rajputana states in eastern India as well. So they really kind of exercised the

01:18:14.320 --> 01:18:20.880
[Guest]: imagination of early nationalists. And you're right. I mean, when Naoroji goes out to Baroda, it is

01:18:21.680 --> 01:18:27.680
[Guest]: in many ways his attempt and the attempt of his young Bombay crowd, if you will, to kind of put

01:18:27.680 --> 01:18:33.600
[Guest]: ideas into practice. Here's an ability to actually implement the reforms and see whether we're right

01:18:33.600 --> 01:18:38.720
[Guest]: about, first of all, a drain of wealth existing in British territories that didn't really exist in

01:18:38.720 --> 01:18:44.560
[Guest]: the quote-unquote native states because they were under the control of our own people and

01:18:44.560 --> 01:18:49.200
[Guest]: whether or not government could be better when the people in charge were actually Indians.

01:18:50.000 --> 01:18:54.800
[Guest]: Now, in any other era, in any other place, this might have been a pretty interesting and

01:18:54.800 --> 01:19:02.160
[Guest]: potentially fruitful experience. Baroda in this period of time, 1873 through 1874, 1875,

01:19:02.160 --> 01:19:07.280
[Guest]: is the exact opposite of that place. I mean, it was ruled by a man called Malharrao.

01:19:07.280 --> 01:19:14.720
[Guest]: And as you had mentioned, Malharrao, the Gaikwad at this time, was in kind of a

01:19:14.720 --> 01:19:20.800
[Guest]: deadly battle with the British resident, a man called Robert Fair, who was himself no angel.

01:19:20.800 --> 01:19:26.000
[Guest]: He was kind of this very puritanical British officer who always tried to meddle in the affairs

01:19:26.000 --> 01:19:33.120
[Guest]: of princely states. He caused chaos when he was posted in Sindh by scheming behind

01:19:33.120 --> 01:19:38.240
[Guest]: the backs of various people. And when he goes to Baroda, he makes it his life's mission to

01:19:38.240 --> 01:19:43.040
[Guest]: somehow take down the Gaikwad. And when he learns that Naoroji is coming to serve as Diwan,

01:19:43.040 --> 01:19:49.600
[Guest]: a prime minister, he's livid. He regards Naoroji as being kind of a seditious traitor who's saying

01:19:49.600 --> 01:19:54.320
[Guest]: all these terrible things about British rule. And he actually says that he will not allow

01:19:54.320 --> 01:20:00.880
[Guest]: Naoroji to enter Baroda. I mean, think about this. I mean, a native state, an Indian princely state

01:20:00.880 --> 01:20:06.080
[Guest]: where the British agent, who's not really in power, still says, you know, I will not allow

01:20:06.080 --> 01:20:10.960
[Guest]: your Diwan to come into the territory of the state he's supposed to rule. It's quite incredible.

01:20:11.600 --> 01:20:17.440
[Guest]: And so for the next one and a half years when Naoroji serves as Diwan, he tries on one level

01:20:17.440 --> 01:20:21.440
[Guest]: to implement these reforms that he has been talking about. And at one level, it's very

01:20:21.440 --> 01:20:26.800
[Guest]: successful. I mean, he and his colleagues from Bombay clean up the judiciary. They get rid of

01:20:26.800 --> 01:20:31.920
[Guest]: practices like Nazarana, where people basically pay for, you know, judicial verdicts in their

01:20:31.920 --> 01:20:38.640
[Guest]: favor. They come up with a proper civil and penal code. They reform the, you know, the economy of

01:20:38.640 --> 01:20:46.560
[Guest]: the imperial household. They, you know, go through the country and revise the land rates, which were

01:20:46.560 --> 01:20:54.800
[Guest]: quite high. But ultimately, none of this really sticks because the Maharaja, the Gaikwad,

01:20:54.800 --> 01:21:00.160
[Guest]: was not fully committed to a program of reform. He wanted to kind of keep his cronies in power

01:21:00.160 --> 01:21:06.080
[Guest]: and at the same time kind of play politics against Robert Fair, the resident. So Naoroji gets trapped

01:21:06.080 --> 01:21:11.760
[Guest]: right in the middle. And many people at this point in time, you know, criticize him rightly for not

01:21:11.760 --> 01:21:16.080
[Guest]: being politically very savvy. I mean, here's someone who, again, has lived his life for the

01:21:16.080 --> 01:21:20.880
[Guest]: most part in an ivory tower. And now he's thrown into a very real politic environment where you

01:21:20.880 --> 01:21:25.840
[Guest]: have these two kind of implacable foes against each other, fighting for political power. And

01:21:25.840 --> 01:21:33.280
[Guest]: it gets so bad that, you know, in the, I think, November of 1874, Robert Fair, the resident,

01:21:33.280 --> 01:21:40.960
[Guest]: is actually poisoned. He's poisoned by via some arsenic being slipped into his glass of pomelo

01:21:40.960 --> 01:21:45.520
[Guest]: juice. And there was some, you know, glass shards and also in here. It's a huge scandal. And

01:21:45.520 --> 01:21:51.360
[Guest]: eventually it's discovered that the Gaikwad of Baroda might have been behind this, which is

01:21:51.360 --> 01:21:55.520
[Guest]: scandalous, right? I mean, you know, things have got that bad. And luckily, Naoroji resigns just

01:21:55.520 --> 01:22:02.320
[Guest]: before the, you know, things go to the wall and the Gaikwad is removed. But ultimately, it's quite

01:22:02.320 --> 01:22:08.000
[Guest]: a disappointing experience. I mean, Naoroji at one point kind of validates his idea that Indians,

01:22:08.000 --> 01:22:12.800
[Guest]: if they are in power, can, you know, kind of implement their own reforms. And he always had

01:22:12.800 --> 01:22:18.160
[Guest]: this idea that good government is no excuse for native government, indigenous government. And so

01:22:18.160 --> 01:22:22.880
[Guest]: in that sense, it's validated. But at the same time, he realizes that Indians, when they're in

01:22:22.880 --> 01:22:27.680
[Guest]: power themselves, are not always going to be these very selfless individuals who are out for helping

01:22:28.480 --> 01:22:32.400
[Guest]: the fellow countrymen. They have their own motives when they're in power and their own

01:22:32.400 --> 01:22:36.480
[Guest]: power dynamics. And the princely state system, you know, there's a reason why nationalists

01:22:36.480 --> 01:22:40.800
[Guest]: eventually fall out of, you know, these princes fall out of favor with nationalists, especially

01:22:40.800 --> 01:22:45.120
[Guest]: by the time of Gandhi's and Nehru's generation, because ultimately they are, you know, at one

01:22:45.120 --> 01:22:49.280
[Guest]: element, they are unrepresentative and undemocratic leaders. I mean, it took a

01:22:49.280 --> 01:22:55.760
[Guest]: Saiji Rao to kind of take that step of reforming. But ultimately, at the end of the day, Saiji Rao

01:22:55.760 --> 01:23:01.040
[Guest]: still wanted to stay in power, right? And by Gandhi and Nehru's time, Indian nationalism had

01:23:01.040 --> 01:23:05.200
[Guest]: moved beyond that stage where these princely rulers were already real political use to them.

01:23:05.200 --> 01:23:10.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, no. And it's also like you pointed out, the timing is just crazy that he actually goes in

01:23:10.240 --> 01:23:15.360
[Amit Varma]: there and, you know, gets his great team together, makes a few changes. But the optics are terrible

01:23:15.360 --> 01:23:18.640
[Amit Varma]: because the Indian guy tried to kill the British guy. So what are you going to talk about?

01:23:20.960 --> 01:23:25.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. Now, the interesting thing after this is that at this point, he decides that I,

01:23:25.920 --> 01:23:30.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, he moves on to the second phase, like he's done the theoretical phase. And this is sort

01:23:30.160 --> 01:23:34.720
[Amit Varma]: of a transition, I guess, between the theoretical phase of the second phase, which is a political

01:23:34.720 --> 01:23:39.920
[Amit Varma]: phase where he decides that, okay, I need to now get into British Parliament because it looks like

01:23:39.920 --> 01:23:46.080
[Amit Varma]: that is the only way I'll be able to make a difference. And there is sort of, for the concept

01:23:46.080 --> 01:23:50.640
[Amit Varma]: of this, there is some precedent, like at one point in your book, you write about Raja Ram Mohan Roy,

01:23:50.640 --> 01:23:56.560
[Amit Varma]: quote, in 1828, Ram Mohan dispatched petitions to both houses of Parliament, protesting the

01:23:56.560 --> 01:24:01.680
[Amit Varma]: company's intention to restrict membership in grand juries only to Christians, a matter that

01:24:01.680 --> 01:24:07.360
[Amit Varma]: he vigilantly pursued in Westminster after sailing to Great Britain in 1830. Recognizing the broad

01:24:07.360 --> 01:24:12.000
[Amit Varma]: public significance of his agitation against the Jury Act, Prasanna Kumar Tagore, a prominent

01:24:12.000 --> 01:24:19.200
[Amit Varma]: Calcutta lawyer, hailed Ram Mohan as India's unofficial MP, stop quote. And you talk about

01:24:19.200 --> 01:24:23.680
[Amit Varma]: how Naoroji decides that, okay, it's time, you know, enough of theory, enough of giving policy

01:24:23.680 --> 01:24:29.520
[Amit Varma]: suggestions. And hey, the Baroda experiment didn't work. So the only way to really change things is

01:24:29.520 --> 01:24:37.040
[Amit Varma]: to get into British Parliament. How outlandish is this at the time? Like at the time, how do people

01:24:37.040 --> 01:24:42.080
[Amit Varma]: think about this? And what is his thinking behind it? And you know, what happens after this? Just

01:24:42.080 --> 01:24:47.040
[Amit Varma]: take me a little bit through his thinking, because just to conceive of something like this seems so

01:24:47.040 --> 01:24:53.840
[Guest]: audacious at one level. It is quite outlandish. But again, from the perspective of Indian nationalism

01:24:53.840 --> 01:25:01.200
[Guest]: at this moment, you are searching for the weakest link, which is the reason why civil service and

01:25:01.200 --> 01:25:07.120
[Guest]: civil service reform preoccupied Indians so much as well. It was the weakest link in the edifice of

01:25:07.120 --> 01:25:10.960
[Guest]: British imperialism. Now that there were civil service exams, there was a chance for Indians

01:25:10.960 --> 01:25:17.680
[Guest]: to compete as well. Similarly, Parliament, the British Parliament, was regarded accurately by

01:25:17.680 --> 01:25:23.200
[Guest]: Indian nationalists as being the ultimate source of power. I mean, you had your viceroy, you had,

01:25:23.200 --> 01:25:30.000
[Guest]: you know, the various officials throughout India. But ultimately, the people who they looked up to

01:25:30.000 --> 01:25:34.560
[Guest]: was the British Parliament. You know, the Parliament would vote on a budget every year.

01:25:35.360 --> 01:25:39.680
[Guest]: The Parliament would occasionally, you know, censure the Indian government if it did some

01:25:39.680 --> 01:25:44.640
[Guest]: things that it didn't like. The Parliament had played a very important role under the company,

01:25:44.640 --> 01:25:49.440
[Guest]: under, you know, the East India Company of being a very vocal critic. So yes, it was outlandish,

01:25:49.440 --> 01:25:55.600
[Guest]: but it was the best option you had. You know, there was, you know, a 99 out of 100 chance that

01:25:55.600 --> 01:26:00.640
[Guest]: you would fail, but at least it wasn't 100 out of 100, which was the case in any other aspect. So,

01:26:00.640 --> 01:26:06.720
[Guest]: you know, at this phase, early Indian nationalism and the Congress, the Congress having just been

01:26:06.720 --> 01:26:13.120
[Guest]: established in 1885, looked to Great Britain as the only possible source of hope. And if it meant

01:26:13.120 --> 01:26:19.760
[Guest]: that an Indian would have to stand to get into Parliament, so be it. And Naoroji was in many

01:26:19.760 --> 01:26:25.600
[Guest]: ways the perfect candidate to try this venture because he had lived in Great Britain for such a

01:26:25.600 --> 01:26:30.640
[Guest]: long period of time. You know, he spoke English fluently, maybe because he was a Parsi, he might

01:26:30.640 --> 01:26:34.960
[Guest]: have looked a little bit more like Gora, he might have looked a little bit more fair than other

01:26:34.960 --> 01:26:41.040
[Guest]: Indians. So, you know, he probably had the best chance. And when he starts to campaign for

01:26:41.040 --> 01:26:44.720
[Guest]: Parliament, or at least starts to think about campaigning for Parliament, he says, you know,

01:26:44.720 --> 01:26:50.480
[Guest]: look, again, I've lived in this country in Great Britain for two or three decades off and on. I

01:26:50.480 --> 01:26:54.880
[Guest]: know many of the important political leaders here. I've talked to members of the Liberal Party. I've

01:26:54.880 --> 01:27:00.800
[Guest]: talked to members of the Conservative Party. And since India is a big political hot button issue,

01:27:02.000 --> 01:27:08.000
[Guest]: maybe there's a chance. Naoroji is not the first Indian to run, to stand for Parliament. That honour

01:27:08.000 --> 01:27:13.360
[Guest]: goes to a man called Lalmohan Ghosh. And I spent the first month of lockdown researching his

01:27:13.360 --> 01:27:19.840
[Guest]: activities for the next book I'm writing. And Ghosh comes very close to winning. It's quite

01:27:19.840 --> 01:27:26.640
[Guest]: remarkable. He stands in a place called Deptford, close by to Greenwich, and, you know, comes within,

01:27:26.640 --> 01:27:33.120
[Guest]: you know, a few dozen votes of winning, but ultimately doesn't win. So the door is already

01:27:33.120 --> 01:27:37.520
[Guest]: open a little bit. Okay, so, you know, there already are a few people who are starting to

01:27:37.520 --> 01:27:42.640
[Guest]: think about standing for Parliament. And the way that Naoroji thinks that he would have an even

01:27:42.640 --> 01:27:48.320
[Guest]: better chance of standing for Parliament is if he made his parliamentary campaign not just about

01:27:48.320 --> 01:27:53.120
[Guest]: India. If you're a Briton living in this era, your vote is not going to be swayed based on what you

01:27:53.120 --> 01:27:56.880
[Guest]: talk about India, right? I mean, most people have no clue about what's going on in India. They can

01:27:56.880 --> 01:28:04.320
[Guest]: maybe identify it on a map, maybe they can't. But if you link Indian political issues with issues

01:28:04.320 --> 01:28:09.760
[Guest]: that resonated with the average British individual, whether it was Irish Home Rule, the idea that

01:28:09.760 --> 01:28:14.720
[Guest]: Ireland should have some sort of autonomy from Great Britain at this point in time, whether you

01:28:14.720 --> 01:28:21.520
[Guest]: were talking about labor rights, the rights of people to unionize, the rights of women to vote,

01:28:21.520 --> 01:28:27.840
[Guest]: then you could catch their attention. And so Naoroji starts to do this during his first campaign,

01:28:27.840 --> 01:28:32.320
[Guest]: which takes place in 1886. I should mention that, you know, he had started to think about standing

01:28:32.320 --> 01:28:38.640
[Guest]: for Parliament many years beforehand, from at least 1877 onward. But it's only in 1886 that

01:28:38.640 --> 01:28:43.920
[Guest]: he really gets the first opportunity to stand. And the reason why he chooses that year is because

01:28:45.440 --> 01:28:51.040
[Guest]: parliamentary reform had just taken place in Great Britain. So Indians were very keenly observing how

01:28:51.040 --> 01:28:56.480
[Guest]: democratization was going on in Great Britain, and then using that democratization to their

01:28:56.480 --> 01:29:02.480
[Guest]: advantage. So in 1885, 1886, there had been these reform bills that had been passed, and

01:29:02.480 --> 01:29:09.520
[Guest]: automatically now, you know, maybe 25% of men had the right to vote. Maybe it was a little bit

01:29:10.160 --> 01:29:15.200
[Guest]: higher than that. I can't remember. But now more people have the right to vote, and you could be

01:29:15.760 --> 01:29:22.400
[Guest]: more popular in your attempts to woo the British voter. And so when he stood for Parliament for the

01:29:22.400 --> 01:29:27.600
[Guest]: first time from Holborn, close by to the British Museum, he doesn't just talk about India. He talks

01:29:27.600 --> 01:29:32.480
[Guest]: about the rights of Irishmen and Irish women. He talks about labor rights, things like, you know,

01:29:32.480 --> 01:29:38.000
[Guest]: eventually stuff like the eight-hour day. He talks to a limited degree about the right of women to

01:29:38.000 --> 01:29:42.880
[Guest]: vote. He talks about local municipal issues, problems with the London municipality,

01:29:44.560 --> 01:29:50.160
[Guest]: problems with transportation. So he's very clearly linking together India to a whole myriad of other

01:29:50.160 --> 01:29:54.880
[Guest]: issues that will capture the attention of the average British voter. And this gives him a bit

01:29:54.880 --> 01:29:59.840
[Guest]: more of a fighting chance. And eventually, again, he does lose in 1886. He loses by quite a large

01:29:59.840 --> 01:30:03.920
[Guest]: margin. But he doesn't lose as badly as many people thought that he would have.

01:30:05.360 --> 01:30:10.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I was kind of fascinated again by this period, because before this, you mentioned that

01:30:10.720 --> 01:30:14.800
[Amit Varma]: earlier there was this, you know, when he goes to Baroda, there is a suspicion that, oh, he's an

01:30:14.800 --> 01:30:19.520
[Amit Varma]: ivory tower guy, and he's going to Baroda. And what does he know? And what I find about his

01:30:19.520 --> 01:30:25.840
[Amit Varma]: England years, from your book, is that his political skills are remarkable, because

01:30:25.840 --> 01:30:31.280
[Amit Varma]: he realizes that India is not a cause, he is not a celebrity. You know, he knows a lot of people,

01:30:31.280 --> 01:30:36.480
[Amit Varma]: how does he get ahead? And he forges these three kinds of critical alliances. You know,

01:30:36.480 --> 01:30:43.200
[Amit Varma]: one, of course, with the Irish, where, you know, he adopts Irish home rule as, you know, one of his

01:30:43.200 --> 01:30:49.520
[Amit Varma]: pet causes. And you point out how, in fact, by the time the election comes around, he's asking

01:30:49.520 --> 01:30:56.160
[Amit Varma]: for electors' votes, quote, on behalf of the 5 millions in Ireland, and the 250 millions of India,

01:30:56.160 --> 01:31:01.520
[Amit Varma]: stop quote. And the other two sort of constituencies who he woos are, one is, of course,

01:31:01.520 --> 01:31:06.880
[Amit Varma]: the communists. And, you know, he gets more and more drawn to the communists. And of course,

01:31:06.880 --> 01:31:13.200
[Amit Varma]: and that obviously means a vote base of workers, and so on. And the third, interestingly, is women,

01:31:13.200 --> 01:31:18.800
[Amit Varma]: and women can't even vote at that time, right. But he figures that getting the women on his side

01:31:18.800 --> 01:31:25.760
[Amit Varma]: will have other knock on benefits, which indeed it does. So tell me a little bit about the sense

01:31:25.760 --> 01:31:30.720
[Amit Varma]: that we get, like, you know, there's another quote that kind of fascinated me is where he

01:31:30.720 --> 01:31:35.120
[Amit Varma]: gives a speech at Holborn, which you could quote from, where he says, during the first campaign,

01:31:35.120 --> 01:31:39.840
[Amit Varma]: which he loses, where he says, quote, I have lived in this country actually for 20 years.

01:31:39.840 --> 01:31:43.840
[Amit Varma]: And I say that if there is one thing more certain than another that I have learned,

01:31:43.840 --> 01:31:48.800
[Amit Varma]: it is that the English nation is incompatible with tyranny, stop quote. And of course,

01:31:48.800 --> 01:31:55.760
[Amit Varma]: he knows this is bullshit. I mean, you know, so yeah, but he says it because hey, it's a means to

01:31:55.760 --> 01:32:00.640
[Amit Varma]: an end. Now, my other deeper question, one is, I want to know a little bit more about your insights

01:32:00.640 --> 01:32:06.000
[Amit Varma]: about how he's thinking at this time and how he's doing these alliances. But the other sort of meta

01:32:06.000 --> 01:32:13.840
[Amit Varma]: question I have is that one of the things that has always struck me about politics is that politics

01:32:13.840 --> 01:32:18.320
[Amit Varma]: corrodes character, in the sense that you might begin out with a certain set of principles,

01:32:18.320 --> 01:32:24.000
[Amit Varma]: but then you compromise so much, so much, so much, so much that you yourself change as a result of

01:32:24.000 --> 01:32:29.200
[Amit Varma]: that. And those principles which you might have felt so deeply about don't matter anymore. Now,

01:32:29.200 --> 01:32:34.400
[Amit Varma]: it's very clear from this biography that that didn't happen to Nauroji, that he was passionate

01:32:34.400 --> 01:32:40.480
[Amit Varma]: about the cause right till the end. In fact, when he loses his last election at the start of the

01:32:40.480 --> 01:32:45.920
[Amit Varma]: century, it's almost pitiful his reaction to it because he cares so deeply about getting in there

01:32:45.920 --> 01:32:50.800
[Amit Varma]: and making change. So it doesn't really happen to him. But at the same time, it's like this is a

01:32:50.800 --> 01:32:58.080
[Amit Varma]: point where his public persona and his private persona seem so different, you know. So what's

01:32:58.080 --> 01:33:04.160
[Amit Varma]: kind of going on? And what is your sense of how can a person, you know, how is he remaining himself

01:33:04.160 --> 01:33:09.200
[Amit Varma]: through this period? It all seems so calculated. How can it not affect you? Like one of the things

01:33:09.200 --> 01:33:15.040
[Amit Varma]: that you do point out, and that does seem to be a genuine shift is his drift towards communism,

01:33:15.040 --> 01:33:19.920
[Amit Varma]: where in fact, in 1902, he attends a second international like you point out, and he becomes

01:33:19.920 --> 01:33:24.640
[Amit Varma]: more and more communist in his rhetoric as the years go by. And that seems to be a, you know,

01:33:24.640 --> 01:33:30.400
[Amit Varma]: a genuine shift, whereas he would not have held those views earlier necessarily. But, you know,

01:33:30.400 --> 01:33:35.600
[Amit Varma]: what is that whole kind of process like? Because the part that I'm sort of, I mean, I know the

01:33:35.600 --> 01:33:40.800
[Amit Varma]: question is a bit long winded, but what I'm fascinated by is not just the events that he's

01:33:40.800 --> 01:33:45.600
[Amit Varma]: so cannily putting together these alliances and saying whatever he needs to and dressing

01:33:45.600 --> 01:33:51.760
[Amit Varma]: differently for different occasions, as you also point out. But you know, what must be the turmoil

01:33:51.760 --> 01:33:56.640
[Amit Varma]: in his mind as he goes through all of these processes? Give me your sense of that.

01:33:57.280 --> 01:34:02.480
[Guest]: So I'll just mention at just at the outset, so he was definitely much more attracted to,

01:34:02.480 --> 01:34:07.760
[Guest]: he was definitely attracted to socialism, communism, not really, since communism as an

01:34:07.760 --> 01:34:12.880
[Guest]: idea was still evolving. And, you know, the ideas of Marx had not really trickled into,

01:34:12.880 --> 01:34:18.640
[Guest]: at least the Indian stream of politics as yet. So I mean, I think it's correct to say that he

01:34:18.640 --> 01:34:23.040
[Guest]: drifted towards socialism rather than towards communism. But you're right. I mean, you know,

01:34:23.040 --> 01:34:26.960
[Guest]: towards the end of his life, he was, you know, associating with these individuals who eventually

01:34:27.680 --> 01:34:32.080
[Guest]: will play a role in kind of leading the groundwork for kind of a global, you know,

01:34:32.080 --> 01:34:36.480
[Guest]: the growth of communism globally. Now, with regard to your question about, you know,

01:34:36.480 --> 01:34:42.960
[Guest]: what's motivating him at this point in time? You know, I think the really abiding passion of his

01:34:42.960 --> 01:34:50.800
[Guest]: life was this belief that so many people in India were being affected by poverty. Every year,

01:34:50.800 --> 01:34:56.800
[Guest]: you know, if it was a famine year, millions of people would lose their lives. And so he felt

01:34:56.800 --> 01:35:02.800
[Guest]: kind of a heartfelt commitment to do all that he could to try to change the situation. He knew that,

01:35:02.800 --> 01:35:07.360
[Guest]: you know, everything he did could potentially save, you know, people from this terrible fate.

01:35:07.360 --> 01:35:12.240
[Guest]: And, you know, his ultimate goal was to reach a point whereby the drain of wealth would be

01:35:12.240 --> 01:35:16.880
[Guest]: stopped and, you know, Indian impoverishment, the cycle of Indian impoverishment would be

01:35:16.880 --> 01:35:22.240
[Guest]: reversed. So I think that was kind of the burning fire in him. And that was the reason why he stayed

01:35:22.240 --> 01:35:29.040
[Guest]: so true to his core convictions. If you look at all of his close political comrades, they were all

01:35:29.040 --> 01:35:34.000
[Guest]: people who had this similar kind of inner fire and made sure that politics did not corrode that

01:35:35.600 --> 01:35:40.320
[Guest]: sense of, you know, pure principle. I mean, one of his good friends was Henry Hinman, who was the

01:35:40.320 --> 01:35:46.240
[Guest]: founder of the first British Socialist Party. And like Naoroji, Hinman grows more radical as he grows

01:35:46.240 --> 01:35:54.640
[Guest]: older. He grows far more radical than Naoroji, of course, in his socialist views. Another friend of

01:35:54.640 --> 01:36:00.800
[Guest]: his was Michael Davitt, who was an Irish home ruler who had gone to jail because of his activities and

01:36:00.800 --> 01:36:06.560
[Guest]: political views. He was someone who was committed towards pacifism. You know, he ultimately was not

01:36:06.560 --> 01:36:12.640
[Guest]: there for the political glory or, you know, money. He was there for principle, you know, fighting on

01:36:12.640 --> 01:36:19.120
[Guest]: behalf of his fellow Irishmen and Irishwomen. And so these people, you know, were ideologically

01:36:20.000 --> 01:36:26.720
[Guest]: motivated to such a degree to achieve some concrete end that I think they kind of, you know,

01:36:26.720 --> 01:36:32.000
[Guest]: immunize themselves from the corroding influences of politics. You can argue that Naoroji was not a

01:36:32.000 --> 01:36:38.560
[Guest]: very good politician in this sense. He did not compromise in many ways. He, as far as I can tell,

01:36:38.560 --> 01:36:44.000
[Guest]: was not corrupt. You know, he pursued a very honest and deliberate line in all his activities

01:36:44.000 --> 01:36:49.840
[Guest]: and that nearly cost him the election in 1892, which he won by five votes. But he very nearly

01:36:49.840 --> 01:36:56.000
[Guest]: lost it because he refused to give in to certain tactics that might have, you know, led to some

01:36:56.000 --> 01:37:00.480
[Guest]: sort of compromise that might have been politically remunerative, but ultimately would compromise

01:37:00.480 --> 01:37:06.160
[Guest]: his core beliefs and his principles. So in that sense, yeah, I mean, he wasn't necessarily a very

01:37:06.160 --> 01:37:10.400
[Guest]: good politician. But, you know, I think it's important to keep in mind that, you know, there

01:37:10.400 --> 01:37:16.960
[Guest]: were these people in this era, just as they are today, of course, who are so committed to, you

01:37:16.960 --> 01:37:23.040
[Guest]: know, doing good and achieving some concrete good that, you know, would have real consequences for

01:37:23.040 --> 01:37:28.080
[Amit Varma]: lives on the ground that kept them running. There are people like that in this era, you said?

01:37:28.080 --> 01:37:35.200
[Guest]: Perhaps a few. I know it's, you know, we live in such a cynical era, but I think there still

01:37:35.200 --> 01:37:40.320
[Amit Varma]: are a few people out there. Okay, I won't ask you for names in this particular

01:37:41.840 --> 01:37:45.840
[Amit Varma]: talking about Nauraj, you know, and also when you talk about his

01:37:46.480 --> 01:37:51.920
[Amit Varma]: obduracy, I'm struck by what happens during the second election, which he finally wins,

01:37:51.920 --> 01:37:57.440
[Amit Varma]: I think 2953 to 2948 or something like that by five votes, as you said. And what's interesting

01:37:57.440 --> 01:38:03.360
[Amit Varma]: there is that he gets the candidateship of the Liberal Party. And then there is this internal

01:38:04.000 --> 01:38:09.200
[Amit Varma]: rebellion and another Liberal candidate says, no, I'm the candidate. And there is for a couple of

01:38:09.200 --> 01:38:14.400
[Amit Varma]: years, tremendous pressure on him to back out of the race. But he is so bullheaded that he just

01:38:14.400 --> 01:38:20.240
[Amit Varma]: won't do it. And he hangs in there, and he somehow gets through and he faces a bunch of racism at

01:38:20.240 --> 01:38:25.520
[Amit Varma]: this time as well. And one of the reasons that you pointed out might have helped him win is that Lord

01:38:25.520 --> 01:38:33.200
[Amit Varma]: Salisbury referred to him as a black man. And this led to an outpouring of number one, sympathy across

01:38:33.200 --> 01:38:38.000
[Amit Varma]: England, because you know, they could see that this is clearly a bit too racist, and the racism

01:38:38.000 --> 01:38:46.240
[Amit Varma]: of it must have seemed starker, because he was essentially like a British liberal, well spoken,

01:38:46.240 --> 01:38:52.320
[Amit Varma]: sophisticated, all of that. And besides outrage, it also leads to a little bit of fact checking

01:38:52.320 --> 01:38:57.520
[Amit Varma]: when people point out that actually Lord Salisbury, who is quite swarthy, is actually darker than him.

01:38:58.160 --> 01:39:05.040
[Amit Varma]: And this whole process was kind of fascinating. Tell me about what happens when he finally wins.

01:39:05.040 --> 01:39:09.760
[Amit Varma]: Like one of the things that strikes me is that number one, when he's standing, it's not as if

01:39:09.760 --> 01:39:15.200
[Amit Varma]: he is standing as an individual. It's like he's standing for all of India. Across India, the

01:39:15.200 --> 01:39:19.360
[Amit Varma]: people are raising money for him and sending it to him. And it's saying he's India's guy,

01:39:19.360 --> 01:39:24.080
[Amit Varma]: you know. So it's almost as if this whole nation is at his back. And then when he finally wins,

01:39:24.080 --> 01:39:30.720
[Amit Varma]: you point out how when he comes to India, I think he goes to the Lahore Congress. And over there,

01:39:30.720 --> 01:39:36.720
[Amit Varma]: across the way, he does this railway trip, which is, you know, presages Gandhi's trip on the

01:39:36.720 --> 01:39:42.080
[Amit Varma]: railways and getting mobbed decades later, where you have these massive mobs everywhere coming to

01:39:42.080 --> 01:39:47.680
[Amit Varma]: see him. He, you know, he lands up at Lahore, and there are tens of thousands of people at the

01:39:47.680 --> 01:39:53.920
[Amit Varma]: railway station or whatever. And it's just mad. So on the one hand, he is a big hope of India. He

01:39:53.920 --> 01:39:58.240
[Amit Varma]: is their guy out there. It's almost like he's been elected President of India when he gets that seat

01:39:58.240 --> 01:40:03.760
[Amit Varma]: as an MP. And yet within the British Parliament, he has a really tough time. Tell me a bit about

01:40:03.760 --> 01:40:12.320
[Guest]: those years. So two things struck me at least about Naoroji's election. You know, his campaign,

01:40:12.320 --> 01:40:18.080
[Guest]: rather, I should say. The first thing was that his campaign took such a long time. I mean,

01:40:18.080 --> 01:40:24.800
[Guest]: he's nominated, as you say, and eventually there's a challenge that takes place. He's nominated in

01:40:24.800 --> 01:40:30.560
[Guest]: the year 1888, and the election doesn't take place until June of 1892. So you have basically

01:40:30.560 --> 01:40:36.320
[Guest]: a four-year-long campaign. And campaigns for Parliament in this era were in the span of days

01:40:36.320 --> 01:40:42.560
[Guest]: and weeks normally. And yet here's someone, you know, going in every day for the large part of

01:40:42.560 --> 01:40:47.440
[Guest]: four years and fighting internal rebellions that were, as you said, largely based on the question

01:40:47.440 --> 01:40:53.360
[Guest]: of race. There are two people who challenge him. And at least as far as I could tell from my

01:40:53.360 --> 01:40:58.800
[Guest]: research, those challenges are to a very large degree based on the fact that here was, you know,

01:40:58.800 --> 01:41:02.080
[Guest]: a foreigner, someone who looked different, someone who had a name that we can't pronounce,

01:41:02.080 --> 01:41:07.680
[Guest]: trying to represent us. And the irony of this was that he was standing in an area called Central

01:41:07.680 --> 01:41:14.000
[Guest]: Finsbury, which was then, and is still today, a very radical area. I mean, this is an area that

01:41:14.000 --> 01:41:20.240
[Guest]: still has, I think, a Lenin library. There was a statue of Lenin until recently over there. So it

01:41:20.240 --> 01:41:25.120
[Guest]: had this very long kind of radical political streak, and yet he's facing this terrible racism

01:41:26.560 --> 01:41:30.800
[Guest]: throughout his campaign. And it's so terrible that, you know, he nearly has to, you know,

01:41:30.800 --> 01:41:36.640
[Guest]: you know, he's encouraged to quit by many people, including many of his friends, to quit. And as

01:41:36.640 --> 01:41:39.840
[Guest]: you mentioned, you know, the prime minister at this point in time, Lord Salisbury, does kind of

01:41:39.840 --> 01:41:45.840
[Guest]: an indirect favor to him by calling him a Black man, which sets up a huge debate about racism in

01:41:45.840 --> 01:41:51.680
[Guest]: Great Britain. Was it acceptable to call, you know, an Indian a Black? What did that mean? And

01:41:51.680 --> 01:41:55.360
[Guest]: of course, there was this whole side debate, as you said, about who actually was darker. And,

01:41:55.360 --> 01:41:59.040
[Guest]: you know, that kind of reveals, I guess, a bit more about what racism was like in the Victorian

01:41:59.040 --> 01:42:03.840
[Guest]: era than, you know, what, you know, we'd like to think of it. So, you know, he becomes kind of a

01:42:03.840 --> 01:42:09.120
[Guest]: popular figure in this era, but that still doesn't help him. You know, he still faces challenges

01:42:09.120 --> 01:42:15.200
[Guest]: after that moment to his campaign. And as you mentioned, he wins by only five votes. He becomes

01:42:15.200 --> 01:42:21.120
[Guest]: dubbed the other by narrow majority. And that leads me to the second kind of really interesting

01:42:21.120 --> 01:42:24.720
[Guest]: thing for me, at least about this election. If you look at the total electoral figures,

01:42:24.720 --> 01:42:30.400
[Guest]: about 5,000 people are voting. This sounds kind of like, you know, a small college election,

01:42:30.400 --> 01:42:36.720
[Guest]: right? I mean, this is not what you think of as, you know, the exercise of democratic power in,

01:42:36.720 --> 01:42:43.680
[Guest]: you know, the beacon of democracy in this era. And that also shows you just how stunted democracy was

01:42:44.240 --> 01:42:49.920
[Guest]: in the supposedly democratic parts of the world in this moment. I mean, the franchise, the power

01:42:49.920 --> 01:42:57.600
[Guest]: to vote was only extended to those men in Great Britain who owned property and who, you know,

01:42:57.600 --> 01:43:02.880
[Guest]: could meet a certain, you know, threshold for earnings. And oftentimes the people who voted

01:43:02.880 --> 01:43:06.640
[Guest]: didn't even live in the particular district they were voting for. So, you know, you could be

01:43:06.640 --> 01:43:10.880
[Guest]: someone who lived, you know, in a completely different part of London, but because you

01:43:10.880 --> 01:43:15.680
[Guest]: owned property or you owned a store in central Finsbury, you had the right to vote. So it was

01:43:15.680 --> 01:43:21.600
[Guest]: a very weird and wacky system. And, you know, I learned far too much about Victorian politics and

01:43:21.600 --> 01:43:28.080
[Guest]: kind of the intricacies of how it worked in this era than I ever would have wanted to. But, you

01:43:28.080 --> 01:43:33.840
[Guest]: know, the long and short of it is, yes, at the end of it, Naoroji is elected. He's elected narrowly,

01:43:33.840 --> 01:43:39.920
[Guest]: but he's nevertheless elected. There's a brief recount effort that's put in place where, you

01:43:39.920 --> 01:43:43.680
[Guest]: know, the Conservative candidate tries to disqualify Naoroji by saying that several of the

01:43:43.680 --> 01:43:48.080
[Guest]: people who voted for him were immigrants, they were Italians or they were French, and how dare

01:43:48.080 --> 01:43:53.120
[Guest]: they had the right to vote. But citizenship laws in this era were so vague that, again, even someone

01:43:53.120 --> 01:43:58.000
[Guest]: like Naoroji had the right to vote in elections almost from the moment that he stepped on show

01:43:58.000 --> 01:44:02.160
[Guest]: in Great Britain, because there was no kind of like law of citizenship at this point in time.

01:44:02.800 --> 01:44:06.960
[Guest]: If you were there on the ground and you met your minimum qualifications for income and such,

01:44:06.960 --> 01:44:12.240
[Guest]: you had the right to vote. So getting to the second part of your question about how Naoroji

01:44:12.240 --> 01:44:17.680
[Guest]: is kind of conceptualized, yes, he is conceptualized as being the MP for India, the member for India.

01:44:18.240 --> 01:44:24.480
[Guest]: And it creates, you know, a moment of jubilation across the country. He is flooded with telegrams

01:44:24.480 --> 01:44:29.120
[Guest]: and letters from not just around the world, but all corners of India. I mean, when I was looking

01:44:29.120 --> 01:44:36.240
[Guest]: through Naoroji's papers, I found letters from Kashmir. I found letters from parts of, you know,

01:44:36.240 --> 01:44:43.600
[Guest]: Mysore province, you know, Chikmagalur, the place where coffee is grown, from village India,

01:44:43.600 --> 01:44:49.840
[Guest]: from urban India, from Indians living in Shanghai or Zanzibar or, you know, other parts of the

01:44:49.840 --> 01:44:56.160
[Guest]: diaspora, South Africa. So this really excites not just Indians in India, but Indians all across

01:44:56.160 --> 01:45:03.040
[Guest]: the world. And all Indians, whether they are, you know, an individual living in Chikmagalur or

01:45:03.040 --> 01:45:10.160
[Guest]: an elite in Bombay or, you know, an indentured worker in South Africa recognize Naoroji as being

01:45:10.160 --> 01:45:14.560
[Guest]: their representative. Finally, they have a voice, right? I mean, finally, there is an Indian

01:45:14.560 --> 01:45:21.120
[Guest]: in power who claims to speak for Indians. And consequently, for the next two to three years,

01:45:21.120 --> 01:45:25.680
[Guest]: when Naoroji is in parliament, he becomes these people's representatives. So he's dealing with

01:45:25.680 --> 01:45:31.440
[Guest]: everything from matters of high policy, you know, the civil service and the question of who is being

01:45:31.440 --> 01:45:38.080
[Guest]: appointed to what in the government of India, to the complaints of Indians living in the diaspora

01:45:38.080 --> 01:45:41.840
[Guest]: in Madagascar. I mean, up until this point in time, I didn't even know that there were many

01:45:41.840 --> 01:45:46.720
[Guest]: Indians in Madagascar, but I found a Gujarati letter from Indians in Madagascar complaining

01:45:46.720 --> 01:45:50.880
[Guest]: about their treatment. So, you know, it's fascinating. And you find letters, again,

01:45:50.880 --> 01:45:56.560
[Guest]: from Indians living in Guyana who are, you know, talking about their grievances and how Naoroji

01:45:56.560 --> 01:46:01.600
[Guest]: will hopefully be able to help them. So it's a moment of kind of unificatory patriotism,

01:46:02.160 --> 01:46:07.840
[Guest]: not just across India, but across the Indian diaspora at large. And it creates this huge

01:46:07.840 --> 01:46:13.520
[Guest]: moment of hope. And I think for Naoroji, it really feeds into this idea of, you know, that he's held

01:46:13.520 --> 01:46:19.120
[Guest]: so close to his heart throughout his life, British justice. You know, he's tried this hard, he's

01:46:19.120 --> 01:46:25.680
[Guest]: walked this hard, he's walked against the odds. And finally, after four terrible years of campaigning,

01:46:25.680 --> 01:46:32.720
[Guest]: he overcame, he succeeded. And now he would have a chance to make his point. Maybe there was a,

01:46:32.720 --> 01:46:38.000
[Guest]: you know, a glimmer of hope in this idea of British justice. And ultimately, it all comes

01:46:38.000 --> 01:46:43.920
[Guest]: crashing down. He loses election in 1895. And it's a moment of deep and dismal disappointment.

01:46:43.920 --> 01:46:48.000
[Guest]: It's probably the lowest moment in his political career. And we can go on and talk about that,

01:46:48.640 --> 01:46:54.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, later on. Yeah, no, before we get to that, I mean, a couple of strands, which I was

01:46:54.000 --> 01:46:58.720
[Amit Varma]: kind of fascinated by that, you know, what you're pointing out about India, you know, him being

01:46:58.720 --> 01:47:05.280
[Amit Varma]: treated as, you know, India's MP in Parliament, as India's man out there, is actually something

01:47:05.280 --> 01:47:09.680
[Amit Varma]: as you, you know, describe in your book, something that's been happening over the couple of decades

01:47:09.680 --> 01:47:16.800
[Amit Varma]: before this also, in the sense that he becomes this sort of figurehead of the Indian community

01:47:16.800 --> 01:47:21.520
[Amit Varma]: in London. So whenever parents are sending kids to study there, they'll send him a letter,

01:47:21.520 --> 01:47:26.160
[Amit Varma]: and they'll say, please make sure he doesn't marry a British girl. And, you know, even Gandhi

01:47:26.160 --> 01:47:32.800
[Amit Varma]: apparently is armed with a letter for Naoroji or, you know, your person X and person Y there with

01:47:32.800 --> 01:47:37.120
[Amit Varma]: the letter for Naoroji saying, listen, I don't know him, but it doesn't matter. He's Indian.

01:47:37.120 --> 01:47:42.640
[Amit Varma]: And he'll, you know, so he is the dude there who's already this massive community figurehead.

01:47:42.640 --> 01:47:47.840
[Amit Varma]: The other thing that struck me is how late in his life all of this is happening. You know,

01:47:47.840 --> 01:47:56.160
[Amit Varma]: he's 67 at the time he wins that election, you know, he's born in 1825, this is 1892, he's 67,

01:47:56.160 --> 01:48:00.880
[Amit Varma]: he's 70 at the time it's done, and he's not even nearly done, like his iconic Congress speech of

01:48:00.880 --> 01:48:06.480
[Amit Varma]: 1906 is when he's 81 years old. And we'll kind of come to that later, which is pretty mind blowing.

01:48:06.480 --> 01:48:12.720
[Amit Varma]: And just reading about his years in Parliament in your book was so impressive, because one,

01:48:12.720 --> 01:48:18.640
[Amit Varma]: you've described his schedule before that, where this is not the age of email. So he's like getting

01:48:18.640 --> 01:48:24.320
[Amit Varma]: up every day, he's devoting hours to writing letters by hand. He's meeting people constantly,

01:48:24.320 --> 01:48:29.600
[Amit Varma]: not just when he's in Parliament, but, you know, for years and years before that, he's giving

01:48:29.600 --> 01:48:34.560
[Amit Varma]: speeches, he's doing all of this. And in Parliament, you point out about how he finally gets

01:48:34.560 --> 01:48:39.280
[Amit Varma]: a victory that is not a victory, he gets a bill passed, which will allow Indians into the civil

01:48:39.280 --> 01:48:44.720
[Amit Varma]: service. But the cabinet, which is from his own party, the Liberal Party, then blocks it and

01:48:44.720 --> 01:48:50.160
[Amit Varma]: doesn't do anything with it. Tell me a bit about that sort of process and how it affected him,

01:48:50.160 --> 01:48:56.960
[Amit Varma]: because this is where that other transition happens in his life, where he shifts from being

01:48:56.960 --> 01:49:02.720
[Amit Varma]: a politician to an agitator. And this failure kind of radicalizes him. Tell me a little bit

01:49:02.720 --> 01:49:08.080
[Guest]: about what this process was like. Going to the first part of your question, at least,

01:49:08.080 --> 01:49:14.480
[Guest]: with regard to the Indian diaspora in Great Britain and what he was like to these students.

01:49:14.480 --> 01:49:18.640
[Guest]: You know, if I were to have written a standalone book on this process, you could almost, you could

01:49:18.640 --> 01:49:23.280
[Guest]: probably title it Indian Uncle. You know, he served as kind of the uncle for all of these

01:49:23.280 --> 01:49:31.120
[Guest]: people who came to Great Britain to study, to work, sightseeing, you know, everyone and anyone

01:49:31.120 --> 01:49:36.560
[Guest]: who is coming to Great Britain from India is asking him for help. And this was one of the

01:49:36.560 --> 01:49:41.280
[Guest]: fun things that I was able to do when I was in the archives, you know, since Naoroji kept

01:49:41.280 --> 01:49:46.880
[Guest]: everything. He was a pack rat. He was very pious in that sense. He kept everything. And I can

01:49:46.880 --> 01:49:52.400
[Guest]: sympathize being a pious thief. You read the letters that were written to him and they cover

01:49:52.400 --> 01:50:00.320
[Guest]: everything. So family disputes, you know, my son has sailed to London. He has not paid us

01:50:00.320 --> 01:50:06.400
[Guest]: remittances. What's going on? My husband has left us. He is somewhere in London. Can you help me?

01:50:06.400 --> 01:50:11.760
[Guest]: All the way down to the most mundane of things. Can you get me tickets to go see a session of

01:50:11.760 --> 01:50:17.040
[Guest]: Parliament? Can you arrange for me to meet the Queen? I mean, completely absurd things like that.

01:50:17.040 --> 01:50:22.560
[Guest]: You know, so everyone is asking him these questions. And most of the letters that I saw,

01:50:22.560 --> 01:50:26.400
[Guest]: there would be a small little note on top of them indicating the date he replied. So the

01:50:26.400 --> 01:50:31.040
[Guest]: incredible thing was, regardless of how absurd the question was, he still had the time. He still

01:50:31.040 --> 01:50:35.760
[Guest]: made the time to reply. It could have been a one line note saying, sorry, I can't help you meet

01:50:35.760 --> 01:50:40.960
[Guest]: the Queen. But in many cases, it was a detailed response saying, you know, I'm trying to get in

01:50:40.960 --> 01:50:45.360
[Guest]: touch with your long lost son and encouraging him to write to you. Or I'm trying to find your

01:50:45.360 --> 01:50:51.920
[Guest]: husband or, you know, your brother or your son passed away. I'm making arrangements for, you

01:50:51.920 --> 01:50:59.440
[Guest]: know, the funeral and, you know, money to be sent back home. So he was really involved in the nitty

01:50:59.440 --> 01:51:06.560
[Guest]: gritty of the lives of hundreds, if not thousands of Indians during his time in Great Britain. I

01:51:06.560 --> 01:51:11.360
[Guest]: mean, he really evolves as kind of this father figure or uncle, if you will, for the Indian

01:51:11.360 --> 01:51:16.320
[Guest]: community. And so as a consequence, you get a snapshot of what Indian life was like, all the

01:51:16.320 --> 01:51:22.960
[Guest]: troubles that people faced, their complaints about the weather, the food, British people and,

01:51:22.960 --> 01:51:27.040
[Guest]: you know, whether they were friendly or not friendly, and also the good things that they

01:51:27.040 --> 01:51:32.720
[Guest]: felt they experienced in British society, their friends, the fact that Britain was, you know,

01:51:32.720 --> 01:51:38.880
[Guest]: much more educated society that, you know, socially, it was much more liberal. So, you know,

01:51:38.880 --> 01:51:44.720
[Guest]: in that sense, Nehruji is important to us for understanding socially how the diaspora develops

01:51:44.720 --> 01:51:50.400
[Guest]: in a place like Great Britain. Now, with regard to his time in Parliament, and, you know, kind of

01:51:50.400 --> 01:51:56.240
[Guest]: the effect that it has on him. So as I said, yes, he begins in this moment of rosy optimism. And if

01:51:56.240 --> 01:52:01.120
[Guest]: you read the speeches he gives in Parliament during his first few years, they are very

01:52:01.120 --> 01:52:05.680
[Guest]: congratulatory towards British rule. You know, he says great things about what British rule has done.

01:52:06.240 --> 01:52:12.720
[Guest]: It's this force of progressivism. He's a loyal member of the Empire. And a very strong and

01:52:12.720 --> 01:52:19.920
[Guest]: distinct break takes place after he realizes that, you know, the goal of his time in Parliament,

01:52:19.920 --> 01:52:25.200
[Guest]: getting civil service reform would ultimately be thwarted. So as you said, you know, he succeeded

01:52:25.200 --> 01:52:30.240
[Guest]: in getting a non-binding resolution for civil service reform passed in Parliament. And he did

01:52:30.240 --> 01:52:35.600
[Guest]: this against great odds. He did this at a time when most parliamentarians were at home asleep,

01:52:35.600 --> 01:52:39.520
[Guest]: very late at night. There were only a few stragglers left in the House, but just enough,

01:52:39.520 --> 01:52:43.680
[Guest]: he made sure that there were just enough so that you would have a quorum and a vote could take

01:52:43.680 --> 01:52:48.880
[Guest]: place. And this was significant because it left Gladstone, the Prime Minister at the time,

01:52:48.880 --> 01:52:54.480
[Guest]: completely red-faced. His government was against it. It was the first defeat the government had

01:52:54.480 --> 01:53:01.920
[Guest]: faced, and it was a defeat by a fellow Liberal MP. So it's extremely embarrassing. But, you know,

01:53:01.920 --> 01:53:08.320
[Guest]: this was all part of Naroji's strategy. And when he goes back to India for the first time after

01:53:08.320 --> 01:53:13.600
[Guest]: being elected to Parliament, it's kind of like a victory lap. And he promises that now, you know,

01:53:13.600 --> 01:53:19.760
[Guest]: having passed this non-binding resolution, the British people and the Parliament would be

01:53:19.760 --> 01:53:24.960
[Guest]: honour-bound to, you know, commit themselves to this reform. And ultimately, that's not what

01:53:24.960 --> 01:53:29.920
[Guest]: happened. And when he realizes that this would not happen instantaneously, you see a tone,

01:53:30.800 --> 01:53:36.480
[Guest]: a change of tone. So he starts talking about the evils of British rule again. He starts comparing

01:53:36.480 --> 01:53:42.960
[Guest]: the fate of Indians to those of slaves in America. He says that Indians were actually probably worse

01:53:42.960 --> 01:53:47.360
[Guest]: off than slaves in America, because at least in America, there had been an incentive to keep

01:53:47.360 --> 01:53:51.840
[Guest]: those slaves alive. In India, there was no incentive, you know, and therefore millions

01:53:51.840 --> 01:53:56.800
[Guest]: of people died. So again, he becomes very bitter and very radical towards the end of his career.

01:53:57.360 --> 01:54:01.120
[Guest]: And worse than that, he realizes that not many people are listening. So ultimately,

01:54:01.120 --> 01:54:04.640
[Guest]: he would have thought that once you got to the stage of being an MP in Parliament,

01:54:04.640 --> 01:54:10.560
[Guest]: people would listen to you. But you had magazines like Punch making fun of Naroji, saying that he's,

01:54:10.560 --> 01:54:14.560
[Guest]: you know, giving this long speech and no one is listening and people are just making fun of him.

01:54:14.560 --> 01:54:20.160
[Guest]: So it's a moment of great despondency. And as you said, you know, he's 70 years old at this

01:54:20.160 --> 01:54:25.840
[Guest]: point in time, he could have thrown in the towel, retired back to India, given up and, you know,

01:54:25.840 --> 01:54:31.520
[Guest]: been a very bitter man but given up and he doubles down, if you will, he decides to become

01:54:31.520 --> 01:54:38.560
[Guest]: more radical. He decides to amplify his schedule. So he spends even more hours writing speeches or

01:54:38.560 --> 01:54:44.480
[Guest]: responding to people's letters, kind of haranguing colleagues to become more radical. And that

01:54:44.480 --> 01:54:49.520
[Guest]: sets up the last moment of his political career where he kind of embarks on this much more radical

01:54:49.520 --> 01:54:55.920
[Amit Varma]: phase of politics. Yeah, and that was almost kind of poignant that, and I guess it's a combination

01:54:55.920 --> 01:55:00.960
[Amit Varma]: of the two, but I was trying to figure out, was this radicalization because of the contingency

01:55:00.960 --> 01:55:06.480
[Amit Varma]: of his failure that he was just so frustrated that he lashed out and whatever or was he perhaps

01:55:06.480 --> 01:55:11.120
[Amit Varma]: expressing the radicalism he felt all along, because it was now no point in putting a veneer

01:55:11.120 --> 01:55:16.960
[Amit Varma]: on it that wasn't helping? Or was it that simply at this point in his intellectual journey,

01:55:16.960 --> 01:55:21.600
[Amit Varma]: he realized that these kind of moderate methods, petitioning and blah, blah, blah,

01:55:21.600 --> 01:55:26.960
[Amit Varma]: are not going to work and therefore you have to try something else. But I also found this poignant

01:55:26.960 --> 01:55:32.000
[Amit Varma]: because of course, he misses the 1900 elections because he's ill. And of course, he's, you know,

01:55:32.000 --> 01:55:38.560
[Amit Varma]: 75 at the time, but then he stands in the next elections, loses badly. And then it's so sad

01:55:38.560 --> 01:55:44.640
[Amit Varma]: because he writes to his Irish friends and almost begs him for a safe seat there. And, you know,

01:55:44.640 --> 01:55:49.360
[Amit Varma]: and he's turned down because there are internal squabbles happening there. And it's like he

01:55:49.360 --> 01:55:55.120
[Amit Varma]: realizes that this is my last chance, I have to get into parliament and do this, get this

01:55:55.120 --> 01:56:01.760
[Amit Varma]: resolution passed. And eventually, that's kind of not happening. And the really interesting thing is

01:56:01.760 --> 01:56:07.920
[Amit Varma]: you think at this point, he's done and dusted. But 1906, when he's 81 years old, is still almost a

01:56:07.920 --> 01:56:12.320
[Amit Varma]: seminal moment for the Congress Party, because the extremists are fighting with the moderates.

01:56:12.320 --> 01:56:16.400
[Amit Varma]: And as a way of stopping Tilak, like you point out, you know, Tilak is being intransigent and

01:56:16.400 --> 01:56:20.880
[Amit Varma]: wants to be president of the Congress. And as a way of stopping that, they call in Naoroji. And

01:56:20.880 --> 01:56:24.880
[Amit Varma]: even though the moderates think he's too extremist, and the extremists think he's too moderate, like

01:56:24.880 --> 01:56:31.520
[Amit Varma]: you say, he's in, they all agree to him and he goes out there and he gives a speech, which he

01:56:31.520 --> 01:56:38.880
[Amit Varma]: makes his compadre Gokhale readout, which is also an interesting tactic. Tell me a little bit about

01:56:38.880 --> 01:56:44.240
[Amit Varma]: that. And why is it so seminal? Why is it such a remarkable moment in Indian politics, what

01:56:44.240 --> 01:56:51.520
[Guest]: Naoroji now says? So going back as to why Naoroji radicalized at this moment, I mean, I think it's a

01:56:51.520 --> 01:56:56.080
[Guest]: little bit of the various reasons that you mentioned, you know, so at one point, he realized

01:56:56.080 --> 01:57:00.720
[Guest]: that now that he wasn't in the in parliament, and he wasn't immediately standing for parliament,

01:57:00.720 --> 01:57:05.360
[Guest]: he could afford to be more radical. You know, he first talks about self-government for India

01:57:05.360 --> 01:57:12.160
[Guest]: publicly in the year 1884. And then in the year 1885, all references to self-government disappear.

01:57:12.880 --> 01:57:16.720
[Guest]: And that's because this is, you know, when he starts to talk about standing for parliament,

01:57:16.720 --> 01:57:20.720
[Guest]: and if you want to stand for parliament in Great Britain, talking about getting self-government

01:57:20.720 --> 01:57:24.800
[Guest]: from Britain is probably not your most effective strategy. So he stops talking about it. And it's

01:57:24.800 --> 01:57:32.000
[Amit Varma]: only... And also, no one's taken screenshots on Twitter. So it's okay. Exactly. Yeah, this is a

01:57:32.000 --> 01:57:37.440
[Guest]: much easier moment, I guess, for, you know, people's former statements to, you know, kind of

01:57:37.440 --> 01:57:42.800
[Guest]: pass by and not be commented upon. So he doesn't talk about self-government, even though it's there

01:57:42.800 --> 01:57:46.720
[Guest]: in the back of his mind. And if you look at his private correspondence, he's still talking about

01:57:46.720 --> 01:57:53.360
[Guest]: it with people like Alan Octavian Hume. And after 1895, well, the gloves are off, right? I mean,

01:57:53.360 --> 01:57:57.600
[Guest]: you can start to talk about more radical views. And so he starts to talk again about kind of the

01:57:57.600 --> 01:58:04.240
[Guest]: evil nature of British rule, a foreign government being, you know, terrible for India. He starts to

01:58:04.240 --> 01:58:08.480
[Guest]: talk about the possibility of a second mutiny, because people were just so sick and tired

01:58:08.480 --> 01:58:13.120
[Guest]: of, you know, the terrible effects of imperial rule. And ultimately, he starts talking again

01:58:13.120 --> 01:58:17.040
[Guest]: about self-government. And he makes this public, even though he's standing for parliament at the

01:58:17.040 --> 01:58:23.760
[Guest]: same time. So now, you know, he just doesn't care that that contradiction might be there.

01:58:23.760 --> 01:58:28.000
[Guest]: And I think one reason for why he's able to let this slide is because he realizes,

01:58:28.720 --> 01:58:32.960
[Guest]: you know, the fact of mortality staring at him in the face. As you said, he's, you know,

01:58:32.960 --> 01:58:40.960
[Guest]: in his 70s when he, you know, when he loses his re-election bid in parliament and in his early

01:58:40.960 --> 01:58:46.240
[Guest]: 70s when he's kind of radicalizing. And he realizes that these are his last chances to

01:58:46.240 --> 01:58:51.440
[Guest]: kind of make effective change. He struggled all these decades on behalf of ameliorating

01:58:51.440 --> 01:58:56.400
[Guest]: the condition of India. And during this period of time, again, it's, you know,

01:58:56.400 --> 01:59:01.040
[Guest]: the terrible things happening in India. The government in power is more reactionary and

01:59:01.040 --> 01:59:05.760
[Guest]: conservative. There's the plague epidemic in Western India, coupled with a famine.

01:59:06.400 --> 01:59:11.760
[Guest]: So the news coming out of India is awful, absolutely terrible. And if you read letters

01:59:11.760 --> 01:59:16.800
[Guest]: written by people like Gokhale or Beramji Malbari, you know, they're heartbreaking.

01:59:16.800 --> 01:59:21.280
[Guest]: You know, when I read them in the archives some 120 years after they were written,

01:59:21.280 --> 01:59:27.120
[Guest]: you're really struck by just how awful things were. You know, people's relatives dying from

01:59:27.120 --> 01:59:34.000
[Guest]: plague, famine camps being set up all around the country, people leaving Bombay in masks to escape

01:59:34.880 --> 01:59:38.480
[Guest]: the plague, and this very kind of draconian effort on part of the British government to

01:59:38.480 --> 01:59:43.600
[Guest]: kind of crack down on health and sanitation in order to, you know, alleviate the plague.

01:59:43.600 --> 01:59:47.440
[Guest]: It was an awful moment. And so I think Naoroji felt all this more keenly,

01:59:47.440 --> 01:59:53.440
[Guest]: because everything that he had struggled for seemed to be at stake. So, you know,

01:59:53.440 --> 02:00:00.000
[Guest]: a part of it was trying to stand for parliament again, making a last ditch effort to be elected.

02:00:00.000 --> 02:00:06.000
[Guest]: And as you mentioned, in 1900, he can't stand for parliament because he's too sick. His doctor

02:00:06.000 --> 02:00:10.240
[Guest]: actually tells him if you stand for parliament, there's a good chance you will die because,

02:00:10.240 --> 02:00:17.600
[Guest]: you know, your respiratory problems that you're having could lead to, you know,

02:00:17.600 --> 02:00:22.080
[Guest]: influenza and could lead to other diseases that, you know, could cause you to die. I mean,

02:00:22.080 --> 02:00:28.240
[Guest]: you're 75 years old at this point in time. He tries again in 1905, 1906, when he's 80 years old,

02:00:28.880 --> 02:00:34.320
[Guest]: and people around him are asking him, good God, what are you doing? Why are you, a man of 80,

02:00:34.320 --> 02:00:42.560
[Guest]: trying to get into parliament? And, you know, he still has that fitness of, you know, of being

02:00:42.560 --> 02:00:48.960
[Guest]: to give multiple speeches a day, to address multiple crowds, to write letters. Maybe it's

02:00:48.960 --> 02:00:55.120
[Guest]: his diet of raw eggs. I don't know. I mean, maybe that keeps him ticking. Who knows? But, you know,

02:00:55.120 --> 02:01:01.040
[Guest]: he still has the energy of someone who is 20 years younger. And that kind of propels him in this more

02:01:01.040 --> 02:01:05.920
[Guest]: radical direction. He knows that time is not on his side, yet he still has the energy, he still

02:01:05.920 --> 02:01:12.880
[Guest]: has the drive, and he still knows that whatever he's doing, you know, has a chance to help save

02:01:12.880 --> 02:01:17.760
[Guest]: people in his country from even worse poverty and famine and, you know, the plague epidemic.

02:01:17.760 --> 02:01:23.440
[Guest]: So there's still that drive. And ultimately, you know, all of that collapses after his

02:01:23.440 --> 02:01:29.360
[Guest]: Congress speech in 1906. His health gives way. And, you know, all of a sudden, this man of 81

02:01:29.360 --> 02:01:34.560
[Guest]: years of age, who had been acting like a man of 50 or something, now is in his 80s. I mean,

02:01:34.560 --> 02:01:39.840
[Guest]: he just cannot go any longer. But it sustains him long enough to do what he needs to do,

02:01:39.840 --> 02:01:46.000
[Guest]: which is, again, give that speech to the Congress in 1906, where he really kind of helps tilt the

02:01:46.000 --> 02:01:51.120
[Guest]: balance in favor of the extremists. You know, as you said, both the moderates and the extremists

02:01:51.120 --> 02:01:56.000
[Guest]: kind of saw Naoroji as a compromise candidate. He kind of fell in between two stools in the sense

02:01:56.000 --> 02:02:01.280
[Guest]: that he was too moderate for the extremists, but too radical for the moderates. And the moderates

02:02:01.280 --> 02:02:07.920
[Guest]: really hope that he ultimately will help them preserve their basis of power in the Congress

02:02:07.920 --> 02:02:13.440
[Guest]: through his leadership at the Congress. And the few eyewitness reports that we have of what people

02:02:13.440 --> 02:02:19.040
[Guest]: like, say, Gokhale or Mehta or, you know, others like Surendranath Banerjee and such are thinking

02:02:19.040 --> 02:02:25.200
[Guest]: after the Congress is a certain feeling of being crestfallen. They felt that Naoroji has really

02:02:25.200 --> 02:02:30.720
[Guest]: passed on the baton to the extremists. And we know that Tilak, after the Congress speech

02:02:31.440 --> 02:02:37.120
[Guest]: that Naoroji gives, has taken place. You know, again, he criticizes Naoroji's moderacy,

02:02:37.120 --> 02:02:41.920
[Guest]: but he also says, look, you know, he has agreed with us, us being the extremists,

02:02:41.920 --> 02:02:45.920
[Guest]: that Swaraj is the way to go for it. We can disagree with him about methods,

02:02:46.720 --> 02:02:51.440
[Guest]: but he ultimately agrees with us for the end. So the means are different that we have,

02:02:51.440 --> 02:02:56.480
[Guest]: but the ultimate end of Swaraj, and not necessarily Swaraj under British rule,

02:02:57.360 --> 02:03:01.520
[Guest]: Naoroji is on the same page with us. And even, you know, fierce critics like Dipenchandra Pal

02:03:02.320 --> 02:03:08.560
[Guest]: ultimately realize this as well, that Naoroji has done us more good than bad through his Congress

02:03:08.560 --> 02:03:13.200
[Amit Varma]: speech of 1906. You know, the wording of the speech is fascinating in the sense that before

02:03:13.200 --> 02:03:18.080
[Amit Varma]: this, as you point out, he's always, one, he uses the term Swaraj, which is Tilak's term and,

02:03:18.080 --> 02:03:22.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, very deliberately. And the other thing that you point out is that before he has always

02:03:22.640 --> 02:03:27.760
[Amit Varma]: spoken to self-rule in the sense of, you know, like the dominions like Australia or Canada or

02:03:27.760 --> 02:03:32.080
[Amit Varma]: whatever, which are still part of the British Empire. But now he says like Australia or Canada

02:03:32.080 --> 02:03:37.520
[Amit Varma]: or the UK, which means, you know, completely independent. And he doesn't need to spell it out.

02:03:37.520 --> 02:03:43.520
[Amit Varma]: Just saying like the UK, as you point out, is, you know, a big seminal moment. And, you know,

02:03:43.520 --> 02:03:48.320
[Amit Varma]: you can imagine why, you know, you've spoken in your book about how Feroz Shah Mehta was so upset

02:03:48.320 --> 02:03:55.360
[Amit Varma]: and crestfallen and all of that. And one can sort of totally imagine. And this shift happens and he

02:03:55.360 --> 02:04:00.960
[Amit Varma]: lives till 92. He dies in 1917. He shows traces of activity in that time, but he doesn't really,

02:04:00.960 --> 02:04:06.480
[Amit Varma]: he's not really too active after this. Gandhi comes to India and meets him, all of that happens.

02:04:06.480 --> 02:04:11.520
[Amit Varma]: You know, one of the things which you mentioned you couldn't do much about during the book,

02:04:11.520 --> 02:04:15.600
[Amit Varma]: because there isn't much written on it is, of course, his personal life. He got married at

02:04:15.600 --> 02:04:20.000
[Amit Varma]: the age of 11 when his wife was seven, of course, which is the kind of classic child marriage thing

02:04:20.000 --> 02:04:26.480
[Amit Varma]: that you have then. He had kids with her, many, many grandchildren, all of that. You know,

02:04:26.480 --> 02:04:31.760
[Amit Varma]: you gave us a sense of his grief when his son Ardashir dies at the age of 35 and all of that.

02:04:31.760 --> 02:04:37.120
[Amit Varma]: And one gets a sense of him as a father, even that moment when his daughter writes to him and

02:04:37.120 --> 02:04:41.040
[Amit Varma]: says, please come to India for my wedding. And he writes back saying, no, no, the nation is

02:04:41.040 --> 02:04:46.000
[Amit Varma]: important. You want me to give this up? So, I got a kind of a sense of those conflicts,

02:04:46.000 --> 02:04:50.080
[Amit Varma]: but there's no mention of his wife anywhere. And obviously, as a biographer, you're looking for

02:04:50.080 --> 02:04:53.440
[Amit Varma]: that. So, how do you sort of deal with that? Do you feel like there's something incomplete there?

02:04:54.080 --> 02:04:59.280
[Guest]: Absolutely. That was the most frustrating aspect of my research. So, as you mentioned,

02:04:59.280 --> 02:05:04.960
[Guest]: Naoroji was married when he was 11 and his wife was, I believe, seven. And they ultimately were

02:05:04.960 --> 02:05:13.200
[Guest]: married for 70 years. And his wife apparently was not literate. She apparently had limited interest

02:05:13.200 --> 02:05:18.640
[Guest]: in learning. At least this is what we know from R.P. Massani's biography that he wrote in 1939.

02:05:19.600 --> 02:05:24.640
[Guest]: Massani knew the Naoroji family, so he would have known family stories and such. There's no way for

02:05:24.640 --> 02:05:29.680
[Guest]: me to verify this because there's just no material. So, when I looked through the Naoroji papers,

02:05:29.680 --> 02:05:35.600
[Guest]: there was a collection of family correspondence, but there were no letters from Naoroji's wife. She

02:05:35.600 --> 02:05:39.920
[Guest]: didn't write or she wasn't able to write. And his wife only comes up every once in a while

02:05:39.920 --> 02:05:44.640
[Guest]: in correspondence. I mean, this was extremely striking for me because, you know, here's a man

02:05:44.640 --> 02:05:49.200
[Guest]: who talks a lot about feminism, right? I mean, he's consorting with some of the leading feminists

02:05:49.200 --> 02:05:55.120
[Guest]: in the world, you know, throughout his political career. He's talked about female education and

02:05:55.120 --> 02:06:01.840
[Guest]: he's acted upon it and yet his own wife is such a distant and remote character for the biographer to

02:06:01.840 --> 02:06:07.440
[Guest]: understand. I mean, you know, a friend of mine, a very good friend of mine found a picture of her

02:06:07.440 --> 02:06:12.800
[Guest]: after having dug through a bunch of old and dusty newspapers in Baroda. And I was shocked to find

02:06:12.800 --> 02:06:17.600
[Guest]: this picture because I'd never seen it before. I mean, there are just no descriptions of her

02:06:18.160 --> 02:06:22.960
[Guest]: throughout his correspondence. So, you know, I would have loved to have written much more about

02:06:22.960 --> 02:06:27.760
[Guest]: his family. But ultimately, you know, two things constricted me. One was, of course, word limit,

02:06:27.760 --> 02:06:32.000
[Guest]: you know, there's only so much you could write about it. And the second was there just wasn't

02:06:32.000 --> 02:06:38.080
[Guest]: that much material about his wife and many of his other children. We know a lot more about his

02:06:38.080 --> 02:06:44.000
[Guest]: grandchildren. In fact, you know, still to this day, I get emails from people every once in a

02:06:44.000 --> 02:06:47.920
[Guest]: while who said, you know, they knew his grandchildren or, you know, they were related

02:06:47.920 --> 02:06:51.840
[Guest]: to him. So I'm still kind of piecing together a few, you know, pictures of stories of his

02:06:51.840 --> 02:06:58.800
[Guest]: grandchildren. So what I can tell you definitely is that even though his marital relationship,

02:06:58.800 --> 02:07:03.440
[Guest]: we don't know much about, and it doesn't seem like, you know, it was, you know, a marriage of

02:07:03.440 --> 02:07:09.040
[Guest]: equals in many way. And, you know, on that ground, we can criticize Naroji for, you know, perhaps

02:07:09.040 --> 02:07:12.480
[Guest]: not, you know, spending more time with his wife or not making more of an effort to kind of

02:07:12.480 --> 02:07:18.960
[Guest]: integrate him into his, you know, his social world. But we do know that amongst his granddaughters,

02:07:18.960 --> 02:07:24.560
[Guest]: he was extremely supportive of their ambitions, you know, with what they did. And, you know,

02:07:24.560 --> 02:07:28.720
[Guest]: his granddaughters included people like the Captain Sisters, who are important players in

02:07:28.720 --> 02:07:35.120
[Guest]: the nationalist movement under Gandhi. They were, you know, radical extremists who worked with

02:07:35.120 --> 02:07:40.400
[Guest]: Madam Kama and even with Savarkar, and then ultimately gave this up in favor of Gandhi's

02:07:40.400 --> 02:07:47.920
[Guest]: political following. My favorite character from his generation of grandchildren was a person

02:07:47.920 --> 02:07:54.640
[Guest]: called Khurshid Ben Naroji, and I've written an essay separately on her. She was Naroji's

02:07:54.640 --> 02:08:02.960
[Guest]: youngest granddaughter through his son. So his son, as you mentioned, Adi, passed away in 1893.

02:08:02.960 --> 02:08:10.400
[Guest]: And Khurshid Ben was born after the son passed away, so born posthumously.

02:08:11.680 --> 02:08:16.560
[Guest]: And she was trained as a classical singer. She was trained in French, and she goes and studies

02:08:16.560 --> 02:08:22.080
[Guest]: in Paris, and eventually even spends a bit of time in Greece, where she meets a very important

02:08:22.080 --> 02:08:28.560
[Guest]: figure involved in reviving the Delphic games in Greece in the early 20th century.

02:08:29.120 --> 02:08:35.680
[Guest]: And she comes back to India, and she gives all of this up in order to join Gandhi, and not just

02:08:35.680 --> 02:08:40.480
[Guest]: join Gandhi in terms of, you know, temperance activities and walking in Sabarmati Ashram and

02:08:40.480 --> 02:08:46.160
[Guest]: such. She does a completely amazing and courageous thing by deciding in the 1930s to go out to the

02:08:46.160 --> 02:08:53.200
[Guest]: northwest frontier province and preach nonviolence to Dacoits. So she learns Pashto, and she goes

02:08:53.200 --> 02:08:58.240
[Guest]: around to camps of Dacoits. And imagine this, you know, petite, Anglicized, Parsi woman who was a

02:08:58.240 --> 02:09:03.280
[Guest]: classical singer living in Paris up until recently. Her house is on Napier and Sea Road in

02:09:03.280 --> 02:09:08.560
[Guest]: Bombay, and now she's traipsing through Waziristan, talking to Dacoits and saying, please, you know,

02:09:08.560 --> 02:09:13.120
[Guest]: stop kidnapping Hindus, you know, in order to restore Hindu-Muslim unity. Instead, why don't

02:09:13.120 --> 02:09:19.360
[Guest]: you weave Khadar and, you know, learn about Gandhi. It's a completely ballsy thing that she's doing.

02:09:19.360 --> 02:09:24.720
[Guest]: She, at several points in time, is probably nearly killed. I mean, she writes to Gandhi about

02:09:24.720 --> 02:09:30.560
[Guest]: bullets whizzing by her in the desert. They're pretty remarkable letters. So, you know,

02:09:31.360 --> 02:09:35.920
[Guest]: all of this is kind of, you know, comes from a political spirit that Naoroji helps inculcate

02:09:36.480 --> 02:09:41.040
[Guest]: in his children and grandchildren. So, you know, his family legacy, even though it might not have

02:09:41.040 --> 02:09:45.520
[Guest]: been very well reflected in his relationship with his wife, it's reflected in the political

02:09:45.520 --> 02:09:51.600
[Amit Varma]: activities of his children and grandchildren. This is so fascinating. I can totally see this as a

02:09:51.600 --> 02:09:58.480
[Amit Varma]: grand Bollywood film. So, you know, I've taken a lot of your time, two kind of final lines of

02:09:58.480 --> 02:10:04.320
[Amit Varma]: inquiry. One is, you know, towards the end of his life, one, he himself becomes very embittered with

02:10:04.320 --> 02:10:09.680
[Amit Varma]: his failure in Parliament or what he sees as his failure in Parliament and so on. And, you know,

02:10:09.680 --> 02:10:14.480
[Amit Varma]: you point out how one of his constant enemies in London, Shyamji Krishnavarma, who I promise

02:10:14.480 --> 02:10:20.880
[Amit Varma]: was no relative of mine, Shyamji Krishnavarma then sort of criticizes him and calls him a

02:10:20.880 --> 02:10:25.680
[Amit Varma]: grand failure and says that he's achieved nothing through all these years. And, you know, when I

02:10:25.680 --> 02:10:31.040
[Amit Varma]: kind of, for me, this, you know, looking at that period of Indian history always seems to me really

02:10:31.040 --> 02:10:36.720
[Amit Varma]: weird because everything seems coherent till the second decade of the 20th century. You have the

02:10:36.720 --> 02:10:40.880
[Amit Varma]: moderates who are doing their petitioning, who are trying to work with government. You have the

02:10:40.880 --> 02:10:45.360
[Amit Varma]: extremists on the other hand, who are gradually moving apart and all narratives are coherent.

02:10:45.360 --> 02:10:49.600
[Amit Varma]: And then up comes this black swan event called Gandhi and he turns everything around. And it's

02:10:49.600 --> 02:10:54.960
[Amit Varma]: like nothing that happened before that was even required or made any sense or whatever. So, on

02:10:54.960 --> 02:10:59.280
[Amit Varma]: the one hand, because, you know, that's also the decade when Gokhale dies, Feroz Shah Mehta dies,

02:11:00.080 --> 02:11:04.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, and of course, Naoroji dies, but he's already so old anyway, he's

02:11:04.640 --> 02:11:09.760
[Amit Varma]: basically out of it. So, the moderates are out. But then again, it's a completely different stand,

02:11:09.760 --> 02:11:14.400
[Amit Varma]: which is nothing, which is no continuity, which seems to have no continuity with what came before.

02:11:14.400 --> 02:11:19.120
[Amit Varma]: So, one, looking back at his legacy and the fact that, yes, you know, on the surface of it,

02:11:19.120 --> 02:11:24.720
[Amit Varma]: it seems like he didn't get much done. So, was he a failure? Did he have a legacy beyond that?

02:11:24.720 --> 02:11:29.680
[Amit Varma]: And perhaps, is that legacy his failure in a sense? Because, you know, Gandhi at one point,

02:11:29.680 --> 02:11:35.280
[Amit Varma]: you point out how Gandhi is telling one of his colleagues in South Africa around 1909 or 1910,

02:11:35.280 --> 02:11:40.560
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, we must not give up because look at Dada bhai, he's been at it for 40 years.

02:11:40.560 --> 02:11:46.160
[Amit Varma]: And if you look at all of, for example, you know, one thing people don't realize when we think about

02:11:46.160 --> 02:11:51.440
[Amit Varma]: Gandhi, such a mythological figure is that all of Gandhi's Satyagrahas basically failed,

02:11:51.440 --> 02:11:56.160
[Amit Varma]: including the ones in South Africa. But he just, you know, the last was sort of a half-hearted,

02:11:56.160 --> 02:12:02.400
[Amit Varma]: face-saving semi-success. But Gandhi essentially kept failing, kept failing, kept failing, but he

02:12:02.400 --> 02:12:08.000
[Amit Varma]: kept at it and then at some point that turned. So, is that Naoroji's legacy or is there a legacy

02:12:08.000 --> 02:12:15.200
[Amit Varma]: beyond the failure of it? How do we, you know, when we now look back at him, besides the mythology

02:12:15.200 --> 02:12:22.160
[Amit Varma]: of Grand Old Man of India or the Indian uncle, as you point out, what do we see? Is it a frustratingly

02:12:22.160 --> 02:12:27.120
[Amit Varma]: wasted life, you know, lived with the best intention, but going nowhere or, you know,

02:12:27.120 --> 02:12:31.600
[Amit Varma]: is it easy to say that in hindsight and did he actually move the needle in ways that are not

02:12:32.160 --> 02:12:37.360
[Guest]: so visible today? That's an excellent question because these are questions that I'm trying to

02:12:37.360 --> 02:12:43.840
[Guest]: wrestle with in my next book. Oftentimes, both from our perspective and from the perspective

02:12:43.840 --> 02:12:50.240
[Guest]: of someone in, say, the 1930s or the 1940s, you could look upon moderate nationalism,

02:12:50.240 --> 02:12:54.160
[Guest]: this kind of early phase of nationalism, as being a bit of a failure. What did they do,

02:12:54.160 --> 02:12:59.440
[Guest]: right? I mean, the Congress was this small party that was relatively elite and city-based.

02:12:59.440 --> 02:13:04.320
[Guest]: What reforms were really, you know, wrested from the British government? And ultimately,

02:13:04.320 --> 02:13:08.400
[Guest]: only when Gandhi comes to the scene do you really have a mass-based movement where there is

02:13:09.200 --> 02:13:15.200
[Guest]: significant, you know, change on the ground. Now, the thing about this is that even people like

02:13:15.200 --> 02:13:20.960
[Guest]: Gandhi realized how wrong that perspective was. Gandhi acknowledged himself. He did not come out

02:13:20.960 --> 02:13:25.280
[Guest]: of any, you know, he didn't come out of nowhere, right? I mean, he came out of the particular

02:13:25.280 --> 02:13:30.240
[Guest]: heritage that India had accumulated in terms of its nationalist history and its political trajectory.

02:13:30.880 --> 02:13:37.920
[Guest]: And, you know, there's a passage in Hind Swaraj where Gandhi defends Naoroji by saying, you know,

02:13:37.920 --> 02:13:43.440
[Guest]: we stand on the shoulders of our, you know, those who come before us, you know, that whole metaphor,

02:13:43.440 --> 02:13:47.200
[Guest]: right? You can see farther because of what people have done beforehand. And he says,

02:13:47.200 --> 02:13:52.800
[Guest]: Naoroji was the person who really kind of laid the foundations. And I think that's what Naoroji's

02:13:52.800 --> 02:13:57.440
[Guest]: greatest legacy was. I mean, it was easy for people like Shyamji Krishnavarma to call him

02:13:57.440 --> 02:14:02.400
[Guest]: a failure because, you know, ultimately he did not achieve civil service reform, right? He did

02:14:02.400 --> 02:14:07.520
[Guest]: not stop the drain of wealth. I mean, India was poorer and more fab and written in the year 1900

02:14:07.520 --> 02:14:12.720
[Guest]: than it had been when Naoroji started his political career in the 1860s. And Swaraj, of course,

02:14:12.720 --> 02:14:17.840
[Guest]: was a very distant goal. So, you know, on those three particular goals, of course, Naoroji failed

02:14:20.320 --> 02:14:26.240
[Guest]: in order to achieve those things. But ultimately he laid the organizational and the philosophical

02:14:26.240 --> 02:14:32.160
[Guest]: and kind of political economic foundations upon which Indian nationalism eventually did achieve

02:14:32.160 --> 02:14:38.320
[Guest]: success. I mean, when we think of any aspect of Indian nationalism, whether it was the organization

02:14:38.320 --> 02:14:43.840
[Guest]: in terms of the Indian National Congress, whether it was the particular message about how poverty

02:14:43.840 --> 02:14:50.080
[Guest]: was the kind of the central feature of why British rule was so bad for India, whether it was the

02:14:50.080 --> 02:14:54.400
[Guest]: international aspects of Indian nationalism. I mean, this is something which I'm trying to

02:14:54.400 --> 02:14:59.760
[Guest]: talk more about in my next book, about how people like Naoroji did not make Indian nationalism just

02:14:59.760 --> 02:15:04.240
[Guest]: about India. It was about much more than just India. It was a much more global campaign for

02:15:04.240 --> 02:15:11.360
[Guest]: emancipation. Any of these aspects had Naoroji at the very core. Naoroji was the people who laid

02:15:11.360 --> 02:15:16.480
[Guest]: the groundwork for many of these aspects of Indian nationalism. He wasn't alone. I mean,

02:15:16.480 --> 02:15:21.520
[Guest]: many other people were part and parcel of this process, but he was at the very center of all

02:15:21.520 --> 02:15:28.480
[Guest]: these various networks. So it's really impossible to understand Indian nationalism without Naoroji.

02:15:28.480 --> 02:15:37.040
[Guest]: Because if you were adopting Gandhi's or Tilak's methods in the 1860s through pretty much the 1880s

02:15:37.040 --> 02:15:42.320
[Guest]: and 1890s, you would have been cut off. There was no way the British government would have

02:15:42.320 --> 02:15:48.880
[Guest]: countenanced your activities. And Gokhale himself recognized this in regards to Alan Octavian Hume.

02:15:48.880 --> 02:15:56.000
[Guest]: When Hume dies in 1912, Gokhale delivers this eulogy for Hume saying, no one else could have

02:15:56.000 --> 02:16:01.760
[Guest]: founded the Congress. It had to have been a British ex-official founding the Congress because

02:16:01.760 --> 02:16:06.640
[Guest]: otherwise it would have been shut down. The government would have shut it down and dissolved

02:16:06.640 --> 02:16:13.360
[Guest]: the Congress. And indeed, you know, the viceroys in power, Lansdowne and Dufferin, nearly did shut

02:16:13.360 --> 02:16:17.760
[Guest]: down the Congress. I mean, if you read their correspondence, they're this close to even,

02:16:17.760 --> 02:16:23.120
[Guest]: you know, charging someone like Hume, a fellow British person, a fellow member of the civil

02:16:23.120 --> 02:16:28.480
[Guest]: service with sedition and treason. So you can only imagine what, you know, they would have done to

02:16:28.480 --> 02:16:34.480
[Guest]: Naoroji or Gokhale and what they did eventually do to Tilak by, you know, acting out on these

02:16:34.480 --> 02:16:39.440
[Guest]: threats. I mean, there would have been no question of the, you know, the velvet glove being off and

02:16:39.440 --> 02:16:44.720
[Guest]: the, you know, the metal fist of imperialism quashing and crushing these individuals.

02:16:45.440 --> 02:16:50.160
[Guest]: So in that regard, it's impossible to really think of us, think of Naoroji as being a failure.

02:16:50.160 --> 02:16:54.160
[Guest]: They did as much as they could do under the circumstances. In fact, they went beyond it

02:16:54.160 --> 02:17:00.160
[Guest]: in many ways. And, you know, they prepared the ground for a later generation when it was much

02:17:00.160 --> 02:17:08.240
[Guest]: easier to kind of go against the grain of British imperialism. And finally, I'll, you know, I'll

02:17:08.240 --> 02:17:13.360
[Amit Varma]: leave it to readers to read your book and to kind of discover Dadabhai Naoroji's fascinating life

02:17:13.360 --> 02:17:17.600
[Amit Varma]: for themselves. But I'll shift back to the personal now. You know, biographers sometimes

02:17:17.600 --> 02:17:22.640
[Amit Varma]: say that by the time they finish a biography, they feel bereaved when it's over. It's like a sense of

02:17:22.640 --> 02:17:27.360
[Amit Varma]: loss because you get so attached to the person that you're writing about. Has it kind of been

02:17:27.360 --> 02:17:32.640
[Amit Varma]: like that for you, especially as there'll be a lot of, I'm guessing, cultural echoes because,

02:17:32.640 --> 02:17:38.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, you're also Parsi, you're in Bombay right now, you know, there would be sort of echoes

02:17:38.160 --> 02:17:44.640
[Amit Varma]: of that also. So, you know, what was the relationship between you and Naoroji through

02:17:44.640 --> 02:17:51.360
[Amit Varma]: this book? You know, how did it feel when it was over and in what ways did it sort of enrich

02:17:51.360 --> 02:17:56.960
[Guest]: your thinking, as it were? I heard your conversation with Saman Subramaniam and I

02:17:56.960 --> 02:18:03.040
[Guest]: remember he mentioned that feeling towards Haldane. Curiously, I have not felt it. It's

02:18:03.040 --> 02:18:08.240
[Guest]: odd. I mean, I remember when I did my undergraduate thesis, it wasn't even a biographical

02:18:08.240 --> 02:18:14.240
[Guest]: project. It was on the construction of the city of Delhi. I felt a tremendous amount of just kind of

02:18:14.240 --> 02:18:18.720
[Guest]: meaningless after it was turned in. It was almost like depression, you know, after you turned it in

02:18:18.720 --> 02:18:24.400
[Guest]: and what do I do now? And I haven't had that feeling with Naoroji probably because he's not

02:18:24.400 --> 02:18:30.480
[Guest]: done for me. You know, I have, I'm sitting on thousands of his letters that I eventually want

02:18:30.480 --> 02:18:38.880
[Guest]: to publish. So, you know, there still is more work that I want to incorporate him into. And secondly,

02:18:38.880 --> 02:18:45.200
[Guest]: the next book that I'm working on currently, you know, which has been thrown a little bit

02:18:45.200 --> 02:18:50.320
[Guest]: asunder because of the whole pandemic, is on early Indian nationalism in general. And again,

02:18:50.320 --> 02:18:55.680
[Guest]: kind of trying to show about why it was relevant, not just in its era, but in our era. I mean, why

02:18:55.680 --> 02:19:00.800
[Guest]: the, you know, the principles and ideas that they fought for and enunciated are as valid today as

02:19:00.800 --> 02:19:05.680
[Guest]: they were back then. And Naoroji, of course, has a big part to play in it. I'm looking at

02:19:05.680 --> 02:19:11.040
[Guest]: other figures, I mean, like Lal Mohan Ghosh or Hume or eventually people like Ranade or

02:19:12.000 --> 02:19:16.320
[Guest]: Feroz Shah Mehta, but Naoroji is always there. I mean, his correspondence figures

02:19:17.200 --> 02:19:21.920
[Guest]: there, his ideas are important, and he's always hovering in the background. So,

02:19:22.480 --> 02:19:28.560
[Guest]: strangely, I haven't felt that feeling of mourning as yet. You know, he'll be an important part of

02:19:28.560 --> 02:19:33.600
[Guest]: my life, whether I like it or not, you know, for many years to come. I can't wait to read

02:19:33.600 --> 02:19:38.080
[Amit Varma]: your next book, because that period of history also kind of fascinates me. You know, I went to

02:19:38.080 --> 02:19:43.280
[Amit Varma]: college in Ferguson College, Pune, and it was only years after I had graduated and left that

02:19:43.280 --> 02:19:47.600
[Amit Varma]: I realized what a rich history it has in terms of so many of the moderate leaders of that era,

02:19:47.600 --> 02:19:52.080
[Amit Varma]: in fact, being there. And one of my favorite stories is, you know, Gopal Ganesh Agarkar,

02:19:52.080 --> 02:19:57.360
[Amit Varma]: who sadly died too young. He was once teaching, I think, a biology class at Ferguson College.

02:19:57.360 --> 02:20:03.920
[Amit Varma]: And he asked him the question that, if donkeys had a gourd, what would the gourd look like?

02:20:03.920 --> 02:20:08.240
[Amit Varma]: And then, I don't know how I'll do this in a podcast, but he basically held both his hands

02:20:08.240 --> 02:20:13.760
[Amit Varma]: above his ears, you know, to imitate donkey ears. And that is such a fantastic thing. And you say

02:20:13.760 --> 02:20:18.400
[Amit Varma]: that those leaders can have lessons for today. I don't think Agarkar could have gotten away with

02:20:18.400 --> 02:20:24.640
[Amit Varma]: it today for all you know. But, Dinyar, it's just been so amazing talking to you. Thanks so much for

02:20:24.640 --> 02:20:28.480
[Guest]: your time and insights. Thank you very much, Amit. It's been a pleasure to be on this program.

